<FIRST>r a AM-Senators-CentralAmerica     04-25 0440</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Senators-Central America,0452</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senators: U.S. Cannot `Wimp Out' on Panama</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD COLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States cannot ``wimp out'' on fraud in
Panama's upcoming presidential vote and still maintain credibility
in Central America, four U.S. senators said Monday after touring
the region.
   U.S. Sens. Bob Graham, D-Fla., John McCain, R-Ariz., Charles
Robb, D-Va., and Connie Mack, R-Fla., hopscotched through Central
America over the weekend, visiting with U.S. and local officials.
   The scheduled May 7 election in Panama, which the senators said
is widely expected to be stacked in favor of Gen. Manuel Antonio
Noriega's candidate, is a test of U.S. attitudes toward next year's
Nicaraguan elections.
   ``We cannot allow to go unchallenged what is obviously a
massively fraudulent election in Panama,'' said McCain.
   The senators called Panama a test in U.S. sincerity, saying the
nation's actions will be used to judge attitudes toward next
February's elections in Nicaragua, which pit a leftist Sandinista
government against the U.S.-backed Contra rebels.
   ``If we wimp out in Panama, and passively let a fraudulent
election go forward ... I think our moral standing within Nicaragua
and our credibility to the world community will be seriously
compromised,'' Graham said.
   Graham and Mack said the United States must immediately focus
world attention on Panama, persuading as many foreign observers as
possible to oversee the vote even though Noriega has sought to ban
such activities.
   ``One of the things we have failed to do is to bring
international pressure with respect to Panama,'' Mack said.
   Graham said reports that President Bush had approved aid to the
Panamanian opposition were understandable, because the United
States has legitimate economic and military interests in the
nation, especially the Panama Canal.
   But he said he was puzzled by the $10 million amount reported.
   ``I was surpised, because the people with whom we met indicated
they were expecting to spend approximately $1 million on the
oppsoition campaign, and they had already raised a substantial
amount of that,'' the senator said. ``I was unclear where the
figure $10 million came from.''
   In Nicaragua, the senators said, Sandinista foreign ministry
official Victor Tinoco met with the senators to discuss next year's
scheduled election in that country.
   But Tinoco refused to answer the senators when they asked
point-blank if the Sandinistas would peacefully transfer power to
the winners of the February 1990 election, Graham said.
   In a visit to the Yamales Contra camp in Honduras, Graham said,
he found the rebels in high spirits. He said they would prefer to
be fighting, but understood their role in pressuring the
Sandinistas to comply with their commitment to democratize
Nicaragua.
</TEXT>
