<FIRST>r a PM-People-LucilleBall     04-25 0475</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-People-Lucille Ball,0488</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lucille Ball Improving, Daughter Says Hairdo Utmost Post-Surgery
Worry</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB THOMAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Comedian Lucille Ball's first words
to her daughter after last week's emergency heart surgery was about
her hairdresser's appointment, actress Lucie Arnaz says.
   ``I went to mom's bedside where she was all tied to tubes and
things and I told her, `Hello mom, I love you,''' Miss Arnaz told
150 people Monday at the Beverly Hills Hotel for the Eastman Kodak
Second Century Award ceremony.
   ``She mumbled something under the oxygen mask, but I said I
couldn't hear her. Finally I asked the nurse if I could lift the
mask a little to hear what she was saying. So I did, and mom said,
`Wouldn't you know _ this is the day I was going to get my hair
done.'''
   Miss Ball was honored for her work in helping young people in
the entertainment field. Miss Arnaz accepted the award on her
mother's behalf.
   The 77-year-old actress was in serious condition and improving
daily, said Ron Wise of Cedars-Sinai Medical Center.
   ``The outlook is very encouraging,'' he said. ``Her doctors have
her in the chair for longer periods each day. Her spirits are good
and she's cracking jokes.''
   She was moved Monday from the cardiac surgical intensive care
unit to a step-down unit, ``technically another intensive care
unit,'' said Wise. ``She should be in her own room toward the end
of the week.
   At the luncheon, Miss Arnaz said she was glad the award wasn't
postponed after her mother's heart attack ``because it means very,
very much to her at this time.''
   Presenting the award, comedian Carol Burnett told of being
visited by Miss Ball on the second night of her New York show,
``Once Upon a Mattress.''
   ``She came backstage to visit us all and she spent 30 to 35
minutes in my dressing room answering my questions,'' Miss Burnett
said.
   Miss Ball's husband, Gary Morton, also attended the luncheon,
where guests signed a huge card with the ``I Love Lucy'' heart logo
and the words, ``We Love Lucy _ Get Well Soon.''
   Wise said the mounds of get-well wishes arriving at the hospital
represents the biggest outpouring of affection for any celebrity
confined to Cedars-Sinai, known as the ``hospital to the stars.''
   ``We've received a tidal wave of mail with a couple thousand
letters coming in today,'' said Wise. ``It's taken four volunteers
several hours to sort it. She wants everything sorted so she can
see every one of them when she gets home.''
   Inside a package addressed to Miss Ball, Wise said, ``You can
hear `Twinkle, Twinkle Little Star' playing on a music box inside.''
   The surgery was performed April 18 when doctors replaced her
aorta and aortic valve with the donated organ tissue of a
27-year-old man.
</TEXT>
