<FILEID>AP-NR-04-25-89 0101EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-APMeeting     04-25 0790</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-AP Meeting,0815</SECOND>
<HEAD>Expanding AP Service Offers New Products, Faster Delivery Within
A Year</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM LITKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Associated Press will introduce three new
services for readers this year to help meet the changing needs of
the news industry, AP President and General Manager Louis D.
Boccardi said.
   ``I want to reaffirm something that I think you know is true, at
least I hope you know is true,'' Boccardi told news executives at
the AP annual meeting Monday. ``That is that I want quality service
and responsiveness to be the twin themes of everything the AP
does.''
   Earlier Monday, President Bush and Vice President Dan Quayle
both addressed the annual meeting and luncheon, highlighting the
start of the 103rd annual convention of the American Newspaper
Publishers Association.
   Bush, reporting on his first 100 days in office, listed among
his accomplishments savings and loan legislation, ethics proposals,
the beginning of a war on drugs and agreements with Congress on the
federal budget and Contra aid.
   ``In three short months we've made a good start coming to grips
with issues demanding urgent attention and decisive action,'' he
said.
   At the same time, defense and foreign policy reviews,
environmental legislation and a program to deal with homelessness
``are all on the near horizon,'' Bush added.
   He also suggested his relationship with the media had matured
after a sometimes-rocky presidential campaign.
   ``Both of us, government and the news media, need one another
and we owe each other a measure of respect, honesty and integrity
equal to the work we're engaged in,'' Bush said.
   The president also pledged continued administration efforts to
win the release of Terry Anderson, AP chief Middle East
corrrespondent, who last month began his fifth year as a hostage in
Lebanon.
   Hours before departing on a trip along the Pacific rim, Quayle
addressed his remarks to the ``declinists'' both at home and abroad
who have predicted a diminished standing for the United States as a
global power.
   ``The point that I will stress to my Asian hosts is that when
Americans express doubts about the health of American society, it's
usually a sign of renewal, not of decline,'' he said.
   Boccardi, who followed Bush at the luncheon, told the AP annual
meeting that improving technology was quickly changing the business
of reporting and delivering news, and that the pace would only
accelerate.
   As an example, he noted that this year the AP was able for the
first time to deliver a presidential inauguration picture in time
for East Coast afternoon newspapers, by using direct transmission
from a digital camera onto the AP photo network.
   He said the news products to be introduced later this year are
aimed at different sections of the newspaper _ new state weather
maps, a sports statistic page and a regular story package aimed at
readers over age 50.
   The state weather maps would compliment national and regional
maps already provided. The AP also will supply a national weather
map in color via its GraphicsNet system of computer-to-computer
transmission.
   The full-page layout of sports agate, complete with graphic
labels and headlines, would be transmitted over the AP's
GraphicsNet system and updated throughout the day.
   The biweekly package of stories and columns aimed at Americans
age 50 and over, dealing with such subjects as retirement planning,
health and legislation affecting the elderly. An added staff member
will be assigned to this package, called ``Prime Time.''
   In his ``report card'' to the members, Boccardi also said the AP
this year will complete the conversion to a 9,000-word-a-minute
high-speed transmission system for DataStream and DataFeature news
copy, after a delay caused by a worldwide shortage of advanced
computer memory chips.
   He also said a new highspeed photo service, PhotoStream, will be
running on a test-basis by mid-year.
   The AP's annual report noted that 72 more daily newspapers
joined the news cooperative in 1988, bringing total membership at
the end of 1988 to 1,483 dailies, representing 95 percent of daily
U.S. newspaper circulation.
   The meeting agenda also included election of seven members of
the AP's 21-member board of directors, including three new members.
All members were elected to three-year terms.
   The new board members are:
   William M. Boyd Jr. of the Central New Jersey Home News of New
Brunswick; William R. Burleigh, senior vice president-newspapers
and publishing, Scripps Howard; and John G. Montgomery of The Daily
Union of Junction City, Kan.
   Four incumbent directors were re-elected:
   David R. Bradley Jr. of the News-Press@Gazette of St. Joseph,
Mo., Frank A. Daniels Jr. of the Raleigh (N.C.) News &amp; Observer and
Times, William J. Keating, chief executive officer, Detroit
Newspaper Agency, and Harold R. Lifvendahl of The Orlando (Fla.)
Sentinel. Keating is chairman of the board.
</TEXT>
