<FIRST>r a PM-APBoardElection     04-25 0399</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-AP Board Election,0420</SECOND>
<HEAD>Boyd, Burleigh And Montgomery Elected To AP Board Of Directors</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   William M. Boyd Jr., William R. Burleigh and John
G. Montgomery have been elected to the board of directors of The
Associated Press. Four incumbent directors were re-elected.
   David R. Bradley Jr. of the News-Press@Gazette of St. Joseph,
Mo., Frank A. Daniels Jr. of the Raleigh (N.C.) News &amp; Observer and
Times, William J. Keating, chief executive officer, Detroit
Newspaper Agency, and Harold R. Lifvendahl of The Orlando (Fla.)
Sentinel were elected to new three-year terms on the AP board.
Keating is chairman of the board.
   Directors were elected from among 12 nominees at the AP annual
meeting on Monday.
   Burleigh and Montgomery were chosen to succeed retiring
directors Howard H (Tim) Hays Jr. of The Press-Enterprise of
Riverside, Calif., and John M. Jones of The Greeneville (Tenn.)
Sun. Hays and Jones were not eligible for re-election because they
have served the maximum three consecutive three-year terms on the
board.
   Burleigh is senior vice president for newspapers and publishing,
Scripps Howard.
   Boyd is chairman of the board, president and publisher of Home
News Publishing Company, New Brunswick, N.J.
   Montgomery is president and publisher of Montgomery
Publications, Inc., Junction City, Kan.
   Boyd was elected to fill the vacancy created by the resignation
from the board of Katherine W. Fanning, who resigned as editor of
The Christian Science Monitor last year. Her term on the board
expires in 1991.
   The AP membership earlier Monday approved a resolution that was
passed in February by the executive committee of the board of
directors authorizing the sixth-place vote-getter - excluding the
separate voting for a director representing a city of less than
50,000 population - to fill her unexpired term
   The voting for directors was based on membership bonds held by
the newspapers that make up the cooperative news agency.
   The results:
   Keating, 14,145 bond votes.
   Daniels, 13,644.
   Bradley, 12,379.
   Lifvendahl, 12,117.
   Burleigh, 10,570.
   Boyd, 7,959.
   F. Al Totter, the San Gabriel Valley Tribune, Covina, Calif.,
6,133.
   Walter E. Bartlett, The Greenville (S.C.) News, 5,152.
   Richard L. Connor, Fort Worth (Texas) Star-Telegram, 3,428.
   Paul J. O'Brien, the Salt Lake Tribune, 2,065.
   Montgomery was elected to the board to represent a city of under
50,000 population. In that separate contest, he received 12,377
votes.
   Ted M. Natt of The Daily News of Longview, Wash., had 8,054
votes.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
