<FIRST>r i PM-Cambodia-Vietnam     04-25 0707</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Cambodia-Vietnam,0728</SECOND>
<HEAD>Withdrawal Could Improve International Climate For Vietnam ^Eds:
Also in Tuesday AMs report.</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER ENG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHNOM PENH, Cambodia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When it withdraws from Cambodia,
Vietnam will be at peace for the first time since its war for
independence began half a century ago against the French, Japanese
and eventually the Americans.
   Reformers now in control hope ending nearly 11 years of
occupation will bring better relations with the outside world,
including the United States. They believe Vietnam risks economic
disaster without expanded trade and assistance from abroad.
   Orders for Vietnam's invasion of neighboring Cambodia in
December 1978 came from founders of the Communist Party made
inflexible by the long struggle. Several have resigned or died
since, and the reformers pledge to withdraw the remaining
occupation forces by Sept. 30.
   Vietnam says 50,000 of its soldiers remain in Cambodia, but
foreign intelligence estimates put the number as high as 70,000.
   A new and bloodier round of civil war between the
Hanoi-sponsored Cambodian government and the three-party guerrilla
groups opposing it may begin after the withdrawal, but the
departure will be a boon to Vietnam.
   Its occupation, aided by the Soviet Union, angered nations on
which Vietnamese trade and economic development depend, such as the
United States, China and members of the Association of Southeast
Asian Nations: Thailand, Malaysia, Indonesia, the Philippines,
Singapore and Brunei.
   Vietnam's invasion overthrew the brutal Khmer Rouge regime,
which was allied with China, and the Chinese army made a punitive
strike into Vietnam early in 1979. Because of sanctions and its
isolation, Vietnam soon found itself in worse shape economically
than the devastated country it had occupied.
   Ngo Dien, Vietnamese ambassador to Cambodia, says relations with
Thailand and the United States have improved and trade along the
China-Vietnam frontier has resumed. ``After the withdrawal, we will
see even more changes,'' he added.
   Washington says it will not consider aid or diplomatic relations
until Vietnamese military forces leave Cambodia, but Hanoi's pledge
and its efforts to account for Americans still missing from the
Vietnam war have caused more U.S. congressmen to recommend quicker
reconciliation.
   Thailand talks of turning Indochina's ``battlefields into
markets.''
   As a condition for a return to normal relations with the Soviet
Union, China has demanded that Moscow force Vietnam to leave
Cambodia. Mikhail S. Gorbachev and Deng Xiaoping, leaders of the
two countries, are to meet next month in Beijing for the
Chinese-Soviet summit in 30 years.
   Asked whether Vietnam made its decision under Soviet pressure,
Ngo Dien said: ``Mr. Gorbachev of course welcomed the withdrawal
because he has something in his hands for the summit.''
   ``Some people may call it pressure. Some people may call it good
coordination between close friends who have the same aim.''
   Improving relations with Vietnam might enable the non-communist
world to wean it from dependence on the Soviet Union and encourage
the limited steps Hanoi has taken toward a more open, freer society.
   For three centuries, Cambodia has found itself shrinking with
Vietnam's steady territorial expansion.
   Communist-led Vietnamese guerrillas used Cambodian and Laotian
territory as sanctuaries and supply routes for the war against the
French and the Americans, and helped communist movements to victory
in the two countries.
   Since economic reformer Nguyen Van Linh became party chief in
late 1986, however, Hanoi has taken steps to get out of Cambodia
and has withdrawn troops from Laos.
   A Soviet diplomat based in Phnom Penh said privately that some
Vietnamese ``saw themselves as the rulers of this country, but
luckily the others got the upper hand.''
   Uch Kiman, head of the Foreign Ministry's political department
in the government installed by Vietnam, suggested greater
independence for Cambodia will accompany the end of occupation.
   ``For the moment, I think we have to stick together because of
the political configuration in the region, but I think in the
future we don't want to wall ourselves in,'' he said.
   ``We certainly want to expand our relations to all neighboring
countries, especially the ASEAN countries.''
   According to the Soviet diplomat, ``Vietnam's influence will
remain'' after withdrawal, ``but it will not be monopolistic.''
   Ngo Dien suggested Vietnam would stop using military means to
resolve problems and would fix its attention on economic
development.
</TEXT>
