<FIRST>r a AM-EngineFails     04-25 0170</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Engine Fails,0175</SECOND>
<HEAD>Midway Plane Returns To Airport As Flames Shoot From Engine</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A DC-9 jet carrying 55 passengers was forced to
turn around minutes after takeoff when the pilot discovered flames
shooting from an engine.
   The Midway Airlines twin-engine jet landed safely at Midway
Airport on the city's southwest side with no injuries, said Sandra
Allen, spokeswoman for the airline. The plane had departed for
Kansas City at 8 p.m. and returned to Midway eight minutes later.
   Ms. Allen said a compressor, which mixes air and fuel, failed
and the fuel ignited as it was discharged out of the rear of the
engine.
   She compared it to a car backfiring _ ``a big backfire from a
big engine.''
   ``I'm sure the passengers heard a loud bang and the pilot
noticed a loss of power in the engine,'' Ms. Allen said
   Emergency vehicles were summoned as the plane returned using
only one engine.
   Ms. Allen said the passengers were assigned to other flights to
Kansas City.
</TEXT>
