<FILEID>AP-NR-04-25-89 0155EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-CharterRevision     04-25 0435</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Charter Revision,0447</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chairman Wants to Eliminate New York's Board of Estimate, Expand
Council</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER ALAN HARPER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The head of a commission appointed to rework the
city's unconstitutional government proposed eliminating the
powerful Board of Estimate on Monday and expanding the City Council
to 50 members.
   The mayor would take control of contracts _ a lightning rod in
view of the city corruption scandals surrounding Board of
Estimate-awarded contracts that have resulted in criminal
convictions. However, various bodies would have oversight
responsibilities.
   Mayor Edward I. Koch and City Comptroller Harrison Goldin were
generally pleased by the proposals made by Frederick A.O. Schwarz
Jr., chairman of the Charter Revision Commission.
   The five borough presidents who sit on the Board of Estimate
opposed them, however, with Howard Golden of Brooklyn saying
Schwarz ``is telling the boroughs to drop dead.''
   At a public hearing, Schwarz also put forth the idea of a
bicameral legislature, but not as a formal proposal. He said a new,
19-member house would be the equal of the City Council, but that it
would only work if it gave greater representation to blacks and
Hispanics.
   The commission was created by the mayor to look into ways city
government could restructure itself as court challenges to the
Board of Estimate made their way through the legal system.
   In March, the U.S. Supreme Court ruled that the board was
unconstitutional because it violated the one-person, one-vote
doctrine by giving each borough equal weight even though they
varied widely in population.
   The commission, which had been on hold pending the court's
ruling, then went into high gear with a self-imposed mandate to get
its proposals on the November ballot.
   The chairman's proposals are the first formal agenda around
which the 15-member commission can debate. Schwarz presented part
of the proposals Monday for discussion with the rest to be reviewed
by the commission Tuesday. His proposals are not final.
   Under his proposals, the powers of the Board of Estimate, made
up of the borough presidents, the mayor, the city council president
and the comptroller, would be dispersed.
   The comptroller no longer would be involved in policy and would
be limited to fiscal matters and oversight and audit functions on
contracts.
   ``I think it is a useful focus for reconstituting the city
government,'' Comptroller Goldin said. ``The comptroller's role has
always been overwhelmingly fiscal. This recognizes that reality.''
   The City Council would expand from 35 to 50 members, with the
districts to correspond as closely as possible to community board
districts. The city council president would continue as an
ombudsman.
</TEXT>
