<HEAD>`Pet Sematary' Buries Box Office Competition With $12 Million Take</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOLLYWOOD (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Paramount Studios was a big winner at the box
office last weekend with its ``Pet Sematary'' and ``Major League''
earning a combined $17.2 million in ticket sales.
   Based on a premise that sometimes dead is better, ``Pet
Sematary'' sold $12 million to win the top spot in its first
weekend. ``Major League'' was second at $5.2 million, according to
Exhibitor Relations Co.
   In third and fourth place were ``Say Anything'' and ``The Dream
Team.''
   The Oscar-winning film ``Rain Man'' clung to the No. 5 position
after 19 weeks in release, followed by ``She's Out of Control'' in
sixth and newcomer ``Red Scorpion'' with Dolph Lundgren in seventh.
   ``See You in the Morning'' with Jeff Bridges and Farrah Fawcett
debuted in the No. 8 position with $1.8 million. In ninth was
``Disorganized Crime.'' ``Speed Zone'' was tenth.
   Here are the top movies for the weekend as tallied by Exhibitor
Relations, with distributor, weekend gross, number of theater
screens, average per screen, total gross and number of weeks in
release.
