<FIRST>r i PM-Israel-PressCards     04-25 0544</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Israel-Press Cards,0558</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police To Investigate Palestinian Press Cards</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police Minister Chaim Bar-Lev says he has
ordered an investigation into press cards Palestinians are issuing
foreign journalists for the occupied lands, where Israeli police
have posed as reporters.
   Many foreign reporters have acquired such cards since a scandal
last month involving two police officers who were filmed using a
``Press'' sign on their vehicle during a raid against Arab rioters
in east Jerusalem.
   Police later imposed limitations on the practice, but did not
rule it out altogether, saying it was a legitimate decoy method in
dealing with the 16-month Palestinian uprising.
   In addition, Jewish settlers living in the occupied lands have
sometimes used ``Press'' signs to pass unharmed through Palestinian
roadblocks where stone-throwers hurl rocks at cars with the yellow
Israeli license plates.
   Palestinians have alleged that Israeli secret service agents
were also presenting themselves as journalists. Masked Palestinian
activists have often stopped reporters to check their credentials.
   Bar-Lev said on Israel radio Monday that police would look into
the Palestinian-issued press cards.
   ``Those issuing these cards are an organization in Jerusalem,''
he said. ``We will check if it's against the law, and what law, and
what steps can we take against people issuing these cards.''
   Robert Slater, chairman of the Foreign Press Association, said
foreign journalists had to use the Palestinian cards because
Israeli security officials had posed as journalists.
   ``After police were posing as journalists, the Palestinians saw
the Israeli press cards as identifying either a real journalist or
a police agent,'' he said on Israel radio. ``I can understand that
the Palestinians want to make our work easier and give us their
cards.''
   ``It gives them some possibility to check if the man is really a
reporter and we accept it, it makes it easier for us,'' said
Slater, whose organization represents 200 to 300 foreign
journalists posted in Israel.
   ``If a reporter has to get a card from some element, it's not a
violation of some norm but a natural thing in every conflict in the
world ... in Lebanon, in South America,'' he added.
   But Yoram Ettinger, head of the Government Press Office, said
that ``the very acceptance of a Palestinian card in Israel, I
think, is a challenge to Israel's sovereignty.''
   ``As far as I know the card has a map of Palestine from the
Jordan river to the sea which means the elimination of Israel,'' he
said on Israel radio.
   Neither Slater nor Ettinger identified the organization that
produces the press cards. The Israeli news agency Itim said it was
a Jerusalem-based organization called ``Palestinian Press Office.''
   Radwan Abu Ayyash, head of the Arab Journalists' Association
based in east Jerusalem, said his office has been issuing cards for
foreign journalists for the last two years. There is no map on
these cards.
   ``The cards are not a challenge to anybody and have no political
significance whatsoever,'' Abu Ayyash said. ``It has nothing to do
with the uprising or an independent Palestinian state. Moreover,
our association has a license from the Israeli Interior Ministry.''
   He said the cards were issued upon request by foreign reporters
who ``told us, we are harmed by your people, would you do something
to help us and we did.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890425-0021 </DOCNO>
