<FIRST>r a PM-SmallestEmbassy Bjt   04-25 0606</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Smallest Embassy, Bjt,590</SECOND>
<HEAD>Embassy of Dominica is Family Affair</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WX6</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT M. ANDREWS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALEXANDRIA, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ambassador McDonald P. Benjamin's
pinstripe pants are wearing a little thin these days. He will miss
his prime minister's arrival from Dominica this weekend because
he'll be flying to Rome, where he doubles as ambassador to Italy.
   Not to worry, says Benjamin, puffing contentedly on his pipe. He
will leave the welcoming ceremonies to the capable hands of his
local embassy staff _ his wife, Angela, and their 25-year-old son,
McDonald Jr.
   Benjamin is the Washington diplomatic representative of the
86,000 people of Dominica (pronounced Dom-i-NEE-ca), a mountainous,
lushly forested island nestled between the French islands of
Guadeloupe and Martinique in the eastern Caribbean.
   His embassy, the smallest in Washington, occupies the Benjamins'
eighth-floor apartment in a high-rise condominium overlooking
suburban Alexandria. His wife says they have ``the best view of any
embassy in Washington.''
   The embassy's only official decoration is the Dominica national
flag, mounted on a six-foot pole in the foyer.
   Dominica is too poor to furnish Benjamin with a chauffeur-driven
limousine, so he drives to his diplomatic appointments in the
family's 1987 Plymouth sedan.
   When the ambassador invites guests to an embassy dinner party,
his German-born wife dons an apron and prepares the food. ``I am
what you call a gourmet cook,'' says Mrs. Benjamin. ``I love to do
my own cooking.''
   Benjamin, 65, a retired economist and official of the
International Fund for Agricultural and Rural Development, a United
Nations agency, has served without pay as Dominica's ambassador to
the United States, Italy and the Food and Agriculture Organization
in Rome since 1986.
   He gets an annual $25,000 expense account to cover the costs of
telephone calls, correspondence and his shuttle flights between
Washington and Rome, where he spends eight months a year. While
he's away, Mrs. Benjamin handles routine embassy affairs, and their
son steps in when they're both traveling.
   ``We get up early and get our work done like any other
embassy,'' Mrs. Benjamin says.
   Benjamin and his wife are staunchly proud of their country,
which gained its independence from Britain in 1978, and their
beloved leader, Mary Eugenia Charles, first female prime minister
of the Caribbean.
   She arrives Sunday for three days of meetings with U.S.
officials, legislators and a private group seeking to raise
$600,000 to rebuild Dominica's Parliament building, which was
destroyed by fire in 1979.
   ``Dominica is one of the most unspoiled and physically one of
the most beautiful countries in the world,'' Benjamin said in a
recent interview.
   The island, 29 miles long and 15 miles wide, contains vast rain
forests, volcanic peaks, waterfalls, hot springs, a cratered
``boiling lake'' and 365 rivers _ one for each day of the year. It
is the home of the world's only Sisserou parrots and the only
full-blooded Carib Indians, and the waters off its southwestern
coast are considered a scuba diver's paradise.
   Benjamin also praises his country's 95 percent literacy rate, a
new highway network, the doubling of Dominica's production of
bananas _ its main export _ an excellent debt-payment record and
plans to build an international airport to spur tourist traffic.
   The ambassador reminds people that he represents the
Commonwealth of Dominica, not the Dominican Republic, even though
his embassy receives phone calls and mail _ some of it top secret _
for the other, much larger Caribbean nation.
   Says Benjamin: ``Whenever I see the ambassador from the
Dominican Republic, I say, `Wouldn't it be a good idea for us to
merge our two embassies? Then we could share our secrets fully'.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890425-0023 </DOCNO>
