<FIRST>r i PM-China-Looters     04-25 0237</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-China-Looters,0242</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police Arrest 98 In Changsha Rioting</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-China</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police in the southern city of Changsha arrested
98 people, just six of them students, for looting that occurred
during a student demonstration last weekend, an official newspaper
reported today.
   The People's Daily said those arrested were caught looting 28
shops and a shopping arcade Saturday in what the official press
described as the worst rioting in 40 years of Communist rule.
   Rioting also broke out Saturday in the ancient capital of Xian,
with crowds throwing rocks and setting fire to buildings and
vehicles.
   The daily said that of the 98 detained in Changsha, 32 were
workers, 28 were unemployed, 26 were peasants, six were
self-employed and six were students. It said 52 were waiting trial.
   The outbreaks of violence occurred as university students in
Beijing and other cities took to the streets to mourn former
Communist Party chief Hu Yaobang, a reformist who died April 15,
and call for democratic reforms.
   In Beijing on Saturday, 150,000 students congregated on
Tiananmen Square in the center of the city for a peaceful
demonstration. Student leaders in Beijing have made efforts to keep
unemployed youth and other potential troublemakers out of their
ranks.
   Most of the other demonstrations have also been peaceful,
although foreign sources said students at the Agricultural College
in Hefei, eastern China, last week smashed windows and furniture in
a campus cafeteria.
</TEXT>
