<FIRST>r w PM-TMI-Siren     04-25 0509</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-TMI-Siren,500</SECOND>
<HEAD>St Paddy's Surprise: Three Mile Island Siren Jolted Residents</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF BARKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Nuclear Regulatory Commission wants to
know why a warning siren blared for 50 minutes near the Three Mile
Island nuclear plant on St. Patrick's Day, frightening residents
enough that some began to pack their belongings.
   The siren was heard by residents of York, Pa., late in the
evening of March 17 _ 11 days before the 10th anniversary of the
nation's worst commercial accident at the plant. During the
accident, pregnant women and preschoolers had been advised to
evacuate within five miles of the two reactors.
   James R. Sutton said he, his wife and two children thought it
was an ``odd time for a test'' when they were awakened by the siren
last month at 11:20 p.m. It lasted until 12:10 a.m., and the couple
said they could get no information from neighbors, television and
radio stations, or the police on the reason why.
   ``Unless you were involved, you cannot realize the anxiety and
concern for the health of your family while the siren was sounding,
nor can you share my anger at not being able to find out what was
happening,'' Sutton said in a March 23 letter to the NRC's Advisory
Committee on Reactor Safeguards.
   ``Those 50 minutes seemed like hours to me, my family and our
neighbors,'' he said. ``Some of the neighbors began to pack up and
leave the area. Even after the siren stopped, we had no idea if
there was a problem.''
   The advisory panel said it considered Sutton's letter serious
enough to warrant an investigation by the NRC staff and GPU
Nuclear, the plant operator.
   ``Events of the type described in Mr. Sutton's letter reflect
poorly on the industry's emergency planning efforts,'' Forrest
Remick, chairman of the advisory panel, said in a letter to the NRC
on April 13.
   Three Mile Island officials are not sure why the alarm was
sounded. The sirens are maintained by the utility, but are also
used by York County officials for other local emergencies not
related to the plant.
   Once it began, the siren is supposed to be able to be shut off
by remote control. But when that failed on March 17, the utility
had to call a contractor to drive to the site and shut it off by
hand, according to GPU Nuclear spokeswoman Mary Wells.
   ``Fifty minutes when you're listening in the middle of the night
is a long time,'' Wells said. ``When you're us and you have to find
out what the problem is, it's not that long. I'm sure it was for
him (Sutton).''
   The most frustrating thing, Sutton said Monday in a telephone
interview, is that he and his neighbors followed emergency
procedures by tuning to designated television and radio stations _
but still could get no information.
   An NRC official looking into the incident recently told Sutton's
wife that information was indeed available from one radio station
``but I guess we don't listen to them,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
