<FIRST>r w PM-FarmExports     04-25 0409</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Farm Exports,400</SECOND>
<HEAD>Foreign Markets Dominate Farm Bill Meeting</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIANE DUSTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Government will have to curtail domestic farm
production if the United States falls behind in world agriculture
markets, says the dean of agriculture at Purdue University.
   ``If we're not competitive, we're talking about downsizing
agriculture,'' Dr. Robert Thompson told Congress' Joint Economic
Committee on Monday.
   International trade has arisen as one of the most important
considerations for lawmakers working on the 1990 farm bill, which
will decide government policies for years to come.
   J.B. Penn, vice president of Sparks Commodities, Inc., told the
committee that technology, which was the issue of previous decades,
has successfully increased farm production.
   Future domestic demand will grow only slightly, creating a need
to pursue foreign markets, he said.
   Former agriculture secretary Bob Bergland, who now heads the
National Rural Electric Cooperative Association, said farm yields
are increasing all over the world, making other countries less
dependent on the United States.
   ``We're not the lowest cost producer,'' Bergland said. He said
Brazil produces soybeans cheaper than the United States and New
Zealand is the world's most efficient dairy producer.
   Lawmakers are also looking into the Export Enhancement Program,
which provides subsidies for U.S. farm exports to make them less
expensive abroad.
   On Monday, at a conference for agriculture reporters, Rep. Dan
Glickman, D-Kan., said he believes the the Office of Management and
Budget has put EEP on hold.
   He said OMB has refused to give its consent to any new sales
under the program since the end of February.
   Glickman, who chairs the House Agriculture soybean and wheat
subcommittee, said President Bush defended the importance of the
export subsidy program during his campaign and Agriculture
Secretary Yeutter also has supported it. The OMB appears to be in
conflict with the rest of the administration, the congressman said.
   The OMB has scheduled a meeting to review the program, but
denies that it has suspended it.
   Last week, Sen. Robert Kerrey, D-Neb., raised the same concern
voiced by Glickman and sent a letter to the OMB saying there should
be no further delays in EEP sales. A spokesman for Kerrey's office
said Monday the budget office had not responded.
   Both Kerrey and Glickman said the Export Enhancement Program is
essential to U.S. strength at trade talks in Geneva where American
negotiators are trying to get countries around the world to remove
or reduce subsidies on agricultural products.
</TEXT>
