<FILEID>AP-NR-04-25-89 0338EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Lites     04-25 0519</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lites,0538</SECOND>
<HEAD>On the Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Carriage drivers are raising a stink over a city
plan to clean up the streets by putting horses in diapers.
   ``The people proposing this don't know one end of a horse from
the other,'' said driver Alan Nugent.
   Sitting behind a gray beauty named Rover, Nugent was one of more
than 30 drivers who rode their carriages Monday to a hearing to
protest the plan.
   Drivers say the diapers _ reusable vinyl sacks strapped to a
horse's rear _ leak, smell bad, attract flies and bees and can
cause sores and infections. They also say all mares would have to
be replaced because their anatomy cannot tolerate the diapers.
   ``We feel it's inhumane,'' said carriage owner Randy Grill, who
testified at the hearing while drivers chanted ``Clean up crime,
not horse manure.''
   The New York Horse and Carriage Association pays $2,000 a month
to a private sanitation service to remove manure from Central
Park's carriage routes. Grill said drivers would be willing to pay
to double the cleanup effort if the city dropped the diaper idea.
   Dr. Fay Smimmo, a veterinarian consulting for the Department of
Parks and Recreation, said the diapers shouldn't bother horses if
adjusted properly. Many of the diapers are made by Amish
communities where horses are used everyday, she said, and special
models are available for mares.
   Smimmo said diapers are used successfully by horses in Montreal,
Atlanta, Denver, Philadelphia and New Orleans.
   ``When I first heard about the diaper idea, I thought, what a
stupid thing. But then when I started talking to drivers around the
country, they said it works fine,'' she said.
   The diapers are scheduled to go into use May 1.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MACON, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Privacy was hard to come by in their parking
lot home, but a brown killdeer successfully hatched a family in
front of a group of birdwatchers.
   Decoy tactics by her mate drew little attention as those who had
marveled at the nest witnessed the hatching of four eggs Friday.
   Last month, the killdeer and her mate spent about 10 days
digging out their nest in the mobile home parking lot.
   Oversized trucks and mobile homes moved within feet of the nest,
but the mother did not abandon her duty unless the male took over.
Although both parents shooed away curious humans, the first two
plum-sized baby birds sneaked out and, on wobbly legs, scampered
inches toward an onlooker.
   ``Last week she took off and he sat on the eggs awhile,'' said
Tommy Karr, a bird-watcher and employee at Sonshine Homes, where
the birds hatched.
   Co-worker James Weekley added: ``She'll be glad when the baby
birds are gone. I'll bet she'll never come here again.''
   After the chicks hatched, the killdeer family escaped to the
edge of the parking lot, Karr said Monday. He said he has seen the
parents, but the babies ``are nowhere to be found.''
   The brown killdeer has orange markings and typically is a shore
bird. About 10 inches long, it runs on long, spindly legs and often
nests in gravel.
</TEXT>
