<FIRST>r w PM-Iran-Contra     04-25 0490</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Iran-Contra,490</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former CIA Station Chief Indicted Again</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former CIA agent was indicted anew on
charges he lied about helping the Nicaraguan Contras, but a
conspiracy allegation was omitted for apparently the same reason
such an accusation was dropped against Oliver L. North.
   Six months after charges against Joseph F. Fernandez were
dismissed on a legal technicality, a new indictment against the
former station chief in Costa Rica was returned Monday. Missing was
the charge that he conspired to deliver arms to the Contras when
such aid was banned by Congress.
   The original conspiracy charge alleged that Fernandez worked
with former National Security Council aide Oliver L. North and arms
dealer Richard V. Secord to set up the covert arms-supply network.
   The new indictment focused on charges that Fernandez lied to
obstruct inquiries of the CIA's inspector general and the
presidential commission headed by former Sen. John Tower, R-Texas,
that investigated the Iran-Contra affair.
   James Wieghart, a spokesman for prosecutor Lawrence Walsh,
refused to comment on why the conspiracy charge was not contained
in the new indictment.
   But it appeared that Walsh decided not to pursue that
arms-resupply allegation because it was fraught with the same
secrecy concerns that forced him to drop similar charges against
North.
   Earlier this year, Walsh dropped charges that North conspired
with others to divert $15 million in U.S.-Iran arms-sale profits to
the Nicaraguan rebels when the government refused to release secret
documents the trial judge ruled were needed for North's defense.
   A federal court jury in Washington is deliberating on 12 related
charges against North, including allegations he lied to Congress
about the Iran-Contra affair.
   Legal observers have considered the Fernandez case even more
laden with secrecy problems because his lawyers are expected to
seek court approval to disclose details of his CIA activities in
Central America, where he used the alias Tomas Castillo.
   Walsh avoided those issues by obtaining a narrow indictment
charging that Fernandez lied when he denied he helped set up the
airstrip in northern Costa Rica for the resupply operation and said
he did not know that North was involved in the effort.
   Fernandez is also accused of lying to the CIA by stating that
the airstrip was built by the Costa Rican government to train
pilots for a possible Nicaraguan invasion of Costa Rica.
   Each of four charges in the indictment carries a maximum
five-year sentence and a $250,000 fine upon conviction.
   The original five-count indictment, brought in Washington, was
dismissed Oct. 19 after a judge ruled the charges should have been
brought in Virginia because Fernandez was questioned at CIA
headquarters in Langley, Va., just across the Potomac River.
   U.S. District Judge Aubrey E. Robinson Jr. gave Walsh the option
of bringing the charges again in federal court in Alexandria.
Fernandez is to appear there May 1 for arraignment before U.S.
District Judge Albert V. Bryan Jr.
</TEXT>
