<FIRST>r w PM-WashingtoninBrief     04-25 0544</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Washington in Brief,550</SECOND>
<HEAD>Astronaut, High Agency Officials Resign from Space Agency</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two top NASA officials say they've decided to
retire before new federal retirement regulations take effect.
   Noel W. Hinners, the third-ranking executive in the National
Aeronautics and Space Administration, said he will retire on May
14, the day before new post-retirement regulations for government
employees become effective.
   James B. Odom, 55, chief of NASA's space station program, said
he is retiring next Sunday and blamed the sudden decision on ``the
impact of some upcoming changes on government retirees.''
   Also announcing retirement plans was astronaut Jon A. McBride,
45, who was scheduled to command a space shuttle flight next March.
He said he will retire from NASA on May 12 and will retire from the
Navy in ``the near future.''
   Hinners blamed his decision to retire on what he called
``uncertainty in interpretation of new post-employment laws.''
   A geologist and geochemist, Hinners served as chief scientist
for NASA and joined the NASA senior management team in Washington
in 1987.
   Odom, a 33-year veteran of NASA, has headed the space station
program for a year. The agency is in the midst of a major push to
persuade Congress to budget funds for starting construction on the
station.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>___</NOTE>
<NOTE>Power Problems Keep Officials in Dark</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some of the nation's top law enforcement
officials worked in the dark for a while because construction crews
couldn't connect an emergency generator supplying power to part of
the Justice Department.
   Electrical power to the southwest portion of the Justice
Department building was knocked out last week when a power cable
was severed by construction crews installing anti-terrorist
security barriers on the west side of the building, said
spokeswoman Deborah Burstion-Wade.
   Power was restored about 6 p.m. Monday but the outage
inconvenienced many top officials for most of the business day.
   A large generator inside a tractor-trailer was plugged into the
building to provide power. But crews had trouble reconnecting the
generator Monday, leaving the office of Attorney General Dick
Thornburgh and some of his top deputies without power, she said.
   ``We are fortunate this occurred on a day the A.G. is in sunny
California,'' said David Runkel, an aide to Thornburgh, who was
meeting with Drug Enforcement Administration officials in Los
Angeles.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>___</NOTE>
<NOTE>Army Grounds Transport Helicopters</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Army has grounded its entire fleet of
Vietnam era UH-1 Huey transport helicopters for a safety inspection
of main rotor bolts.
   The service said the grounding order was issued late Friday and
was keeping about 3,100 choppers on the ground.
   Lt. Col. John Reitz, an Army spokesman, said the grounding order
was prompted by an incident last week in which a Huey was being
moved manually across a tarmac and two of the bolts in the ``main
rotor pillow block'' suddenly snapped.
   He said that further inspection showed cracks and stress
corrosion in the bolts.
   ``In this case, there was no accident and no loss of life,''
Reitz said. ``But you would have a big problem if this happened in
flight. So a grounding order was issued immediately to ensure
safety.''
   The bolts at issue sit atop the main rotor hub and help hold the
main rotor blades to the shaft.
</TEXT>
