<FIRST>r i PM-Panama-US     04-25 0496</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Panama-US,0512</SECOND>
<HEAD>Panama Protests Reported US Funding Of Opposition</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALINA GUERRERO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Acting President Manuel Solis Palma
has accused the United States of secretly giving $10 million to
opponents of Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega as part of a plan to
retain control of the Panama Canal.
   Solis Palma said Monday that ``Panamanian traitors'' were
conspiring to renege on the 1977 treaties under which control of
the vital waterway is to be ceded to Panama in the year 2000.
   Noriega, head of the Defense Forces and Panama's de facto ruler,
accused the United States of playing a ``dirty game.'' He told a
news conference that ``the men who speak of democracy have dirtied
their hands.
   ``The Panamanian people _ and it is important that the United
States know this and that President Bush not be deceived _ are
supremely angered.''
   The United States has been at odds with Noriega, once a strong
ally, since last year, when a U.S. grand jury indicted him on
charges of drug trafficking and money laundering.
   U.S. News and World Report said in its May 1 issue that
President Bush has signed a secret intelligence directive to give
$10 million to the Panamanian opposition. It says the money was to
be used for printing, advertising, transportation and
communications for opposition candidates in May 7 elections.
   White House officials have refused to comment on the report,
saying it involves covert operations.
   Attorney Guillermo Endara, who is running against Noriega-backed
presidential candidate Carlos Duque, on Monday denied receiving any
campaign funds from the United States.
   ``We haven't asked for or received, nor are we going to receive,
cent from foreigners nor from the United States nor from any other
power,'' Endara said in a television appearance. ``All the money we
have used in this campaign has been Panamanian money and we would
not accept any foreign money.''
   The opposition has accused Noriega of planning to rig the May 7
vote, in which Panamanians will choose a new president, two vice
presidents, 67 legislators and 510 local representatives.
   Endara has called the election a plebiscite on Noriega's de
facto rule.
   Solis Palma contended Monday that the United States would resort
to military intervention if its attempts to ``destabilize'' Panama
failed.
   Last year, the Reagan administration set in motion a plan to
oust Noriega. The New York Times reported Monday that if that
approached failed, the administration wanted to organize a coup.
   The Senate Intelligence Committee rejected the coup plan,
however, on grounds that Noriega might be assassinated, the Times
reported. A presidential order forbids U.S. participation in
assassinations.
   Last spring, the United States imposed economic sanctions
against Panama in an attempt to force out Noriega.
   Bush this month extended the sanctions, which include sharp
restrictions on U.S. companies that do business in Panama, a hold
on assets of the Panamanian government in the United States and a
prohibition on tax payments by U.S. organizations to Panama.
</TEXT>
