<FIRST>r w PM-Turner-Resignation     04-25 0357</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Turner-Resignation,350</SECOND>
<HEAD>DC Police Chief to Quit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police Chief Maurice T. Turner is retiring
amid growing notoriety of the District of Columbia as a drug and
murder capital as well as continuing conflict with Mayor Marion S.
Barry, published reports say.
   Turner, a 32-year veteran of the force whom Barry had appointed
chief in 1981, submitted his retirement papers and will step down
July 31, The Washington Post and The Washington Times reported in
today's editions.
   ``I've been thinking about it a while,'' Turner told the Times.
``I guess you've got to go when the environment is right.''
   Turner declined to comment on reports that he may take a
position with the office of national drug policy director William
J. Bennett, the Times said. The Post reported that Asstistant Chief
Isaac Fulwood, the department's second-ranking official, will be
named to succeed Turner in running the 3,990-member force.
   The Times said Turner did not rule out the possibility he might
run for mayor. ``Well, I'm still playing it by ear,'' he said.
``Some people are asking me (to run for mayor), but I just don't
want to say publicly right now.''
   Turner had been increasingly at odds with Barry over the past
few months, according to the reports.
   The Times quoted a source close to Turner as saying the chief
feared his years of service would be tarnished by controversy
surrounding Barry.
   One source of friction was Barry's attempt to call police
officials to learn the results of an internal department inquiry
into the handling of Barry's visit to a friend at a downtown hotel
room, the Post said. The friend, Charles Lewis, has since been
indicted on drug charges.
   A police investigation of a drug complaint at the hotel room
last December was abruptly halted when police learned that Barry
was in the room, according to reports.
   The two also feuded over increasing the size of the force, a
move that Barry opposed, the Post said.
   In a statement issued by his office Monday night, Barry praised
Turner for his ``illustrious and distinguished career'' and said he
is ``respected both locally and nationally.''
</TEXT>
