<FIRST>u i PM-TakeshitaProfile     04-25 0526</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Takeshita Profile,0540</SECOND>
<HEAD>Takeshita Steps Down To Save Party</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Japan-Politics, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JANICE FUHRMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When Noboru Takeshita took office as prime
minister, skeptics doubted that the man known for his cautious,
back-room political style would be able to create a commanding role
for Japan on the international stage.
   Ironically, he proved successful at his diplomatic efforts, but
it was his main strength _ fund-raising for the governing Liberal
Democratic Party _ that brought him down after only 18 months on
the job.
   In announcing today that he intended to resign as Japan's 46th
prime minister, Takeshita took responsibility for a scandal that
made the country's Japan's least popular prime minister since World
War II, according to polls.
   Takeshita, 65, took over as prime minister from the charismatic
Yasuhiro Nakasone in November 1987.
   Within two months of taking office he had visited the United
States and established a first-name relationship with former
President Reagan. He traveled frequently to other countries.
   Under Takeshita's leadership, Japan surpassed the United States
as the world's biggest foreign aid donor to developing countries.
It also earned new respect as a contributor to diplomatic efforts.
   Takeshita also played busy host to dignitaries from 164 nations
in February at the state funeral for Emperor Hirohito, an
unprecedented gathering of world leaders.
   But his popularity sagged among the Japanese with increasing
revelations that he and members of his Cabinet had accepted
bargain-priced stocks and other donations from the Recruit Co., an
information conglomerate that allegedly attempted to buy government
influence.
   Takeshita acknowledged receiving more than $1 million from
Recruit. He also confirmed that he borrowed about $381,700 from the
company in 1987 and repaid the money a few months later.
   Recruit was a major donor to Takeshita's fund-raising parties.
Party tickets are an important tool in raising the money needed to
gain and maintain office in Japan.
   Takeshita was partly motivated to resign out of fear his term
would be remembered for nothing but the Recruit scandal, said
Yotaro Konaka, a political analyst.
   Konaka said the prime minister did not want to see the Liberal
Democratic Party lose its 35-year hold on the nation's parliament
in summer elections, or watch his newly implemented _ and highly
unpopular _ tax reform program be canceled.
   ``Other than the emperor's funeral, he must have realized that
the tax reform was his only domestic achievement,'' Konaka said.
``If the tax reform is erased, it will make him a prime minister
with no achievement whatsoever.''
   The eldest son of a rice-wine brewing family, Takeshita was born
Feb. 26, 1924, in a village in western Japan. After serving as a
pilot trainee at the end of World War II, he completed his
university studies, taught English and social studies for several
years, and then turned to politics.
   He was elected to his local state assembly at 27, and then won a
seat in the powerful lower house of the Parliament in 1958 at age
34.
   His political skills gained him key posts. He became finance
minister in 1979 under Prime Minister Masayoshi Ohira and continued
to hold that high post under Nakasone's administration.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
