<FIRST>r i AM-Japan-Markets     04-25 0267</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Markets,0277</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Falls, Share Prices Bounce Back</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar finished lower against the Japanese yen
Tuesday, but share prices on the Tokyo Stock Exchange gained
markedly following Prime Minister Noboru Takeshita's announcement
that he will resign.
   The 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average, a 223.89-point loser on
Monday, regained 438.86 points, or 1.34 percent, to finish at
33,244.78 points. The gain was the third-largest for one day this
year.
   The dollar closed at 131.17 yen, down 0.21 yen from Monday's
131.38-yen finish. The currency started higher at 131.65 yen and
gradually fell while ranging between 131.05-131.65 yen.
   The yen rose as participants began buying the currency after the
news about Takeshita's resignation as well as the possibility of an
interest rate hike by the Bank of Japan, traders said.
   Market players expect Takeshita's resignation, coming after much
uncertainty, to stabilize the yen, said a trader with a commercial
bank in Tokyo.
   Takeshita announced his decision to resign following a Cabinet
meeting late Tuesday morning.
   Also encouraging yen-buying were expectations that the Japanese
central bank might raise its interest rate soon.
   Bank of Japan Governor Satoshi Sumita at the bank's branch chief
meeting Tuesday said the bank would swiftly take appropriate
measures if instability of prices occurs.
   On the stock exchange, dealers attributed the sharp gain in the
market's main index to Takeshita's decision to resign.
   ``Investors have already expected the resignation to come sooner
or later, and were reassured by the news'' because they believed
the resignation would remedy current political instability, said a
dealer with Nomura Securities, speaking on condition of anonymity.
</TEXT>
