<FILEID>AP-NR-04-25-89 0418EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Palestinian-Americans 1stLd-Writethru a0423 04-25 0818</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Palestinian-Americans, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0423,0841</SECOND>
<HEAD>American Citizen Disappears In Israeli Military Custody</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: To CORRECT uprising death figure to 444, SUB penultimate graf.
^An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KARIN LAUB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KUFR MALIK, Occupied West Bank (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two Palestinians who are
American citizens have become entangled in Israel's military
justice system and one disappeared after answering a summons to an
army headuarters.
   Relatives of Jafer Hamayel, 25, said he complied with the army
summons on April 13 and they have since been unable to locate him.
   The other American, 16-year-old Mansour Abdallah, was accused of
throwing stones and has been held for three months without bail and
without appearing in court, his lawyer said.
   Human rights activists say Hamayel and Abdallah are among
thousands of Palestinians who are being denied basic legal rights
under military justice in effect in the occupied West Bank and Gaza
Strip.
   Army officials deny the allegations, saying the military has set
up a special office to help lawyers find clients and that bail has
been granted in hundreds of cases.
   ``We believe we have a liberal judicial system in the
territories, but we should not be judged in the same context as
Western countries that are not in a state of war,'' an army
official said earlier this year.
   In the cases of Hamayel and Abdallah, both of whom had lived in
Puerto Rico, the army was unable to locate either one even after
being given details three days earlier by The Associated Press.
   An army official, who could not be identified under military
regulations, said he could not locate them because he did not have
Israeli-issued identification numbers for them.
   Palestinian lawyer Jonathan Kuttab said Abdallah has only a U.S.
passport and not an Israeli identity card. Hamayel's relatives said
he had his Israeli card with him when he disappeared and they did
not know the number.
   Hamayel was born in Kufr Malik, a mountain village known for its
resistance to Israeli occupation.
   On a visit Monday to the village 15 miles north of Jerusalem,
Palestine Liberation Organization slogans, Palestinian flags and a
poster of PLO chief Yasser Arafat adorned the main square.
   Hamayel left Kufr Malik in 1983 after being imprisoned for three
months on charges of violating Israeli law by raising Palestinian
flags, said his uncle, Ata Hamayel, 39.
   He said Jafer Hamayel then lived for six years in San Juan,
Puerto Rico, joining his parents who went to the Caribbean island
in 1966 and now own a clothing store.
   The uncle said the young man had studied accounting at Puerto
Rico's InterAmerican University.
   Ata Hamayel gave this account of his nephew's disappearance:
   Several months ago Jafer Hamayel became a U.S. citizen. On April
4, he returned to Kufr Malik to renew his Israeli-issued identity
card. Without the card he would lose the right to live in the West
Bank.
   Shortly after his arrival he was given a summons to appear at
the military headquarters in Ramallah and went there April 13.
   Later that day, a Ramallah man saw Jafer Hamayel being held in a
tent jail at the headquarters but the family has not seen him since
and has not been notified by the army of his fate.
   Ata Hamayel said U.S. consular officials were refused permission
to see his nephew at the Ramallah headquarters.
   U.S. Consulate spokesman David Good said efforts were made to
find Jafer Hamayel but ``we haven't been able to make contact with
him yet.'' Good refused to discuss details of the case.
   Ahmed Sayyad, Abdallah's lawyer, said the youth was arrested
Jan. 23 in his native West Bank village of Surda on charges of
throwing stones and setting up road barricades.
   Sayyad said military officials failed to present Abdallah at
court hearings March 19 and March 30 and have not responded to a
request that the youth be released on bail.
   The lawyer said another court hearing is scheduled for Sunday.
   Good said consular officials visited Abdallah on March 24 and
are trying to get him released on bail. He said Abdallah and
Hamayel are the only two Palestinian-Americans being held under
military detention.
   Good said he did know how many American citizens have been
arrested since the Palestinian uprising began in December 1987 in
the West Bank and Gaza Strip but added: ``We never had more than
three or four at a time.''
   About 7,000 Palestinians with U.S. passports live in the West
Bank and Israeli-annexed Arab east Jerusalem, according to Good. He
said only a few live in the Gaza Strip.
   Army officials say at least 20,000 Palestinians have been
arrested during the uprising, which has claimed the lives of 444
Palestinians and 18 Israelis.
   Army figures showed 6,650 Palestinians were being detained as of
early April with 3,627 awaiting trial, 1,187 held under emergency
laws that require no charges or trial, 974 awaiting sentencing and
862 serving sentences.
</TEXT>
