<FIRST>r p PM-DaleyInauguration     04-25 0447</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Daley Inauguration,0460</SECOND>
<HEAD>Daley Takes Office As Mayor</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BERNARD SCHOENBURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Richard M. Daley put a hand on an old family
bible, looked into the eyes of an old family friend and took the
oath of mayor, a job his late father held for 21 years.
   But in Orchestra Hall, surrounded by many state and local
officials whose careers started with the blessing of Chicago boss
Richard J. Daley, the new mayor said his administration would not
resemble his father's vaunted army of loyal foot soldiers.
   ``Business as usual is a prescription for failure,'' he said
Monday after he took the oath on his 47th birthday, noting that his
father instilled him with values, but policies will be his own.
   ``The old ways of doing business simply aren't adequate to cope
with the new challenges we face,'' Daley said.
   Daley said City Hall will be open to all _ a pledge that
produced optimism among his black election opponents and their
supporters. Chicago is the largest U.S. city to replace a black
mayor with a white.
   ``He appears to be using a reconciling approach as opposed to a
polarizing approach, and that is good,'' said Jesse Jackson, who
supported two blacks and had warned during the campaign that
Chicago would return to the machine politics that marked the elder
Daley's reign.
   Daley was sworn in by U.S. District Judge Abraham Lincoln
Marovitz, a family friend who presided at the elder Daley's six
inaugurations.
   ``This is a sentimental journey for me,'' said the 83-year-old
judge.
   The new mayor delivered an upbeat speech, mentioning few
specific goals but acknowledging that the city's school system,
labeled the worst in the nation by President Reagan's Education
Secretary William Bennett, needs an overhaul.
   ``Today our foundation is crumbling and nothing but genuine
school reform will repair it,'' Daley said.
   The former Cook County prosecutor was elected April 4 to
complete the last two years of the second term of the late Harold
Washington, Chicago's first black mayor. Daley succeeds Eugene
Sawyer, who had been acting mayor since Washington's death 17
months ago.
   Daley defeated Sawyer, who is black, in the Democratic primary
Feb. 28 and then defeated black Alderman Timothy Evans and
Republican Edward Vrdolyak in the general election.
   Washington's first election in 1983 led to a few years of bitter
debate in City Council, with a white majority blocking his
programs. Evans predicted that black aldermen would not act as
obstructionists during Daley's term.
   ``Wherever he (Daley) is correct, we're going to move right
along with him,'' Evans said, but if aldermen disagree with the
mayor they will ``protect the gains of this community.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
