<FIRST>r a PM-IceChunk     04-25 0243</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Ice Chunk,0248</SECOND>
<HEAD>Volleyball-Size Chunk Crashes Through Roof in Thunderstorm</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A chunk of ice the size of a volleyball
crashed through the roof of a house during a thunderstorm and a
meteorologist said it may have come from an airplane.
   ``You can safely say it was related to the thunderstorm, but I
don't think it fell out of the sky by itself,'' said Ted Buehner,
meteorologist for the National Weather Service office at Portland
International Airport. ``It had to have some kind of assistance.''
   Most likely the ice accumulated on the wing of a plane and then
fell off, Buehner said. But he checked with the control tower and
was told there had been no reports of abnormal ice buildup.
   The ice smashed through the roof into a bedroom of a house owned
by Duane and Joan Cline as Cline was reading the newspaper in his
living room Monday night.
   Cline said when he first heard the noise, he thought a car had
crashed into his house, as one did a few years ago.
   But then he looked into the spare bedroom and saw a foot-long
hole in the ceiling with plaster, wood and roof material scattered
with ice on the floor. The ice apparently had broken into about 20
pieces, with the largest about the size of a softball, he said.
   Cline said he planned to store the ice in his freezer and may
have it tested.
</TEXT>
