<FILEID>AP-NR-04-25-89 0628EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-ComputerHacker     04-25 0441</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Computer Hacker,0456</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Rejects Plea Bargain as Too Lenient</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDA DEUTSCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A pudgy super-hacker who agreed to plead
guilty and spend a year in prison for computer fraud must stand
trial after all because a judge thinks the proposed sentence isn't
harsh enough.
   U.S. District Judge Mariana Pfaelzer surprised Kevin David
Mitnick, his defense attorney and a prosecutor by rejecting their
plea agreement on Monday and ordering Mitnick to trial.
   ``You have been engaged in this activity for far too long and no
one has adequately punished you,'' the judge told the defendant,
citing two previous convictions for computer fraud in 1981 and 1987.
   ``This is the last time you are going to do this.''
   The judge suggested the 25-year-old Mitnick remains a danger and
rejected a prosecutor's belated claim that Mitnick didn't destroy
anything of value.
   Mitnick, clad in a blue prison uniform, appeared stunned by the
rejection. Outside court, defense lawyer Alan Rubin expressed
disappointment and said the judge's action took him by surprise.
   ``She obviously considers him a far greater menace than I do or
the government does,'' he said. Rubin said it was unlikely Mitnick
would agree to any new bargain involving a longer sentence.
   When the case began last December, prosecutors portrayed Mitnick
as a brilliant youth obsessed with junk food and computers who used
the code name ``Condor'' to infiltrate computer systems in the
United States and England.
   They suggested he might have gained access to top secret
National Security Agency computers, but such charges were never
brought. Last month, they agreed to a plea bargain.
   Under his plea, Mitnick had admitted he infiltrated Digital
Equipment Corp.'s computer system and stole one of its programs. He
also admitted stealing 16 MCI telephone codes and using them to
make long-distance calls for free.
   The prosecution had agreed to dismiss two additional charges,
one of which alleged Mitnick infiltrated the computer system of
Leeds University in England. If Mitnick stands trial, those charges
would be reinstated.
   Assistant U.S. attorney James Sanders told the judge he had
``thought long and hard'' before entering the agreement and
concluded that Mitnick's actions weren't seriously destructive.
   ``This is not a case where Mr. Mitnick destroyed anyone's
computer or inserted viruses in a computer,'' he told the judge.
   He also noted that the government would have to grant immunity
to an alleged co-conspirator, Leonard DiCicco, to obtain his
testimony against Mitnick.
   But Pfaelzer was unmoved.
   ``I don't think a year is long enough. And I'm not going to
honor the agreement,'' she said. A pretrial report recommended a
higher sentence, she noted.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890425-0056 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-25-89 0646EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Executions-US     04-25 0614</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Executions-US,0631</SECOND>
<HEAD>Amnesty Says Capital Punishment In US Arbitrary, Racially Biased</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL WEST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Amnesty International, which opposes capital
punishment in all circumstances, said today that the use of the
death penalty in the United States appears arbitrary and biased
against blacks and Hispanics.
   In a 268-page worldwide report titled ``When the State Kills,''
the human rights group condemned the use of the death penalty as a
``judicial lottery'' that does not deter crime.
   The United States and 99 other countries execute people for
crimes.
   ``Despite a range of safeguards, the use of the death penalty in
the USA appears to be arbitrary and racially biased,'' Amnesty
International said in the report's introduction.
   The London-based group, which won the Nobel Peace Prize in 1977,
criticized America for executing convicts for crimes committed when
they were juveniles.
   In June 1988, 30 prisoners in 14 states were under sentence of
death for crimes committed when they were under age 18. This is
permitted by 25 states, the report said.
   As of May 1988, 2,048 prisoners were under the death sentence in
35 states, according to the report. Ninety-eight prisoners were
executed from 1977 to May 31, 1988, including three juveniles, two
in Texas and one in South Carolina.
   The report mentioned the case of James Terry Roach. He pleaded
guilty in 1977 when he was 17 to two murders, sexual assault,
kidnapping and other charges, and was executed in South Carolina on
Jan. 10, 1986.
   Amnesty said there are regional disparities in the numbers of
death sentences. Four states _ Florida, Georgia, Louisiana and
Texas _ have accounted for more than three-quarters of all
executions since 1977, the report said.
   ``Jury selection procedures in most states allow prosecutors to
exclude committed opponents of the death penalty from sitting as
jurors. ... Studies have indicated that this practice has created
`death-prone' juries,'' according to the report.
   It said black defendants, especially in Southern states, have
often been convicted by all-white juries after prosecutors have
excluded black prospective jurors.
   Blacks comprise 12 percent of the national population but 41
percent of prisoners under sentence of death, the report said.
   ``The evidence suggests that race _ especially that of the
victim _ has an important bearing on the likelihood of a death
sentence being imposed, especially in the Southern states. Although
blacks and whites are the victims of homicide in almost equal
numbers, most offenders who are sentenced to death are convicted of
murdering whites.''
   This was the case in 86 percent of trials in 1987, it said.
Between January 1977 and May 1988, according to Amnesty's report,
45 of the 98 people executed were black or Hispanic and 84 were
convicted of killing white victims, the report said.
   It cited the cases of Willie Jasper Darden in Florida and Edward
Earl Johnson in Mississippi as two since 1985 in which evidence
emerged after the executions that strongly suggested innocence.
   Amnesty International also finds deficiencies in legal aid
available to capital defendants. The lawyers often are
``inexperienced, ill-equipped to handle such cases and severely
limited in their resources,'' it said.
   Most states do not provide legal representation for capital
defendants after appeal to state supreme courts, so ``in order to
file further appeals on constitutional grounds, they must rely on
volunteer lawyers working without payment,'' the report said.
   Many prisoners awaiting execution may be mentally ill or
mentally handicapped, it argued, and said at least six such
prisoners have been executed since 1984.
   The report cites a 1987 study saying 349 people convicted of
capital offenses between 1900 and 1985 turned out to be innocent
and 23 of those people were executed.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890425-0057 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-25-89 0704EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-WeatherpageWeather     04-25 0414</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Weatherpage Weather,0427</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rains Drench West; Thunderstorms Hit Plains</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Much of the nation enjoyed fair skies today, but an unusual span
of foul weather brought more rain to Northern California and
thunderstorms produced hail and damaging winds in the Plains.
   The eccentric weather pattern over Northern California created a
series of mini-floods, traffic tie-ups and accidents, and clogged
drains in San Francisco.
   Elsewhere, thunderstorms produced golf ball-size hail in
northeastern Colorado, and wind gusts up to 59 mph in northeastern
Nebraska.
   Thunderstorms also produced dime size-hail and downed trees in
parts of southeastern Minnesota and southern Wisconsin. Wind gusted
to 70 mph in northwestern Oklahoma and produced severe weather in
south-central Kansas. Hail accompanied a late evening thunderstorm
in north-central South Dakota.
   Showers dampened eastern South Carolina and southwestern Oregon
early today.
   Today's forecast called for widely scattered thunderstorms over
the Great Plains; scattered showers and thunderstorms from the
upper Mississippi Valley across the Great Lakes and central
Appalachians to parts of North Carolina; showers and a few
thunderstorms over the West Coast and the northern Rockies; snow
over northern Nevada, western Montana and northern Maine.
   Highs were expected to be in the 40s over northern Nevada and
parts of Montana and northern Maine; in the 50s and 60s on the West
Coast, the northern Rockies, the Dakotas and the Great Lakes to the
north Atlantic Coast; in the 90s over parts of the central and
southern Plains and the middle Mississippi Valley; and in the 70s
and 80s elsewhere.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 a.m. EDT ranged from 26
degrees at Concord and Lebanon, N.H., to 78 degrees at Fort Riley,
Kan.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 65 fair; Boston 44 partly cloudy; Buffalo 43
cloudy; Charleston, S.C. 66 fair; Cincinnati 61 fair; Cleveland 46
fair; Detroit 43 partly cloudy; Miami 72 fair; New York 50 partly
cloudy; Philadelphia 46 fair; Pittsburgh 47 partly cloudy;
Portland, Maine 26 fair; Washington 49 fair.
   _Central: Bismarck 47 cloudy; Chicago 65 cloudy; Dallas-Fort
Worth 71 partly cloudy; Denver 55 cloudy; Des Moines 72 cloudy;
Indianapolis 59 fair; Kansas City 74 windy; Minneapolis-St. Paul 54
cloudy; Nashville 68 fair; New Orleans 66 fair; St. Louis 74 partly
cloudy.
   _West: Albuquerque 54 fair; Anchorage 36 rain; Las Vegas 53
windy; Los Angeles 54 fair; Phoenix 64 fair; Salt Lake City 55
partly cloudy; San Diego 56 fair; San Francisco 46 partly cloudy;
Seattle 55 fair.
   _Canada: Montreal 34 partly cloudy; Toronto 43 rain.
