<FILEID>AP-NR-04-25-89 0726EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-NYCGovernment     04-25 0394</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-NYC Government,0410</SECOND>
<HEAD>Proposals to Revamp Government Get Mixed Reviews</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER ALAN HARPER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A plan to make the city's government
constitutional by expanding the City Council and setting up a new
commission drew good reviews from the mayor but was panned by
presidents of the five boroughs.
   Frederick A.O. Schwarz, chairman of the Charter Revision
Commission, outlined proposals Monday that would give the mayor
more direct control over awarding contracts, previously the domain
of the powerful Board of Estimate. The mayor would be required to
submit his plans to communities for review, though.
   The proposals also would increase the City Council to 50 members
from 35 and create a new commission to oversee city-owned land,
rule on zoning changes and award city franchises, also currently
the board's province.
   The mayor would appoint four of the 11 commission members.
   The plan comes one month after the U.S. Supreme Court ruled that
the Board of Estimate was unconstitutional because it violated the
one-person, one-vote doctrine. Schwarz said he hoped his plan would
provide fair representation for all New Yorkers.
   Staten Island, the city's smallest borough with about 400,000
residents, has the same presence on the board as the other four
boroughs, including Brooklyn with 2.2 million residents.
   Staten Island Borough President Ralph Lamberti said the
proposals ``are a disaster for Staten Island and all local
communities. It makes the authority of the mayor almost czar-like.''
   Brooklyn Borough President Howard Golden said Schwarz ``is
telling the boroughs to drop dead.''
   But Schwarz said the plan would give borough leaders more say
over land use, budget formulation and budget oversight.
   Mayor Edward I. Koch and City Comptroller Harrison Goldin were
generally pleased by the proposals.
   ``The principles that the chairman lays out in his report would
seem to be quite positive,'' said mayoral spokesman Clifford Chanin.
   Under the plan, the comptroller no longer would be involved in
policy and would be limited to fiscal matters and oversight and
audit functions on contracts.
   ``The comptroller's role has always been overwhelmingly
fiscal,'' Goldin said. ``This recognizes that reality.''
   The Charter Revision Commission, which was created by the mayor,
has set a goal of getting a proposal for governmental change on the
November ballot.
   The chairman's proposals are the first formal agenda on which
the 15-member commission can debate. They aren't final.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
