<FILEID>AP-NR-04-25-89 0728EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Korea-PlaneBombing     04-25 0538</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Korea-Plane Bombing,0557</SECOND>
<HEAD>North Korean Woman Sentenced To Death For Plane Bombing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL SHIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A confessed North Korean agent wept
today as a court sentenced her to death for the 1987 bombing of a
South Korean airliner in which 115 people were killed.
   Officials said they expect 27-year-old Kim Hyon Hui to be
pardoned.
   Ms. Kim shook with grief as Judge Chung Sang-hwak pronounced her
guilty of violating national security and aviation laws and
sentenced her to die by hanging. She said nothing before being
whisked away by security agents.
   Relatives of the victims sat quietly as Chung said there was no
doubt that Ms. Kim was guilty of planting a bomb aboard a Korea Air
Boeing 707 that disappeared on Nov. 29, 1987 over the Andaman Sea
as it approached the Burmese coast. The plane was en route to Seoul
from Baghdad, Iraq.
   Ms. Kim confessed on South Korean television in January 1988
that she planted the bomb as part of a plot by senior leaders of
communist North Korea to disrupt the Olympic Games, held
successfully in Seoul last summer.
   She said at a hearing on April 4 that she wanted to die to atone
for the deaths.
   She has a week to appeal the sentence, but defense lawyers said
no decision had been made on the matter.
   South Korean officials, speaking on condition of anonymity, said
Ms. Kim was expected to be pardoned on grounds she was duped by
communist North Korea and has repented.
   North Korea has denied it had anything to do with the plane
bombing and has claimed it was engineered by South Korea to
embarrass the north.
   The two Koreas have been bitter rivals since the division of the
peninsula at the end of World War II.
   Judge Chung, who headed the three-judge panel hearing the case,
said the destruction of the plane underlined the threat the north
poses to South Korea's freedom and survival.
   ``We have an enemy which always tries to our destroy liberal
democratic system. We must face that reality with resolute
determination,'' he said in a 13-minute statement.
   The sentencing came after three hearings during which Ms. Kim
often sobbed into a hankerchief as she listened to testimony that
the plane exploded in less than a second, killing all aboard
instantly. The bodies were never recovered.
   Ms. Kim arrived at the courthouse today under heavy security and
hundreds of police surrounded the building to prevent protests by
angry relatives or a possible threat from North Korean agents.
   Relatives of the victims disrupted the earlier proceedings and
often yelled ``Kill her!''
   They were silent today as Chung read the verdict and gathered in
small groups outside afterward. Some relatives expressed
satisfaction with the death sentence, but others urged mercy.
   Ms. Kim said she and another intelligence agent pretending to be
Japanese tourists planted the bomb disguised as a radio and a
liquor bottle when they flew from Baghdad to Abu Dhabi, where they
got off.
   The pair were arrested a short time later in Bahrain and
attempted to take cyanide hidden in cigarettes. The other agent, an
elderly man, died, but Kim recovered and was extradited to Seoul.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
