<FIRST>r a PM-RougeExplosion     04-25 0242</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Rouge Explosion,0251</SECOND>
<HEAD>2 Killed In Blast At Massive Ford Complex</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto DT1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DEARBORN, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Investigators were searching today for
the cause of an explosion underneath Ford Motor Co.'s massive Rouge
complex that killed two maintenance workers, tore holes in parking
lots and flipped cars.
   Ford spokesman John Spelich said the bodies of John L. Hatch, in
his early 50s, and Billy Stiener, 27, were found Monday evening in
an underground tunnel. Spelich did not know how or when they died.
   The explosion Monday morning shook the underpinnings of the
1,100-acre complex just west of Detroit and knocked out power to
factories, including the plant that makes Mustang automobiles.
   Spelich said the complex would operate normally today, except
for one glass-making building.
   Divers searched for the men after the tunnel was flooded with 4
to 6 feet of water. The blast apparently ruptured a water pipe,
Spelich said.
   Spelich said the victims were employed by Doetsch Industrial
Services Inc. of Detroit.
   John Schultz, a bus driver at the complex, said soon after the
explosion he saw flames shooting 300 to 500 feet into the air for a
short period. No fire damage was found, however.
   On the ground, concern that asbestos from steam pipe wrappings
might escape into the air caused workers to wear masks and
protective clothing.
   About 6,500 first-shift employees were sent home after the
explosion. Monday afternoon shifts were canceled.
</TEXT>
