<FIRST>r a PM-BRF--CrackCleanup     04-25 0145</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--Crack Cleanup,0148</SECOND>
<HEAD>Church Is Getting Rid Of Crack Houses</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A church that raised $175,000 over two
decades toward building a new place of worship used the money
instead to buy several abandoned neighborhood homes formerly taken
over by crack dealers.
   The homes bought by the Third Shiloh Missionary Baptist Church
will be renovated and rented to low-income people, said Benjamin
Edwards Sr., the church's board chairman.
   Church members ``all jumped at the idea. The vote was
unanimous,'' Edwards said Monday. The church bought seven houses
this month.
   He said the decision was easy. The church has been broken into
repeatedly; thieves even took the air conditioner. And churchgoers
were particularly upset when drugs were sold a few feet from the
church during services.
   The church already has a waiting list for renters. ``The word
spread like wildfire,'' Edwards said.
