<FILEID>AP-NR-04-25-89 0841EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-AlcoholLawsuit     04-25 0473</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Alcohol Lawsuit,0484</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bourbon Drinker Asks Damages for Son's Birth Defects</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATIA BLACKBURN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A lawyer for a 4-year-old with severe birth
defects said the child deserves to be compensated because a liquor
company did not warn the boy's mother of the dangers of drinking
during pregnancy.
   But a lawyer for the James B. Beam Distillery Co. of Deerfield,
Ill., said Monday the mother had been repeatedly warned over a
period of years about the risks of alcohol and she kept drinking up
to a half of a fifth of bourbon per day. No warning on the part of
a manufacturer would have persuaded her to stop, the attorney said.
   Michael Thorp, the 4-year-old son of Harold and Candace Thorp of
Seattle, was born mentally retarded, neurologically impaired,
developmentally stunted and malformed, according to the lawsuit
filed by his parents.
   The Thorps contend that the liquor company should have provided
labels warning that alcohol can cause birth defects. In court
papers, Mrs. Thorp said she didn't know her drinking would damage
her child.
   The case focuses attention on a federal law taking effect in
November that will require labels on all beer, wine or hard liquor
that alcohol can cause health problems and birth defects.
   In his opening statement Monday, a lawyer for the boy and his
parents, Barry M. Epstein, said Michael was the victim of fetal
alcohol syndrome and deserves enough money to take care of him for
the rest of his life.
   Epstein said Beam knew about a link between alcohol and birth
defects in 1978 but made no effort to inform the public. Beam
decided, along with 22 competitors, not to place warnings on its
beverages, Epstein said.
   Had warning labels existed and the information been out, the
Thorps ``could have acted to see what could be done to safeguard
this child,'' he said.
   In opening statements by the defense, lawyer Shannon Stafford
said, ``Family members and doctors tried for years to get Candy to
stop drinking. ... (She) ignored every warning she got.
   ``Evidence will demonstrate that Candace Thorp was warned not
once but repeatedly'' about the possible effect of alcohol on
pregnancy, he said. ``A warning on a bottle label would not have
done any good.''
   He also said he will prove that Michael's rate of development is
not much different from that of his older sister, and that his
condition is due to poor nutrition during pregnancy, heredity, and
severe neglect during his early years by parents who are admitted
alcoholics.
   In court documents, lawyers for Beam said, ``Beam does not
concede that maternal alcohol consumption causes birth defects.''
   An estimated 30,000 children are born each year nationwide with
fetal alcohol syndrome, according to a 1982 study by researchers at
the University of Washington's Alcohol and Drug Abuse Institute.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890425-0067 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-25-89 0914EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Britain-StadiumDisaster     04-25 0334</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Britain-Stadium Disaster,0343</SECOND>
<HEAD>Liverpool Leader Asks Royal Family To Attend Stadium Memorial</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Liverpool City Council leader today urged Queen
Elizabeth II or members of her immediate family to attend a
memorial service for the 95 soccer fans killed in Britain's worst
sports disaster.
   ``It is never too late to do the right thing,'' city council
leader Keva Coombes said on British Broadcasting Corp. radio. ``All
we can do is say we think you're making a mistake. Please, please
come.''
   The only members of Britain's royalty planning to attend
Saturday's service in Liverpool are the Duke and Duchess of Kent.
The duke, the queen's cousin, is president of the Football
Association.
   Buckingham Palace has said the queen and her husband will send a
representative, the Lord Lieutenant of Merseyside, Kenneth
Stoddart. A message from the queen will be read aloud by church
leaders conducting the service.
   Coombes, leader of Liverpool's Labor Party-controlled local
government, said the royal family is out of touch with ordinary
Britons.
   ``It looks as if their advisers are ... are starting to lose the
feel of ordinary men and women up and down the country, who are
very keen on the monarchy,'' he said.
   Britain's royal family also was criticized for failing to attend
a memorial service for the 270 people killed in the bombing of Pan
Am Flight 103.
   Coombes said either the queen, her husband or one of their
children should attend Saturday's service for Liverpool fans who
were crushed to death at a soccer match in Sheffield on April 15.
   Prince Charles, heir to the British throne, and his wife
Princess Diana visited the injured at a hospital in Sheffield.
Buckingham Palace said today that Charles would visit the Liverpool
Football Club next week.
   ``Everybody appreciates their going to the hospitals and
comforting those who are alive, but I think they need to listen a
bit more closely perhaps to ordinary men and women than some of
their advisers in London,'' Coombes said.
</TEXT>
