<SECOND>PM-Abortion-Jail Guards,0336</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jail Guards Say They Were Told to Get Abortions to Keep Jobs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN SHANAHAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two pregnant correction officers say a city
health official told them to have abortions or face losing their
jobs.
   The Department of Correction said the complaint resulted from a
misunderstanding, but the head of the correction officers' union
called Monday for the official's resignation.
   Phil Seelig, president of the Correction Officers' Benevolent
Association, charged that Leon Silverberg, director of the Health
Management Division of the Department of Correction, gave the
ultimatum last week to Livinia Forts, 21, and Alethea Hutchinson,
31. Both were hired March 2 and assigned to the department training
academy.
   Emily Steinberg, an attorney for the union, said an action
charging discrimination would be taken in federal court.
   Seelig said it ``appears to be part of a department conspiracy
to violate the civil and human rights of pregnant officers and
their babies in direct contradiction of the law.''
   Silverberg was out sick Monday and could not be reached for
comment. Correction Department spokeswoman Ruby Ryles called the
complaints a misunderstanding and said the circumstances were being
reviewed.
   Ms. Forts said that when she learned she was pregnant, she asked
to be excused from some strenuous exercises in gym class. She said
she was told to see Silverberg.
   ``He told me I had two options which are either to resign or to
have an abortion to continue my job,'' she said.
   ``I'm confused. I'm scared to work under these conditions,'' she
said. ``It felt like I don't have any rights at all. It's
horrible!''
   Mrs. Hutchinson, who has two daughters ages 9 and 13, said that
when she found out she was pregnant, she also was told to see
Silverberg.
   Silverberg ``told me I was to get an abortion or be fired,''
Mrs. Hutchinson said. She said Silverberg indicated he had given
similar advice to three other pregnant officers.
