<FIRST>r i PM-Philippines-Slaying     04-25 0449</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Philippines-Slaying,0465</SECOND>
<HEAD>Communist Leader Says Slaying U. S. Colonel Was Not Bad</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EILEEN GUERRERO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The founder of the outlawed
Philippine Communist Party said today the rebel slaying of a U.S.
colonel was justified because of American ``aggression'' in the
country.
   ``I think we cannot say that what happened was bad at all,''
Jose Maria Sison told a Manila radio station of the killing Friday
of Col. James ``Nick'' Rowe, 51, a Vietnam War hero and former
prisoner-of-war.
   Communist rebels have said they shot and killed Rowe. The
McAllen, Texas, man was ambushed en route to work at the Joint U.S.
Military Advisory Group headquarters.
   ``The United States continues with perpetuated aggression,''
Sison, who lives in the Netherlands, told independent radio DZXL.
   U.S. officials said Rowe's body will be flown to the United
States today, but they refused to give further details at the
request of his family.
   Military Chief of Staff Gen. Renato de Villa said Rowe's killing
adds a new dimension to the 20-year-old Communist insurgency.
   ``They are apparently targeting foreign nationals and that is a
new situation for all of us,'' de Villa told reporters. ``You
cannot win a war in the Philippines through assassination and
murder.''
   Defense Secretary Fidel Ramos charged the rebels are escalating
``their terror campaign'' because ``they have failed in their
military struggle'' against the Philippines armed forces.''
   He called on the public to rally behind the government so the
international community sees it can ``effectively take measures to
protect the population and also our foreign visitors.''
   Police chief Maj. Gen. Ramon Montano said police are more
interested in destroying the rebel capability for assassinations
than in arresting individual killers.
   ``It is immaterial whether we get the real hit men or not,''
Montano said. ``What is more important to us is the destruction of
their terror machinery. The Communist hit man can be anybody.''
   The United States maintains six military facilities in the
country, including Clark Air Base and Subic Bay Naval Base, both
north of Manila. The lease on the bases expires in 1991.
   Last Sunday, the Communist-led National Democratic Front urged
political parties to ally themselves with the front in its campaign
against the bases.
   ``I think it is preferable that a national alliance is created
to fight and oust the Americans from the bases,'' Sison told the
radio station.
   He founded the Communist Party in the Philippines in 1968 and
was arrested Nov. 10, 1977. He remained in jail until a month after
President Corazon Aquino took office in 1986. Sison then went
abroad and won political asylum in the Netherlands last year after
the military filed subversion charges against him.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
