<FIRST>r i PM-Poland-Popieluszko     04-25 0245</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Poland-Popieluszko,0255</SECOND>
<HEAD>A Killer of Pro-Solidarity Priest Freed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One of four security policemen convicted
of killing the pro-Solidarity priest Jerzy Popieluszko has been
freed from prison after four years, the government said today.
   Deputy government spokesman Zbyslaw Rykowski said Waldemar
Chmielewski was released, but said he did not know when he left
prison.
   Chmielewski's sentence _ which has been reduced twice _ was to
expire the third week in April.
   He was sentenced to 14 years' jail in February 1985 for his part
in the 1984 kidnapping and murder of Popieluszko, a Roman Catholic
priest who fervently supported the independent trade union that was
banned by authorities at the time.
   Popieluszko's body was recovered from the Vistula river
northwest of Warsaw.
   The other officers received longer sentences and a court upheld
the verdicts during a 1985 appeal.
   However, Chmielewski's sentence later was reduced twice, most
recently in 1987 when the Supreme Court cut his prison term to four
years on humanitarian grounds.
   The sentences of the other three killers also have been reduced
sharply.
   Popieluszko has become a symbol of Solidarity's struggle and his
grave at the Warsaw church where he served has become a pilgrimage
site for Poles and foreigners.
   This weekend, Solidarity leader Lech Walesa laid flowers on the
grave to mark the priest's name day.
   Solidarity was suppressed when martial law was declared in
December 1981, and outlawed the following October. It was legalized
earlier this month.
</TEXT>
