<FIRST>r i PM-Israel     04-25 0605</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Israel,0627</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two Alleged Collaborators Reported Killed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By G.G. LaBELLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Palestinian attackers today stabbed to death
two Arabs accused of collaborating with Israeli authorities in the
occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip, Arab reports said.
   The deaths were the latest of several recent attacks on alleged
collaborators. Underground leaders of the Palestinian uprising had
called for Wednesday to be a day of vengeance against Arabs aiding
the Israelis.
   Army officials said they were unaware of the two deaths.
   Three Palestinians were reported shot and wounded in clashes
with soldiers today, one in the West Bank city of Hebron, another
in the Gaza Strip city of Khan Yunis and a third in Gaza's Shati
refugee camp.
   Seven children between the ages 8 and 14 also were struck with
rubber-coated metal pellets in confrontations with troops in Khan
Yunis and Gaza City, Arab reports and hospital officials said.
   The army said it was checking the reports.
   In the West Bank town of Suseya, Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir
urged Israeli Jews to keep settling the occupied lands. The
government said Foreign Minister Moshe Arens would visit the United
States next month to give details of Shamir's plan to hold
Palestinian elections in the territories occupied in the 1967
Middle East war.
   In Khan Yunis, Fauzi Muhareb, 45, was fatally stabbed near his
home early today, Palestinian reporters said.
   The reporters, who requested anonymity for their own safety,
said Muhareb was a collaborator and a drug dealer. Israel radio
said police arrested three suspects.
   In the West Bank city of Nablus, the body of a 21-year-old
Palestinian who was beaten and fatally stabbed was brought to a
hospital. The victim, identified as Azam Qadi, was described as a
collaborator by Palestinian sources.
   In a leaflet issued nearly two weeks ago, the Unified National
Leadership of the Uprising called for Wednesday to be ``a day of
accounting for the collaborators.''
   Within the past week, at least five alleged collaborators were
reported killed in the occupied lands.
   The latest deaths would bring to 24 the number of Palestinians
slain as alleged collaborators this year, in addition to 11 last
year, Palestinian sources say.
   Not counting the two reported deaths today, 444 Palestinians
have been killed in the uprising, most by army gunfire during
stone-throwing clashes. Eighteen Israelis also have been killed.
   Israel radio reported today that uprising leaders called for the
rape of Palestinian women as a way of forcing their husbands to
stop working in Israel. It said the threat had been carried out
against six Gaza women.
   But Brig. Gen. Zvi Poleg, Israel Defense Force commander in the
Gaza Strip, said he had no reports of sexual assault in connection
with the revolt.
   Shamir, speaking at the dedication of a new archaeological park
aimed at luring more tourists to the West Bank, said Israelis would
settle in all regions where Jews once lived.
   ``In every place where Jews ever set foot in past generations,
the Jewish people shall return,'' Shamir told 4,000 people in
Suseya in the Judean desert.
   Shamir's visit to the occupied lands comes as he tries to win
U.S. support for his Middle East peace plan.
   Washington has been trying to get Shamir to halt Jewish
settlement in the occupied territories, where about 70,000 settlers
live amid 1.7 million Palestinians.
   A Foreign Ministry spokesman said Arens would travel to
Washington in mid-May to discuss the plan further. The plan
includes proposals to hold elections in the occupied lands and
improve conditions for Palestinian refugees.
   Shamir rejects any PLO participation in the negotiations and the
U.S. ``land for peace'' formula.
</TEXT>
