<FIRST>r i PM-Britain-Thatcher     04-25 0355</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Britain-Thatcher,0369</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Prime Minister Heath ``Affronted'' At Defeat By A Woman</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release at noon EDT</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Prime Minister Edward Heath, whom Margaret
Thatcher ousted as Conservative Party leader in 1975, felt
affronted at being defeated by a woman, a former deputy prime
minister said in a television interview released today.
   Lord Whitelaw, who was deputy prime minister until retiring last
year, said Heath also felt betrayed by the party. He spoke on a
British Broadcasting Corp. program about him titled, ``The Power
Behind the throne,'' which is to be broadcast Wednesday.
   Whitelaw said he, too, was ``desperately upset'' when Mrs.
Thatcher defeated Heath and he doubted that a woman could lead a
political party or be prime minister.
   ``That is a dreadful male chauvinist remark, but it had never
happened before,'' Whitelaw said. ``So I had these questions in my
mind. Was the country ready to vote for a woman as a leader? Would
she have the strength of purpose? ... Would she be able to control
a whole lot of men in a Cabinet?''
   ``That makes one laugh today but it was true then,'' Whitelaw
said.
   Mrs. Thatcher ousted Heath after he lost two consecutive
elections. She became prime minister when the Conservative Party
won power again in 1979.
   In the leadership contest, Mrs. Thatcher outpolled Heath in a
first ballot among Conservative members of Parliament. Heath
withdrew, Whitelaw joined the contest in the second ballot and she
defeated him, too.
   Whitelaw, 70, became a trusted Thatcher supporter, serving in
her Cabinets and being made a peer in 1983. He was deputy prime
minister until he quit after suffering a stroke last year.
   In contrast, Heath, 72, is an embittered rank-and-file
legislator who periodically attacks Mrs. Thatcher publicly.
   Whitelaw described Heath's attitude as ``strange and sad.''
   ``But I think Ted felt desperately and totally betrayed by the
party,'' said Whitelaw.
   ``So this rather shy, rather withdrawn man, felt deeply
affronted,'' said Whitelaw. ``Certainly he would mind more than
most people who had been beaten by a woman. Most men wouldn't like
it, but I think he minded more.''
</TEXT>
