<DOCNO> AP890425-0076 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-25-89 1003EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-GingrichBook     04-25 0761</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Gingrich Book,760</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gingrich Book Partnership Reported Tax Loss Of More than $100,000</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID PACE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The partnership created in 1984 to promote a
book co-authored by House Republican Whip Newt Gingrich reported a
loss of more than $100,000 during its first five years, according
to partnership tax returns released today by Gingrich.
   The COS Limited Partnership was formed by 21 individuals or
corporations that each put up $5,000 to pay for a promotional
campaign for ``Window of Opportunity,'' written by Gingrich, his
wife, Marianne Gingrich, and David Drake. One person, Janet Morris,
received a $5,000 share of the partnership for editorial work.
   The partnership is the subject of a formal complaint filed with
the House ethics committee by Rep. Bill Alexander, D-Ark., accusing
Gingrich of 10 apparent violations of House rules. The committee
has not indicated whether it will launch a preliminary
investigation of Alexander's complaint.
   Gingrich initiated the investigation that resulted in the filing
of 69 ethics charges against House Speaker Jim Wright last week.
   Gingrich has denied any wrongdong in connection with the book
deal.
   He released several hundred pages of documents today identifying
the 21 partners and detailing the organization's finances and
incorporation history. The documents, including the partnership's
tax returns for 1984-1988, were released in response to questions
submitted by news organizations.
   The partnership agreement with the book's publisher provided
that the partnership would get half of the publisher's profits in
exchange for promoting the book.
   But despite the partnership's expenditure of $51,571 to
advertise and promote the book from 1984 through 1986, the
publisher reported to Gingrich and his wife in 1988 that there was
a net loss of $6,259 on the book.
   The 1988 accounting from the publisher showed that 58,996 copies
of the book were sold to bookstores, but 29,981 of those copies
were returned. Net sales of the book totaled $122,120.
   Because the partnership received no profits from the book sales,
the $104,185 loss it generated between 1984 and 1988 was
distributed among the partners, providing them with tax writeoffs.
   Mrs. Gingrich, as general partner of the partnership, received a
$10,000 payment in 1984 for her work in setting up the
organization, and later was given a 2 percent interest in the
partnership for her work, according to the documents. She did not
invest any of her own money in the partnership.
   In written responses to questions from reporters, Mrs. Gingrich
said she also received a recent $1,500 payment from the partnership
``for part of the work I have done since the partnership was
formed.''
   ``I have worked hard in organizing and running this
partnership,'' Mrs. Gingrich said.``I have been paid for my work
and my legal responsibilities. According to the partnership
agreement, I am entitled to more than I have been paid so far.''
   Alexander's complaint alleges in part that the payments and
ownership interest in the partnership that Mrs. Gingrich received
were gifts that violated House rules limiting gifts that members
may receive.
   The complaint also alleged that because of the unusual nature of
the partnership promotional deal, the royalties Gingrich and his
wife received from the book do not fit the definition of royalties
in House rules and thus constitute a violation of House limits on
outside income.
   According to the documents released by Gingrich, he and his wife
each received $7,018 in royalties from the publisher. Under the
agreement with the publisher, the three authors received a total 10
percent royalty on hardback sales and 8 percent on paperbacks.
   While the documents identify the 22 partners in the book
promotional deal, Gingrich did not respond to questions about
whether he had intervened with any agency of the federal government
in behalf of any of the investors.
   The 21 investors were Richmond N. Aggrey of Peachtree City, Ga.;
Bigard Oil and Manufacturing Co. of Newton, Ill.; Joe Coors of
Golden, Colo.; Jeanne R. Ferst of Atlanta; Richard A. Guthman Jr.
of Atlanta; Robert H. Krieble of Old Lyme, Conn.; Roger Milliken of
Spartanburg, S.C.; O.D. Resources Inc. of Atlanta; Gregor Peterson
of Incline Village, Nev.; Roger Schoerner of Carrollton, Ga.;
Marguerite Williams of Thomasville, Ga.;
   John M. Barrell of Peachtree City, Ga.; Howard H. Calloway of
Denver, Colo.; Joel H. Cowan of Peachtree City, Ga.; Flowers
Industries of Thomasville, Ga.; Jean Hails of Roswell, Ga.; Estate
of William F. McClain, College Park, Ga.; Janet Morris, Mashpee,
Mass.; Diane Parker of Thomasville, Ga.; James C. Richards of
Carrollton, Ga.; Thomas E. Tidwell of Douglasville, Ga.; and Thomas
L. Williams III of Thomasville, Ga.
