<FIRST>r i PM-Germany-Missiles     04-25 0358</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Germany-Missiles,0369</SECOND>
<HEAD>West Germany Insists On Superpower Talks On Short-Range Weapons</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   West Germany said today it was
sticking with its demand for superpower talks on short-range
nuclear weapons despite Washington's refusal to begin such
negotiations.
   Foreign Minister Hans-Dietrich Genscher also said West Germany
would be speaking with other NATO partners about the internal
alliance dispute over the short-range weapons.
   ``We are going into the talks with our partners with the same
position that we have already worked out,'' Genscher told reporters.
   Genscher and Defense Minister Gerhard Stoltenberg had just
returned from Washington, where they tried to convince U.S.
officials of the need to take up early talks with the Soviets on
reducing short-range nuclear weapons.
   The United States and Britain are concerned that negotiating the
missiles issue with the Soviets could lead to stripping the NATO
allies of their ground-based nuclear weaponry, leaving them at the
mercy of stronger Warsaw Pact conventional forces.
   Most of the North Atlantic Treaty Organization's short-range
nuclear weapons _ 88 Lance launchers with a range of up to about 75
miles _ are based in West Germany.
   West Germany also is opposed to U.S. proposals to upgrade the
Lance missiles. The issues are expected to be at the forefront of
the NATO summit in Brussels at the end of May.
   West Germany's support for talks on the short-range weapons
comes amid a growing anti-military mood among the populace and
predictions that Chancellor Helmut Kohl could lose next year's
elections.
   The missiles are a subject of irritation in West Germany.
Because of their short range, the nuclear-tipped missiles are
designed to hit targets almost exclusively on German soil.
   Genscher said his talks with U.S. officials had resulted in a
``better understanding'' of the positions of both sides, but he
gave no indication there would soon be a breakthrough in attempts
to resolve the dispute.
   Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher of Britain will fly to Bonn on
Sunday to try to persuade Kohl to suspend his campaign for
U.S.-Soviet negotiations on the issue.
   Kohl has support among several of the smaller NATO countries,
including Norway, Belgium, the Netherlands and Denmark.
</TEXT>
