<HEAD>Police Look For Links Between Remains, Serial Killings</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MARION, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police were examining evidence from
skeletal remains found along a highway to see if it fits the
pattern of a serial killer or killers believed to have slain at
least eight women in the area.
   The remains were found Monday by state workers clearing brush
along Interstate 195, about 12 miles east of Dartmouth, where
bodies of four of the eight victims were found, also along the
highway.
   ``The parallels are there,'' said John Corbett, assistant
district attorney for Plymouth County. ``It's certainly reasonable
to make the assumption that there is some connection between them.''
   James Martin, a spokesman for Ronald Pina, Bristol County
district attorney, said a brief examination of the scene in Marion
indicated there were ``exact, numerous similarities'' between the
eight victims and Monday's discovery.
   Corbett would not say whether the body was that of a male or
female, and added that officials were not able to determine whether
it was a homicide. An autopsy was to be done today.
   Three other victims were found along Route 140 in Freetown, and
the eighth was found along Route 88 in Westport. The three
locations, all within a 10-mile radius, are in Bristol County;
Marion is in Plymouth County.
   The eight dead women had ties to Weld Square, an area of New
Bedford associated with prostitution and drugs.
   Police have said that as many as three missing women may be
additional victims.
