<FIRST>r i PM-Lebanon 1stLd-Writethru a0496 04-25 0651</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lebanon, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0496,0669</SECOND>
<HEAD>Christian, Syrian Forces Resume Heavy Bombardment</HEAD>
<HEAD>INSERTS 4 grafs after 6th pvs, ``The Syrians ...'' to UPDATE with
shelling details. DELETES 7th to trim. Picks up 8th, ``On Monday ...''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RIMA SALAMEH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Christian army units and Syrian gunners
poured rocket and artillery fire on Beirut in an escalation of
violence today, the eve of an Arab League meeting aimed at ending
the fighting.
   Police said at least two people were killed and 16 wounded in
the bombardment, which began at midnight and raged until 6 a.m.,
then dwindled to sporadic exchanges.
   The deaths raised to 272 killed and 991 wounded the toll since
the latest round of fighting broke out March 8 in the 14-year-old
civil war that pits Christians against Moslems.
   The city shook as army troops under Gen. Michel Aoun fired 155mm
and 130mm howitzer and mortar shells into Moslem west Beirut. The
only sound other than the blasts of shells was the occasional siren
of a Civil Defense ambulance.
   Civilians scurried to basements and underground shelters.
   The Syrians opened up on east Beirut, the heart of the besieged
310-square-mile Christian enclave, with 240mm mortars and BM-21
launchers, which fire 40 122mm rockets in 20 seconds.
   Four shells crashed in the garden of east Beirut's Comfort
Hotel, which houses offices of U.N. peacekeepers and the U.N.
Relief and Works Agency, police said. Windows were shattered and
windshields of five U.N. cars were blown out, the hotel and a U.N.
official said.
   Shells destroyed the facade of the three-story Goethe Institute,
a West German cultural center in west Beirut.
   Police said west Beirut's Sahel hospital on the main airport
highway took several direct hits that damaged equipment but hurt no
patients.
   On Monday, Moslem forces fired rockets at a French tanker as it
delivered fuel to restart power stations, police reported. Much of
Lebanon, including Beirut, has been without electricity since fuel
for power stations' generators ran out nine days ago.
   Police said four rockets crashed into the Mediterranean about
700 yards from the French navy tanker, the Penhors, as it unloaded
4,000 tons of fuel in the Christian town of Zouk north of Beirut.
   The salvo was fired despite what Christian officers called
``solid guarantees'' given to French Ambassador Paul Blanc by
Christian and Syrian commanders that there would be no shooting
while the tanker unloaded.
   The delivery of the fuel oil caused an interruption in the
stream of refugees fleeing Beirut from the Christian-controlled
port of Jounieh north of the city. An aide to Aoun said he ordered
two Cypriot-flag ferries to stop picking up Christians while the
Penhors unloaded.
   Foreign ministers of the 22-member Arab League are to meet in an
emergency session in Tunis, Tunisia, on Wednesday to find ways to
end the violence. Three cease-fires arranged by the league have
collapsed.
   An Arab League committee will recommend that the group send an
observer force of people from all Arab states to monitor a
cease-fire, said Kuwait's foreign minister, Sheik Sabah al-Ahmed.
   The current fighting erupted after Aoun, who heads the Christian
government vying for legitimacy with a rival Moslem cabinet,
clamped a blockade on illegal ports run by Moslem militias south of
Beirut in a bid to restore long-eroded state authority.
   The Druse Progressive Socialist Party retaliated by shelling the
Christian enclave. They soon were joined by the Syrians, who
maintain 40,000 troops in Lebanon under a 1976 Arab League
peacekeeping mandate.
   ``The observer force will not be a deterrent one, but rather a
symbolic force assigned to oversee a cease-fire,'' Sabah said in
Kuwait.
   The truce would be an interim step aimed at stabilizing the
situation in Lebanon until a political solution is worked out, with
provisions for arranging presidential elections and the formation
of a a coalition government.
   Syria has said it will attend the Arab League meeting.
</TEXT>
