<FILEID>AP-NR-04-25-89 1023EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-India-ColdFusion     04-25 0320</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-India-Cold Fusion,0332</SECOND>
<HEAD>Indian Scientsts Duplicate Cold Fusion Experiment</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BHAGWAN SINGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KALPAKKAM, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Scientists at an Indian laboratory have
achieved nuclear fusion in an electrolytic cell, a process first
reported by two University of Utah researchers in March, an Indian
researcher said.
   The experiment at the Indira Gandhi Center for Atomic Research
in this city on the Bay of Bengal 40 miles south of Madras differs
slightly from the Utah work.
   Cherian K. Mathews said in an interview that he and two
associates achieved the ``cold fusion'' April 16 after three days
of experiments.
   He said the team used titanium cathode and platinum anode dipped
in so-called heavy water, which contains a form of hydrogen called
deuterium that has a neutron in its nucleus. The Utah researchers
had used a cathode made of a palladium, a highly expensive element,
to achieve cold fusion.
   Cold fusion aims at getting the deuterium atoms to fuse, forming
helium and releasing energy.
   The reaction occurs at room temperature and hence is called cold
fusion. Previously fusion had been achieved under extremely high
temperature and pressure, as seen in the core of the sun.
   Mathews said his team experimented with ordinary water and heavy
water. He said there was a significant increase in temperature
(heat) during the experiment with heavy water, as compared to
ordinary water.
   That suggests that the reaction involved nuclear processes, such
as fusion, rather than chemical processes. Heavy water and ordinary
water are chemically identical.
   The team did not measure the energy output. But Mathews said
they had rough estimates of energy during the different
experiments. He did not give details.
   The team also noticed an increase in the number of neutrons
emitted but these could not be reproduced at will, he said.
   Mathews, 50, said he had worked with India's Atomic Energy
Department after receiving a doctorate from McMaster University in
Hamilton, Ontario.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890425-0082 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-25-89 1038EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Scotus-Lotteries     04-25 0396</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Lotteries,390</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Tosses Out Dispute Over Lotteries in Minnesota Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court, by a 6-3 vote, today tossed
out a dispute over the federal government's power to ban newspapers
from publishing lists of winners in privately run lotteries.
   The justices ruled that a controversy from Minnesota has become
moot because the government no longer intends to enforce the ban.
   ``We conclude that there is no longer any live controversy on
the issue of whether the (challenged) statute is constitutional as
it applies to prize lists, and that this appeal is moot,'' the
court said in an unsigned opinion.
   Justices Byron R. White and Thurgood Marshall cast dissenting
votes but did not explain why.
   Justice John Paul Stevens, in a brief dissenting opinion, said
the court should have reversed _ not merely set aside _ a federal
judge's ruling that had upheld the publishing ban.
   The Minnesota Newspaper Association originally challenged a
postal law that bars newspapers from carrying advertisements and
prize lists.
   Postal laws currently prohibit use of the mails to disseminate
information about any lottery not run by a state. Since nearly all
newspapers rely on the mail for at least a portion of their
distribution, the postal laws apply to them.
   But after the justices agreed last October to study the case,
Congress enacted a new law, to take effect in May 1990, dropping
the ban on advertising for private lotteries. The newspaper
association and the government agreed to drop that part of the case.
   Government lawyers then told the justices that the existing ban
on publishing prize winners will not be enforced.
   The dispute had focused on lotteries and other gaming, such as
bingo and raffles, sponsored by non-profit, charitable
organizations and others.
   Lawyers for the Minnesota newspapers said, ``The revenue
generated by charitable gaming is very substantial. In Minnesota
alone it appears to exceed $200 million per year.''
   U.S. District Judge Paul A. Magnuson upheld the ban on lottery
advertising even though he acknowledged that the ads are a
constitutionally protected form of commercial speech. The newspaper
association appealed.
   The judge, however, ruled that newspapers cannot be barred from
running lists of private lottery winners unless such lists are
found in advertisements. The government had appealed that part of
his ruling.
   The case is Frank vs. Minnesota Newspaper Association, 87-1956.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
