<FIRST>u i PM-Soviet-Protest     04-25 0463</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet-Protest,0478</SECOND>
<HEAD>Authorities Jail 25 In Sunday's Protest</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Moscow courts jailed 25 people and fined 18 who
took part in a protest against the violent crackdown on
demonstrators in the Soviet republic of Georgia, an activist said
today.
   Yuri Mityunov of the Democratic Union said in a telephone
interview that most of the jail sentences ranged from seven to 15
days, and that other protesters were fined between $160 and $480.
   They were arrested during a demonstration Sunday on Moscow's
Pushkin Square. The rally was called by the Democratic Union, which
bills itself as an alternative to the Communist Party.
   The official Soviet news agency Tass said Sunday that 47 people
were arrested, but the daily Moskovskaya Pravda reported today that
more than 70 people were arrested.
   In court cases completed by midday today, Moskovskaya Pravda
said, seven people were warned, 13 were fined and 15 received
administrative punishments. It did not specify what the
administrative punishments were, but many were likely to be brief
jail sentences handed out for violating rules of the Soviet
administrative code.
   In addition to the 25 jail sentences and 18 fines, Mityunov said
six people were warned and that it was uncertain what happened to
eight others. He said one resident of Kiev had been sent back to
the Ukrainian capital.
   There was no explanation for the discrepancies between
Mityunov's figures and those published by Moskovskaya Pravda.
   Thousands gathered at the square in central Moscow on Sunday
even though the demonstration was banned and authorities warned
they would arrest protesters.
   The rally lasted several hours and a special Interior Ministry
police force waded into the crowds to seize some protest leaders.
   Hundreds of people then marched about a mile from the square to
the Arbat pedestrian mall where they held a memorial meeting for
those killed in Georgia.
   Nineteen civilians were killed in a clash between soldiers and
demonstrators on April 9 in the Georgian capital, Tbilisi, and one
young man was later shot and killed for a curfew violation.
   Officials in Moscow condemned the crackdown and the party
leaders in the republic were ousted and replaced. Officials
revealed that some of the victims of the clashes were killed by a
gas used against demonstrators.
   In Tbilisi, the Georgian minister of health pledged today to
pressure military authorities to reveal the type of gas used.
   Irakli Managarishvili told reporters an investigation by
military prosecutors into charges a poisonous gas was used was
ordered by Foreign Minister Eduard A. Shevardnadze.
   Doctors say some gas victims are suffering from paralysis of the
central nervous systems.
   Several dozen of the approximately 105 patients still
hospitalized in the Georgian capital after inhaling the gas signed
a letter Monday to President Mikhail S. Gorbachev appealing for an
antidote.
</TEXT>
