<HEAD>Hijacker Blows Himself Up After Failing to Force Plane to Taiwan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A hijacker with explosives strapped to his back
blew himself up after failing to force a domestic Chinese airliner
carrying 50 people to fly to Taiwan, a Chinese news agency reported
today.
   The China News Service said two passengers were injured in the
explosion during Monday's attempted hijacking on a flight from
Ningbo in Zhejiang province to Xiamen in the neighboring eastern
province of Fujian.
   Ningbo is about 490 miles north of Xiamen.
   It said the hijacker, who was carrying a pass from the
journalism department of a university, stabbed an airline hostess
in the hand before charging into the cockpit and demanding to be
flown to Taiwan.
   The pilot fooled the hijacker by flying around before landing in
the city of Fuzhou in Fujian, it added. Fuzhou is 260 miles south
of Mingbo.
   It said the hijacker then blew himself up.
   It said the aircraft, carrying 44 passengers and six crew
members, belonged to the Shanghai Eastern Airlines but gave no
other details about the plane.
   China's last hijacking came in May, when two Chinese used a toy
gun and fake explosives to force a jetliner to fly from Xiamen to
an air base in Taiwan.
   Taiwan gave political asylum to the two and let the plane fly
back to China five hours later. The two hijackers were later
sentenced to 3{ years in prison.
