<FIRST>r i PM-Britain-Airports     04-25 0227</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Britain-Airports,0234</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Announces New Security At British Airports</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Transport Secretary Paul Channon has announced
improved airport security measures following the bombing of Pan Am
Flight 103.
   He told Parliament on Monday the measures include examination of
radios and computers and planned use of a thermal neutron analysis
machine for bomb detection at Heathrow and Gatwick airports. More
airport security inspectors would be employed and the government
would give more money for research into detecting explosives.
   Channon said he would discuss the thermal neutron analysis
machine being developed by the U.S. Federal Aviation Authority in
talks this week with U.S. Transportation Secretary Samuel Skinner.
   British press reports say the machines cost $850,000 each.
   Channon said under the new measures, all hold baggage on high
risk flights is being screened and aircraft design changes are
being carried out to make it more difficult to hide arms or
explosives.
   ``This package represents a concerted effort to tighten up
security. The aim is to give passengers and air crew a high level
of security,'' Channon told reporters later.
   New York-bound Flight 103 blew up over Lockerbie, Scotland, on
Dec. 21, 1988, killing all 259 people aboard and 11 on the ground.
The flight originated in Frankfurt, West Germany, changing planes
at Heathrow. Investigators say a bomb in a portable radio in the
hold destroyed the plane.
</TEXT>
