<FIRST>r a PM-ANPA-Technology     04-25 0314</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-ANPA-Technology,0321</SECOND>
<HEAD>Knight-Ridder Exec Says Industry Needs To Take Advantage of Technology</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Newspapers should take advantage of technology to
stay close to their readers, Knight-Ridder Inc. President James K.
Batten told publishers gathered today for the American Newspaper
Publishers Association convention.
   Batten, chief executive officer of Miami-based Knight-Ridder,
said, ``If newspapers are going to be as successful in the future
as they've been in the past, we have to be much more zealous about
getting close to our customers and staying there. Technology can
help us do that.
   ``Used intelligently, the telephone and the computer can let us
recreate the kind of personal relationships that newspapers had
with their customers 20 or 25 years ago.''
   For example, he said, the Providence (R.I.) Journal-Bulletin
uses a voice service to offer telephone recordings of soap opera
updates, publishing a daily access code for readers to call. The
Journal reported more than 20,000 calls a month. In Colorado, the
Boulder Daily Camera gets more than 77,000 calls a month on a
system that offers recordings of sports scores and stories.
   The call-in systems are relatively inexpensive, requiring little
more than a personal computer, phone lines and tape recordings,
Batten said during a session on the convention's second day. It
ends Wednesday.
   In addition, the industry has little choice but to change in
dealing with the aging of the baby-boom generation, an increase in
two-income households and the growing cultural diversity of the
U.S. population, he said.
   ``These are threats, not to our existence but to our pricing
flexibility, to our ability to finance the news coverage that our
communities deserve and that we want to provide,'' Batten said.
   ``We can respond to those threats ... we can do that by using
technology to take some modest steps that will bring us closer to
the customer who keeps our business going _ the reader.''
</TEXT>
