<HEAD>Transportation Secretary's Flight Linked With Fatal Crash</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Investigators are trying to determine if there
was any connection between the crash of a student pilot coming in
for a landing and the almost simultaneous clearing for takeoff of a
plane carrying Transportation Secretary Samuel Skinner.
   Carol Ann Reiser, 33, of suburban Itasca, was killed April 15 at
Du Page County Airport, west of Chicago. Her single-engine Cessna
152 plunged to the ground about 580 feet short of the runway as she
was practicing landings.
   Skinner's plane, a government Beechcraft King Air 90, was
cleared for takeoff at the same time on the same runway, officials
revealed Monday.
   The same controller, who was in training, gave the clearances to
both aircraft, said Michael Benson, a spokesman for the National
Transportation Safety Board, which is conducting the investigation.
   ``Our preliminary reading of the air-traffic control tapes is
that the messages to both planes were virtually simultaneous,'' he
said.
   Investigators are trying to learn if the back-to-back orders
were an error that contributed to the Cessna crash, or if the pilot
simply lost control of her airplane.
   Investigators have reported no evidence of mechanical failure of
the Cessna.
   Officials said witnesses have provided conflicting reports on
the position of Skinner's plane when the Cessna went down.
   Some say Skinner's aircraft was in a holding position waiting to
take off. Others say it was already airborne.
   Skinner, who had visited Chicago for press interviews and to
attend the baseball home opener of the White Sox, was heading for a
meeting in St. Louis at the time of the accident.
