<FIRST>u w PM-S&amp;Ls 1stLd-Writethru a0427 04-25 0589</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-S&amp;Ls, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0427,600</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gonzalez Offers S&amp;L Bill with Stricter Capital Requirements</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDs: SUBS lead and DELETES 8th graf pvs, In one, to CORRECT by removing
statement that Gonzalez proposing to include subordinated debt in core
capital</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House Banking Committee is considering a
proposal from its chairman that would force savings and loan owners
to back their lending with more of their own capital.
   According to a draft document circulated among committee members
and obtained Monday by The Associated Press, Rep. Henry B.
Gonzalez, D-Texas, is offering a plan with moderately stricter
capital requirements than the bill passed earlier this month by the
subcommittee on financial institutions, chaired by Rep. Frank
Annunzio, D-Ill.
   Gonzalez' committee is scheduled to hold its first public
session on the bill Wednesday, after a private meeting of committee
Democrats today.
   Both Gonzalez' plan and the subcommittee's bill include a
risk-based formula for capital that offers a break to S&amp;Ls making
low-risk loans such as home mortgages.
   But the Gonzalez proposal would require most S&amp;Ls to maintain a
somewhat higher base of ``tangible'' or ``real money'' capital,
which includes cash and assets readily convertible to cash.
   The subcommittee's bill provides for a base of tangible capital
of $1.50 for every $100 in loans, while another $1.50 could consist
of ``goodwill,'' an intangible asset representing the value of an
institution's customer loyalty and name recognition. Together, they
amount to ``core'' capital of 3 percent.
   Gonzalez' plan also provides for core capital of 3 percent, but
it's tougher on goodwill, allowing it make up only one fourth,
rather than one half, of the core.
   Both the Gonzalez and subcommittee legislation represent
advances over current rules, which do not require owners to put up
any real money if they have enough goodwill and subordinated debt _
money S&amp;Ls borrow _ on their books.
   As of the end of 1988, goodwill was the biggest loophole,
accounting for a third of the industry's $60 billion in capital.
Subordinated debt amounts to about $4 billion.
   S&amp;L industry critics are targeting goodwill because it cannot be
sold when an institution closes.
   The subcommittee bill would allow S&amp;Ls to maintain goodwill on
their books, in some cases for as long as 40 years. Gonzalez would
eliminate it in 20 years. The Bush administration had wanted to get
rid of it in 10 years.
   The Gonzalez' plan is also stricter with risky activities
conducted in S&amp;L subsidiaries, such as investment in commercial
real estate and junk bonds. It gives S&amp;Ls five years to come up
with extra capital to back the subsidiaries, while the subcommittee
plan doesn't require extra capital.
   In another change, Gonzalez would move back the deadline for
complying with the new capital rules, from the June 1, 1990, target
in the subcommittee bill to the June 1, 1991, originally proposed
by President Bush.
   Rep. Jim Leach of Iowa, one of the top-ranking Republicans on
the House Banking Committee, is pressing for even stricter capital
requirements, calling the 1.5 percent tangible rule ``absolutely
utterly insane.''
   ``We have made a prescription for repetition of the problem and
I think the country ought to be alarmed,'' Leach told a National
Press Club forum.
   The Senate voted 91-8 to approve its version of S&amp;L legislation
last week.
   Bush, praising the vote in a speech in Chicago to the annual
meeting of The Associated Press, said, ``I urge the House to act
promptly, and pass this S&amp;L reform bill with its central provisions
intact.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890425-0096 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-25-89 1203EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-TransplantTherapy     04-25 0580</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Transplant Therapy,0595</SECOND>
<HEAD>Treatment Could Revolutionize Organ Transplants</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVE WILSTEIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>STANFORD, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A treatment that could revolutionize
organ transplants by overcoming the rejection of foreign tissue and
improving the quality of patients' lives is showing promising
results, researchers say.
   The treatment, which could eliminate the lifelong need for
highly toxic drugs to fight organ rejection by the body's immune
system, may be ready for human studies within three years, said Dr.
C. Garrison Fathman, Stanford University professor of medicine.
   The approach uses three doses of tailor-made, laboratory-grown
monoclonal antibodies before the transplant to temporarily
``blind'' the immune system and keep it from recognizing the new
organ as foreign tissue and attacking it.
   Rats given the treatment before receiving transplanted hearts
have survived for more than 200 days without signs of rejection and
without any anti-rejection drugs.
   Dr. Thomas Flavin, of the Stanford department of cardiovascular
surgery, was scheduled to present the findings today at the
International Society for Heart Transplantation meeting in Munich,
West Germany.
   Meanwhile, the first full year of mandatory reporting of organ
transplants by U.S. hospitals shows 12,798 of the procedures were
performed around the country in 1988, according to the national
transplant network.
   The statistics, released Monday, were compiled by the United
Network for Organ Sharing. Medical centers have been required since
Oct. 1, 1987, by federal law to report transplants to the
Virginia-based network.
   There were 9,123 kidney transplants, according to the network
data. There also were 1,680 liver transplants, 1,647 heart
transplants, 243 pancreas transplants, 74 heart-lung transplants
and 31 lung transplants. Twenty-one of the lung transplants
involved a full set of lungs and 10 involved single lungs.
   The monoclonal antibody treatment effectively paralyzed the rat
immune system by killing certain cells while surgeons implanted
hearts from donor rats into the abdomens of other rats with
mismatched tissue type, leaving the recipients' original hearts
intact.
   The drugs a patient must take to prevent the immune system from
attacking a transplanted organ also prevent the immune system from
attacking other harmful diseases. Patients then are susceptible to
infections and may suffer other problems related to the drugs'
toxicity.
   The antibody treatment takes a new approach to the problem by
creating a ``transient window of immunosuppression,'' said
co-research, Dr. Judith Shizuru.
   The antibody wipes out the specific type of white blood cells,
called CD4 T lymphocytes, that lead the attack on the foreign
organ, she said. But only mature cells are killed. Immature T cells
are protected inside the thymus gland and begin repopulating in the
body a few weeks after the transplant.
   ``We're sort of fooling the immune system for awhile,'' Fathman
said.
   ``We're wiping the blackboard clean by removing the (mature) T
cells that have not yet come into contact with the foreign antigen,
in this instance the transplant,'' he said.
   By transplanting the new organ at a time when those cells are
absent, the T cells repopulating from the immature cells in the
thymus apparently do not recognize the transplant as anything
except ``self,'' he said.
   When the T cells grew back, the immune system appeared to be
``blind'' to the foreign transplanted organ. But the T cells
maintained their ``memory'' and attacked other foreign tissue.
   ``If the same thing holds in man, and we can prove that
immunologic memory is not impaired by this type of immune
paralysis, then we would be very hopeful that this technique could
be readily applied to man,'' Fathman said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890425-0097 </DOCNO>
