<DOCNO> AP890425-0102 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-25-89 1229EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u n JXJXJX     04-25 0342</FIRST>
<SECOND>JX JX JX</SECOND>
<HEAD>PM-Nixon,320</HEAD>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Impeachment of Imprisoned Mississippi Judge Urged by Lawmakers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A House panel called today for the impeachment
of imprisoned U.S. District Judge Walter Nixon of Mississippi, who
has collected $286,000 in pay since his 1986 perjury trial and is
planning to return to the bench within months.
   ``His pattern of lies and deceit led ... to the inevitable
conclusion that he has to be impeached,'' Rep. Don Edwards,
D-Calif., said as the House Judiciary Committee approved three
articles of impeachment, 34-0.
   Floor action by the full House on the move to impeach the
Mississippi jurist could come as early as Wednesday.
   Nixon stands accused of lying to a federal grand jury and
Justice Department investigators and bringing the judiciary into
disrepute.
   The case centers on an oil and gas investment arranged for Nixon
by a wealthy businessman, Wylie Fairchild, and Nixon's alleged
intervention in marijuana smuggling charges against Fairchild's son.
   Nixon was sentenced in 1986 to two concurrent five-year
sentences for perjury after denying involvement in the marijuana
case. Since then, he has collected $286,000 in judicial salary,
authorities say. They say he will be released within a matter of
months and plans to don his black robes again and resume his seat
on the bench.
   ``I believe that Judge Nixon should have had the good grace to
resign after his appeals were exhausted,'' Rep. James
Sensenbrenner, R-Wis., told the Judiciary Committee.
   Defense attorney David Stewart had said that some of the
statements cited as instances of perjury were factual, and that in
any case Nixon has done nothing serious enough to warrant
impeachment. He said Nixon was ``subjected to a sensationalized
investigation and an unfair trial.''
   In such cases, the House first votes on a bill of impeachment.
If it approves the bill, the judge is impeached and must stand
trial in the Senate.
   The Senate is currently preparing for a trial of U.S. District
Judge Alcee L. Hastings of Miami, who was impeached last year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890425-0103 </DOCNO>
