<FIRST>r i AM-Flight103     04-25 0249</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Flight 103,0255</SECOND>
<HEAD>Marathon Race to Lockerbie Gets Under Way</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 500-mile road race got under way before dawn
Tuesday to honor those killed aboard Pan Am Flight 103 and to draw
attention to a campaign for a U.S. congressional inquiry into the
disaster.
   The race by four marathon runners, to be held in stages between
London and the Scottish village of Lockerbie, began outside the
Houses of Parliament and is due to end Sunday.
   A bomb blew apart the New York-bound Pan Am jumbo jet over
Scotland on Dec. 21, killing 270 people.
   Organizers said the race is being held in memory of the victims
and to focus attention on their relatives' campaign for a
congressional inquiry and for improved security at airports.
   Two U.S. runners, French-born circus clown Yves Pol, 35, and Tom
Grace, 48, of New York, are competing against Malcolm Campbell, 55,
of Scotland, and Eleanor Adams, 41, of Britain.
   They ran 26 miles Tuesday to Hemel Hempstead northwest of
London, then set out from nearby Leighton Buzzard for Oakham 62
miles away in central England.
   On Saturday, they will race around Glasgow's Ibrox Stadium
during the halftime break in a soccer game between Glasgow Rangers
and Heart of Midlothian.
   They will be joined on the last five-miles to Lockerbie in
southwestern Scotland by Eleanor Bright, 32, whose husband died in
the crash. Nicholas Bright, also 32, had been returning to his
Brookline, Mass., home from a business trip to London.
</TEXT>
