<SECOND>PM-Lottery Fever, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0482,0513</SECOND>
<HEAD>High-Stakes Lottery Game Not Just for Pennsylvania Anymore</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS lead, 10th graf, `On Monday,' to UPDATE with jackpot hitting
$100 million; deletes 11th graf, `Lottery executive...' as outdated.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SHREWSBURY, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Even before Pennsylvania's Super 7
lottery jackpot hit $100 million today, the frenzy over a North
American record was getting to be a little too much for some state
residents.
   It's not the money they mind. It's the out-of-staters.
   ``Go home, Marylanders!'' one man shouted out his car window
Monday evening as he drove by the Case &amp; Keg in Shrewsbury, just
across the border from Maryland, where about 200 people waited in
line to buy $1 tickets.
   Would-be millionaires from Maryland, Virginia, Washington, D.C.,
Ohio, Kansas, New York and California joined the queues at the beer
distributorship, and at another store in Shrewsbury.
   The scene was repeated across the state as long lines and
traffic jams formed around ticket outlets ahead of Wednesday's
drawing.
   At Philadelphia International Airport, the ticket line was 30
deep at lunchtime.
   TWA pilot Bob Link flew from his home in Columbus, Ohio, to
Greater Pittsburgh International Airport to buy $25 worth of
tickets for himself and $86 for friends and relatives.
   ``Seventy million dollars gets your attention real quick,'' he
said, referring to an earlier estimate of the jackpot, ``and $83
million gets your attention even quicker.''
   The jackpot began reaching record proportions after six straight
drawings yielded no winning ticket. Last week's jackpot was for $46
million. Unclaimed, it grew to $62 million on Thursday and $70
million by the weekend.
   On Monday, lottery officials announced the drawing would be
worth at least $83 million, based on ticket sales. Lottery
spokesman Terry Murphy said today that the jackpot had risen to
$100 million.
   There was even an international flavor to the ticket-buying
spree.
   Bill Thwaites of Toronto, who was en route to Virginia, stopped
for tickets in Shrewsbury after hearing of the jackpot from friends
who live near Reading.
   ``It's been on the radio and TV up in Toronto, but I didn't know
the jackpot was this large,'' Thwaites said. ``I'm just buying a
few tickets, nothing extravagant.''
   Susan and Hans Lienhards, who recently returned from nine years
in Europe, took time off from house shopping to buy tickets.
   ``This is like a carnival, and people are having fun, talking
about what they would do with the money,'' Mrs. Lienhards said.
   The world's richest lottery jackpot was Spain's El Gordo, or
``the fat one,'' last December. The $159 million first prize was
split by hundreds of people.
   The largest U.S. jackpot to date was an Illinois prize of $69.9
million that was split by four players nearly two weeks ago. The
largest single U.S. lottery payout was $55.16 million won by a
Florida woman in her state's drawing in September.
   Super 7 players pick seven numbers out of a possible 80, having
a 1 in 9.6 million chance of selecting a winning ticket.
</TEXT>
