<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--India-Witch     04-25 0181</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--India-Witch,0191</SECOND>
<HEAD>Neighbors Kill Woman Suspected of Being a Witch</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CALCUTTA, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman suspected of being a witch was
dragged from her hut, tied to a tree and then axed to death by her
neighbors in an eastern India village, police said Tuesday.
   Sonamoni Kisku was killed Sunday by Ganesh Soren and his
brother, Meghraj, in Goaljoi, about 155 miles northwest of
Calcutta, police said.
   Ganesh Soren was arrested but his brother was at large,
according to Police Chief Satyan Pal.
   It was the latest in several killings of women suspected of
being witches in the predominantly tribal region of the state. The
Santhal tribes believe many women, especially widows, have the
power to heal the sick and cast evil spells.
   But Mrs. Kisku, 50, was married and had two sons, Pal said.
   He said Ganesh Soren believed Mrs. Kisku had cast an evil spell
on his 6-year-old daughter, who had been ill since January.
   State Chief Minister Jyoti Basu said at least 20 women were
killed in West Bengal in 1987 on suspicion of practicing witchcraft.
</TEXT>
