<FIRST>u a PM-SovietDefections 1stLd-Writethru a0468 04-25 0426</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet Defections, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0468,0433</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two Soviets Defect During Border Ceremony</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 7 grafs to UPDATE with Soviet, INS comment, quote
from Nome official; picks up 5th graf, `The Soviet delegation...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NOME, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Immigration officials were waiting today for
a break in bad weather to fly two asylum-seeking Soviets to
Anchorage from a Bering Strait island where they defected.
   The two sought political asylum on the island of Little Diomede
on Sunday, hours before officials signed a protocol aimed at easing
travel restrictions between Alaska and Siberia, the Immigration and
Naturalization Service said.
   INS officials in Nome gave the Soviets permission to stay on the
island, and they spent the night in a National Guard Armory there.
   The defectors were being kept under tight security, Jim
Stimpfle, a Nome Chamber of Commerce official who reached the
island before the weather turned bad, said today. ``Everything is
hush-hush. They've even got the armory windows blacked out with
ponchos or something.''
   Soviet officials are aware of the defections, but ``at this
point we have no comment,'' said Andre Dronov, a Soviet vice consul
in San Francisco.
   The men were reported missing when the Soviet delegation
prepared to leave the island by helicopter after a party following
the signing ceremony.
   INS District Director Gary Johnson said they were the first
Soviet defectors in his 10 years with the agency in Alaska. Their
asylum requests will go to the State Department for review before
the INS makes a decision.
   The Soviet delegation came to Little Diomede to sign the
protocol, which urged the U.S. and Soviet governments to approve a
border commission to handle visits by Eskimos between Alaska and
Siberia. Eskimos would not need visas to make the trip.
   Gov. Steve Cowper was supposed to take part in the ceremony
along with his counterpart from the Magadan region of Siberia. Fog
and blowing snow prevented Cowper from reaching the island, and the
ceremony was conducted by telephone.
   The ceremony was held in conjunction with the Bering Bridge
Expedition, a skiing and sled dog journey from Siberia to Alaska.
The expedition consists of six Soviets and six Americans. Two of
the Soviets and two of the Americans are Eskimos.
   Many Eskimo families were separated when the Soviets closed the
border in the Bering Strait at the onset of the Cold War in the
late 1940s.
   The Soviet island of Big Diomede, three miles from Little
Diomede, is a military installation. Eskimos who once lived there
were relocated to the Siberian mainland in the 1950s.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890425-0110 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-25-89 1324EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Tusks     04-25 0152</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Tusks,0156</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tanzanians Seize 127 Ivory Tusks, Arrest 4</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DAR ES SALAAM, Tanzania (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Anti-poaching officers in
southern Tanzania seized 127 elephant tusks worth $19,000 and
arrested four people, a news agency reported.
   The tusks were seized near Tanzania's southern border with
Mozambique while en route to the central Tanzanian town of Iringa,
west of the port city Dar es Salaam, according to the report Monday
by the state-run Shihata news agency. Shihata did not say when the
ivory was seized.
   Police said two suspects eluded capture.
   Tanzania banned trade in ivory in 1986, but poaching continues.
In the last 15 years, hunters, lured by ivory's soaring world
price, have reduced Tanzania's elephants by about one-third to an
estimated 100,000.
   Western wildlife officials say ethnic Somali tribespeople, or
Shiftas, hired by private businessmen and corrupt government
officials, are largely responsible for the slaughter of East
Africa's once flourishing elephant herds.
</TEXT>
