<FILEID>AP-NR-04-25-89 1330EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-ImprisonedWriters     04-25 0570</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Imprisoned Writers,0584</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Writers Honor Jailed Vietnamese Poet, African Woman</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY CHENAULT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   From prisons and re-education camps in Vietnam,
Nguyen Chi Thien wrote of despair, of loved ones and of dreams of
freedom.
   Through poetry, he found a way to let his thoughts escape from
``the swamplands'' where he spent nearly half his life.
   Human rights groups have conflicting reports on Thien's fate,
with some sources saying he died in jail and others suggesting he
remains imprisoned. His plight has drawn attention of writers
around the world, and now his works are part of an effort to
highlight the risks writers take to express themselves.
   On Wednesday, a U.S. chapter of the PEN organization, a leading
voice of international literary freedom, will honor Thien with one
of two Freedom-to-Write awards.
   The other writer to be honored at the PEN American Center
Montblanc Literary Gala is identified only as ``an anonymous
African woman.''
   ``The very thought that that person is unable to be identified
says so much about the importance of focusing attention on these
writers,'' said author John Irving, a member of PEN American Center.
   ``We can't even say which country in Africa she is from because
of the dangers she faces. That underlines the need for us to turn
to these heroic people as symbols in the fight against the harsh
treatment of writers in countries where people are a lot less free
to write.''
   In addition to $3,000 that the PEN American Center will send to
a friend or relative of each recipient, the group hopes to pressure
Vietnam with a written request for Thien's release and pleas from
prominent writers.
   Irving said freedom of expression is not just important to
writers:
   ``In a world where we have writers who are not free, who are
imprisoned and tortured for writing, what happens to the readers in
these societies?''
   He said promoting freedom of expression is especially important
this year because of the controversy over Salman Rushdie's novel,
``The Satanic Verses.'' The book, considered blasphemous by many
Moslems, ignited an international furor and led to calls for
censorship and for Rushdie's death.
   For Thien, imprisoned for 26 of his 55 years after opposing the
Communist government, pushing for literary freedoms and writing
articles critical of communism, poetry became a creative diversion
to help him survive prison hardships and the emotional torment of
captivity.
   According to reports from human rights groups, Thien burst into
the British Embassy in Hanoi in April 1979. He gave a staff member
a collection of poems and a letter asking that they be published.
Vietnamese guards arrested him.
   His poems have been translated into French and English, set to
music and compiled in a book titled ``Flowers From Hell,'' which
won the prestigious Rotterdam International Poetry Prize in 1985.
   ``When successful, it sounds like the depth of feelings from a
man who has endured much pain but continued to dream and to hope
for freedom,'' said Huynh Sanh Thong, who translated the poems into
English. Thong is director of Vietnamese Studies Projects at Yale
University, where the book was published.
   The London-based human rights group Amnesty International
received reports that Thien had died in 1986. But sources in
Southeast Asia have told Amnesty International since then that he
is alive. There also have been reports that he is suffering from
depression and is partially paralyzed.
</TEXT>
