<SECOND>AM-BRF--Elephants,0167</SECOND>
<HEAD>Four Squatters Killed by Hungry Elephants</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GWERU, Zimbabwe (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hungry elephants broke out of a game
reserve in search of food and killed four peasant squatters who
were tending crops, news reports said Tuesday.
   Families from the minority Tonga tribe recently settled and
planted crops on the edges of the Chirisa game reserve in the
Midlands, said Claudius Hove, the Department of National Parks and
Wildlife's chief warden in the province.
   In past weeks, they beat tribal drums to keep stray elephants
from their plots. Instead, the drumbeats attracted the animals,
Hove told the Zimbabwe Inter-African News Agency.
   ``These people have been settling in and around the game park
and the elephants have been increasingly attracted by crops in
their fields,'' Hove said.
   The settlers will be moved from the reserve and game rangers
will try to drive the stray elephants back into the park, he said.
If the animals don't budge, they will be shot, he added.
</TEXT>
