<FIRST>u a PM-PlaneDoorHearing 1stLd-Writethru a0488 04-25 0553</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Plane Door Hearing, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0488,0563</SECOND>
<HEAD>Probe Of 747 Accident Begins Without Key Piece Of Evidence</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 6 grafs to UPDATES with hearing beginning, statement
from Dickinson. Picks up 6th graf, `Investigators are...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NICHOLAS K. GERANIOS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal officials today opened a hearing aimed at
explaining how a cargo door was torn off a United Airlines jumbo
jet in February, killing nine passengers.
   National Transportation Safety Board Chairman Lee Dickinson
began the four-day hearing with a statement that the testimony
gathered would assist the NTSB in ``determining the probable cause
and in making any recommendations to prevent similar accidents.''
   But he said any conclusions would await a report issued later in
Washington, D.C.
   The Boeing 747's 800-pound, 9-foot-square forward lower cargo
hatch was left at the bottom of the Pacific Ocean after United
Flight 811 lost part of its fuselage shortly after takeoff from
Honolulu.
   The door was located 85 miles southwest of Honolulu and under
nearly 17,000 feet of water.
   Dickinson has said efforts may be made to raise the door, which
several experts say is the best chance of finding definitive
answers for the cause of the accident.
   Investigators are debating whether a Navy salvage mission this
summer would be essential and worth the high cost.
   Officials for United, the Boeing Co., the Federal Aviation
Administration, and unions representing airline pilots and
mechanics were expected to testify during the hearing.
   ``The board's full report will not be issued for several months,
but recommendations to prevent any recurrence could come at any
time,'' Dickinson said in a news release.
   The plane was bound for Sydney, Australia, with 337 passengers
and a crew of 18 on Feb. 24. At about 23,000 feet, the airplane
experienced an explosive decompression following the loss of the
cargo door.
   Nine people were sucked out, along with seats and luggage, when
the door and part of the aircraft fuselage were swept away.
   Though two engines conked out, pilot David Cronin managed to
land at Honolulu with no further loss of life.
   The 747-100 was one of the first jumbo jets built by
Seattle-based Boeing.
   The 13 people testifying were expected to discuss maintenance,
inspection procedures and practices, human factors and details of a
1987 incident in which the cargo door on a Pan Am 747 opened
slightly during a flight from London.
   There has been speculation the United cargo door may have broken
free in an explosive decompression when the latching mechanism
failed. Airline records indicated there had been recent problems
with the door before the accident, including a faulty door seal and
electrical problems requiring the door to be closed manually rather
than electrically on several occasions.
   The FAA on March 3 issued an emergency order requiring all U.S.
airlines to reinforce within 30 days the relatively lightweight
aluminum latch mechanisms with steel, so the doors would be less
vulnerable to damage caused by improper closing.
   The cargo bay door is hinged at the top so it closes downward,
with eight latching mechanisms along the bottom attached to the
plane's frame. It also has a latching mechanism and a hook pin on
each side.
   The United 747 remains at Hickam Air Force Base in Honolulu and
will be returned to service after repairs are completed.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
