<FIRST>u i AM-Lebanon     04-25 0614</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lebanon,0639</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fighting Escalates on Eve of Arab League Peace Talks</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos BEI1, ROM2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA ABU-NASR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Syrian gunners firing giant mortars
battled Christian forces in an ill-matched duel Tuesday that each
accused the other of starting in an effort to sabotage a new Arab
peace initiative.
   Police reported two people were killed and 16 wounded as
artillery and rockets pounded the Lebanese capital for six hours.
   The fighting shadowed a peacemaking effort by foreign ministers
of the 22-state Arab League, who are to meet Wednesday in Tunis.
   Christian leader Gen. Michel Aoun was reported to have accepted
a league proposal for 200 Arab observers to enforce and monitor a
cease-fire.
   But the plan was jolted when Justice Minister Nabih Berri
rejected having more foreign troops in Lebanon, where his staunch
ally, Syria, has 40,000 troops under a 1976 league peacekeeping
mandate.
   ``We don't need more armies,'' Berri said Tuesday.
   His remarks are seen as a rejection by proxy of the Arab plan
from Syria, Lebanon's main power broker.
   Berri's Shiite Moslem Amal militia so far has taken no part in
the fighting between Aoun's mainly Christian troops and an alliance
of Syrian troops and Moslem Druse militiamen that outgun and
outnumber the Christians.
   Sheik Sabah Ahmed, Kuwait's foreign minister and architect of
the Arab plan, left Tuesday for Tunis declaring: ``We hope our
Lebanese brothers will discern the interests of their people and
country and stop fighting so that dialogue and wisdom replace
shells and cannons.''
   In Tunisia, the Palestine Liberation Organization announced a
plan to send its own forces to quell the fighting, but the plan is
not expected to win much support.
   ``Observers say who is wrong and who is right. But to stop the
killing of the people, we need real forces,'' said PLO spokesman
Ahmed Abderrahman.
   Earlier Arab attempts to halt the carnage have failed, as has a
U.N. Security Council appeal Monday for an end to the battles that
erupted March 8. Since then, at least 272 people have been killed
and 991 wounded.
   Pope John Paul II repeated his calls for peace Tuesday at a Mass
in the Vatican, where he invited Lebanese clerics and families.
   The London-based Mideast Mirror newsletter quoted Aoun as saying
he will accept an Arab observer force ``as a first step'' toward a
political solution ``so long as it doesn't include any of the
participants of the fighting.''
   ``The ultimate objective ... remains ending the Syrian and
Israeli occupation of Lebanese territory,'' it quoted Aoun as
saying.
   Some Arab states support Christian demands that Syria withdraw
because it has violated its mandate by shelling them. Syria says it
will not withdraw.
   Tuesday's random bombardment raged from midnight to daybreak,
forcing tens of thousands of residents to shelter in underground
bunkers. It later slackened into sporadic shelling.
   The Syrians hammered the east of the city, heart of the besieged
310-square-mile Christian enclave, with 240mm mortars and B-21
launchers that fire 40 122mm rockets in 20 seconds.
   Beirut shook as Aoun's forces lobbed 155mm and 130mm howitzer
and mortar shells into west Beirut. Ambulances with wailing sirens
sped through rubble-strewn streets.
   Four shells crashed into the garden of east Beirut's Comfort
Hotel, shattering windows and windshields of five cars of the U.N.
monitoring force in Lebanon, a U.N. official said.
   In west Beirut, the facade of the West German cultural Goethe
Institute was destroyed.
   Police said west Beirut's Sahel Hospital was hit, but no
patients were hurt.
   The Arab League proposes an interim truce to stabilize the
situation until a political solution is worked out providing for
presidential elections and the formation of a coalition government.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
