<DOCNO> AP890425-0117 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-25-89 1348EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-100Days-BushStyle     04-25 1072</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-100 Days-Bush Style,990</SECOND>
<HEAD>Trappings Go Back In The Closet, Horseshoes Come Out</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In his first 100 days, President Bush put the
imperial trappings of the White House in storage. The place now
rings with the squeal of grandchildren and the clang of horseshoes.
   Born to wealth and privilege, George Herbert Walker Bush brought
to the Executive Mansion the down-to-earth tastes and attitudes of
a common person: hot dogs and baseball games, barbecues and country
music, guided tours of the grounds, side trips to tourist
attractions.
   Yet for all the bustle of the White House these days, the
nation's 41st president often rides about town in a silent
motorcade, politely stopping at red lights to avoid tying up
traffic.
   Historians and political analysts may differ over the
president's accomplishments in these first 100 days, but few will
deny he's been enjoying every one of them.
   ``Bush is sort of a James Stewart figure,'' said Rep. Newt
Gingrich of Georgia, the House Republican whip, recalling the mix
of aw-shucks naivete and stubbornness in the actor's
characterization in the movie classic, ``Mr. Smith Goes to
Washington.''
   ``The president's personal style is nice and warm and collegial.
It's just the way he is. He's also a very tough man,'' Gingrich
said, adding, ``Reagan was a star. Bush is more of a senior
player-coach type.''
   Riding the crest of 60 percent-plus approval ratings in public
opinion polls, Bush is settling with obvious relish and comfort
into the job that he long coveted. At the same time, he has
eschewed efforts to compare him with his predecessor, who also
scored high in the polls.
   ``I certainly know something about following a class act,'' Bush
told a recent audience.
   Bush himself can joke that his first 100 days are ``about the
same as Martin Van Buren's'' _ who was forced in his first 100 days
to deal with one of the nation's worst financial panics and the
long depression that followed _ and whose name the president enjoys
invoking.
   But Bush's constant-motion style gives aides and reporters a
difficult time keeping up with him.
   Beginning work each day at 7 a.m., Bush routinely puts in
11-hour workdays in the Oval Office, although he also has been
known to slip away in the middle of the afternoon to play tennis,
jog, throw horseshoes or play racquetball in a congressional
gymnasium.
   While he seldom held news conferences during his presidential
campaign, Bush has met roughly once a week with reporters since
taking office, in forums ranging from regular news conferences to
small-group chats in the Oval Office.
   He's travelled to four foreign counties and 17 states in his
first three months in office.
   Bush set a populist tone on his first full day in office,
opening the White House and its grounds to the public. And he's had
a stream of visitors in ever since, among them Democratic leaders
who got little such attention from Reagan.
   ``I've been here more ... since Bush has been president than I
was in eight years under his predecessor,'' said Rep. Jack Brooks,
D-Texas.
   Congressional leaders who have met frequently with Bush say he
is a good listener at high-level meetings, but a tough negotiator.
   ``I am amazed at how much at peace with himself he is, and
really knows where he wants to go, how he wants to do it,'' said
his chief of staff, John Sununu.
   Sununu said Bush has no trouble making quick decisions, even
though the president himself jokes that ``People say I'm
indecisive. I don't know about that.''
   Aides and associates say he gives careful attention to detail,
even checking travel manifests to make sure there aren't too many
staff members on trips, while always keeping up to speed on the
issues of the day.
   In addition to daily intelligence and national security
briefings, he reads ``about five papers as far as I can see'' each
morning, said his wife, Barbara.
   Participants at Cabinet meetings say the president often stays
on the sidelines and lets others do most of the talking, while
other times jumping in and vigorously leading the discussions.
   ``He enjoys the give and take,'' said Vice President Dan Quayle.
``He enjoys having ideas put forward. ... He enjoys the competition
of ideas and discussion of policy and where we ought to be going.''
   Bush, who as vice president had lunch once a week with Reagan,
has carried the custom forward. He eats a private lunch each
Thursday with Quayle, who said he has complete access to Bush and
can go into his office any time he wants.
   Bush is ``a much more open, gregarious, outgoing president than
we've had in a long time,'' said Norman Ornstein, a political
analyst with the American Enterprise Institute.
   ``His early reputation is that this is a president who makes
things happen. Once you establish that reputation, you are going to
carry it to your advantage for a long time.''
   Still, others have trouble focusing on Bush's true political and
policy identity in all the swirl of activity.
   ``The non-image is the image he has created for himself,'' said
Tom Griscom, who was Reagan's communications director.
   Bush, after all, is the president who begins speeches on
education with the phrase, ``you know;'' who talks about ``things''
and ``stuff;'' who frequently stumbles over his own lines.
   ``It's been said that sometimes I don't speak in very good
English and that I have a hard time being understood,'' he told a
White House audience the other day. ``I'll admit it, it's true. And
all I can say is that I'm in pretty good company, though. Look at
Yogi Berra.''
   ``I love to quote Yogi,'' Bush, captain of Yale's 1948 baseball
team, told another audience.
   ``He once said at a state dinner right here in this building,
`How could you get a conversation started in there? Everybody was
talking too much.'''
   And if Berra, the Yankee catcher who turned the language on its
ear, is the baseball great that Bush quotes the most, the one he
admires the most is another Yankee, the low-keyed Lou Gehrig, whom
Bush calls his personal hero.
   ``He played in 2,130 straight games _ a record which still
stands,'' Bush said. ``But more than that, he was a good and decent
man about whom a teammate said, `Every day, any day, he just went
out and did his job.'''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890425-0118 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-25-89 1353EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Soviet-Party 2ndLd-Writethru a0599 04-25 0530</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet-Party, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0599,0543</SECOND>
<HEAD>Central Committee Pensions Off Some Senior Members</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with three grafs with number of retirements, including
Gromyko's; picks up 5th pvs: Gorbachev has...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN IAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Communist Party's Central Committee today
retired 74 senior members, including former President Andrei A.
Gromyko, to make way for a renewal of the party's top policy-making
body that likely will strengthen President Mikhail S. Gorbachev.
   Party ideology chief Vadim A. Medvedev told a news conference
the committee unanimously approved 110 requests for retirement by
Central Committee members, non-voting committee members, and
members of the party's Central Revisions Committee.
   The official Tass news agency transmitted a list of the retirees
that included Gromyko, who retired as president last fall, former
Politburo members Geidar A. Aliev, Mikhail S. Solomentsev and
former candidate Politburo member Vladimir I. Dolgikh.
   Gorbachev has complained opposition to his reform program exists
within the Central Committee, which has included many officials who
gained membership before he became party leader in March 1985.
   Medvedev said 83 members, or more than one-quarter of the
300-member body, have lost the government and party jobs that
entitled them to Central Committee membership.
   Western observers call that group the ``dead souls'' and say it
can be a conservative presence on the Central Committee.
   Among those promoted to full Central Committee membership were
Yevgeny Velikhov, the vice president of the Soviet Academy of
Sciences who is believed to be a supporter of Gorbachev; Yuli A.
Kvitsinsky, an arms control expert who is ambassador to West
Germany; and Yevgeny Primakov, director of the Institute of World
Economics and International Relations.
   Gorbachev opened the meeting today with a speech on the party's
program and local organizations, Tass said.
   The full agenda of the one-day meeting was not disclosed, but
Foreign Ministry spokesman Gennady I. Gerasimov said Monday that
the issue of nationalities would not be the main topic of
discussion.
   At least 20 people were killed in Soviet Georgia on April 9 when
troops clashed with demonstrators demanding independence, and last
year more than 90 died in the neighboring republics of Armenia and
Azerbaijan.
   Gorbachev has said the Central Committee will devote a summer
meeting to policy toward the Soviet Union's 100 ethnic groups.
   Today's meeting was the first Central Committee session since at
least three dozen top officials across the country were defeated in
parliamentary elections March 26.
   Among the losers were the premiers of Lativa and Lithuania, the
mayor and party chief of Kiev and the mayor and No. 2 party leader
of Moscow.
   The defeats were particularly embarrassing for Communists who
ran unopposed. Others lost as they faced opponents for the first
time in the first multiple-candidate races in 70 years.
   The Central Committee has the power to oust members who were
defeated in their parliamentary bids.
   Gorbachev portrayed the parliamentary elections for a new
2,250-seat parliament as a referendum on perestroika and said party
and government officials lost because they ``were restructuring
slowly.''
   The Central Committee laid the foundation for perestroika,
Gorbachev's wide-ranging overhaul of the Soviet economy, political
and social systems, in April 1985, six weeks after Gorbachev became
party chief.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
