<FILEID>AP-NR-04-25-89 1401EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Reagan-Personnel     04-25 0521</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Reagan-Personnel,500</SECOND>
<HEAD>Study Group Says OPM Appointees Often Hostile to Civil Service</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Presidents Carter and Reagan ``made
bureaucrat-bashing the norm'' and Reagan's political appointees at
the Office of Personnel Management were often hostile to the civil
service, a congressional panel was told Tuesday.
   The congressional Federal Government Service Task Force received
reports from task forces of the National Commission on Public
Service, a private organization that has recommended pay increases
and other steps to make federal service more attractive.
   The commission's task force on recruitment and retention said in
its report that the personnel management office, created by
Congress in 1978, ``has not met early expectations and remains, in
many ways, an agency in search of an identity.''
   ``Although OPM operated for a brief time at the end of the
Carter administration, it was President Reagan who really shaped
the early character of OPM,'' the task force said.
   It said Reagan's first appointee to head OPM, Donald J. Devine,
``took a political approach to both the position and the agency''
and more than quadrupled the number of political appointees,
increasing them from eight to more than 32.
   ``Equally troubling is the fact that the political appointees to
OPM were often actively hostile to the career civil service,'' the
task force said. It charged that ``the organization's effectiveness
was severely diminished'' by low morale among the remaining career
employees.
   Rep. Norman D. Dicks, D-Wash., a co-chairman of the
congressional task force, said, ``Clearly, the public's perception
of the federal civil service has been influenced by negative
messages from some elected officials in recent years, too many of
whom have been willing to blame civil servants for the country's
problems.''
   ``The previous two presidents made bureaucrat-bashing the
norm,'' Dicks said.
   The commission task force said the appointment of Constance
Horner as director of OPM in 1985 ``signaled a new direction'' for
the agency, which in 1987 and 1988 ``paid serious attention to
promoting the public service.''
   ``There is consensus that OPM stands at the crossroads,'' the
task force said.
   One of the commission's recommendations is a sharp decrease in
the ratio of political to career appointees in the federal
government.
   Rep. Steny H. Hoyer, D-Md., also a co-chairman of the
congressional task force, said that ``career executives have been
driven off the leadership team in recent years, displaced by
deepening layers of political appointees.''
   ``This is a dangerous trend for the federal government,'' Hoyer
said. ``Career executives help assure continuity as political
appointees change.''
   Paul Volcker, former Federal Reserve chairman and chairman of
the privately financed study group, said President Bush ``speaks
clearly and spontaneously about the value of public service'' and
``I think that is an indication and a hopeful sign that attitudes
in this area may be in the process of changing.''
   The commission's recommendations, calling among other things for
a 50 percent increase over two years in pay for senior federal
officials, judges and members of Congress, were submitted to the
president March 29. Bush has recommended pay raises for judges, but
has withheld recommendations on other increases.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
