<FIRST>r i AM-Korea-Bombing     04-25 0503</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Korea-Bombing,0522</SECOND>
<HEAD>Condemned Aircraft Bomber Probably Will be Pardoned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL SHIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman condemned to death for bombing
a South Korean airliner probably will be pardoned even if the
Supreme Court upholds her sentence, government officials said
Tuesday.
   Confessed communist agent Kim Hyon Hui was convicted Tuesday and
sentenced to death by a three-judge panel headed by senior Judge
Chung Sang-hwak, who said her crime underlined North Korea's
unchanging policy of destroying South Korea's freedom.
   Pyongyang has denied Kim's assertions that North Korean leaders
ordered her to bomb the Korean Air passenger plane in 1987. All 115
people aboard died when the plane disappeared over the Andaman Sea
near the coast of Burma.
   ``We have an enemy which always tries to destroy our liberal
democratic system. We must face that reality with resolute
determination,'' Chung said in the verdict of the three-judge panel.
   Kim, 27, wept and her shoulders heaved as he pronounced her
guilty of violating national security and aviation laws and
sentenced her to death.
   South Korean law gives Kim one week to appeal. Ahn Dong-il, her
lawyer, said they have not yet decided whether to do so.
   Relatives of those killed sat quietly in the court, watching Kim
as she stood before the judge with downcast eyes. She said nothing
before being led away.
   ``She deserves death because she killed 115 people,'' Park
Son-jin, 60, whose son was on the plane, said after the hearing.
   Hundreds of security agents and police surrounded the courthouse
to prevent more angry protests by relatives, or a possible threat
from North Korea.
   The judge said there is no doubt Kim planted the bomb aboard the
Boeing 707 that disappeared Nov. 29, 1987, on a flight from Baghdad
to Seoul.
   Kim has said she blew up the plane on orders from Kim Jong Il,
son and heir of North Korean President Kim Il Sung, to disrupt the
Seoul Olympics.
   She has said she wants to die to atone for her sin.
   But South Korean officials said privately they expect she will
be reprieved on grounds she was duped by North Korea and has
repented.
   Court officials said if Kim is pardoned, she will be free on a
stay of the sentence. Similar arrangements have freed other North
Korean agents pardoned under a special amnesty after they switched
loyalty.
   North Korea denies involvement in the bombing and claims it was
engineered by South Korea to embarrass the Pyongyang government.
The two nations have been bitter rivals since their land was
divided in 1945.
   Testimony given by Kim corroborated the findings of bomb experts
who said the plane exploded in less than a second. No bodies were
found.
   Kim has said she and another agent pretended to be Japanese
tourists and planted the bomb, which was disguised as a radio and a
liquor bottle.
   The two were arrested a few days later and tried to take cyanide
hidden in cigarettes. The other agent, an elderly man, died.
</TEXT>
