<HEAD>Trappings Go Back In The Closet, Horseshoes Come Out</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In his first 100 days, President Bush put the
imperial trappings of the White House in storage. The place now
rings with the squeal of xpediting U.S. economic and
military aid and states: ``President Reagan personally authorized
the entire plan.''
   Kozak testimony was in response to questions from subcommittee
chairman David Obey, D-Wis., who asserted that his panel had been
misled or lied to by Reagan administration officials when it sought
to find out at the time whether foreign aid money was being
indirectly used to help the Contras at a time when such aid was
prohibited.
   Kozak said he had learned before coming to Capitol Hill that he
would be asked about apparent discrepancies between the North trial
document and what administration witnesses had told Congress. He
said he called the White House for guidance on how to respond
before testifying.
   ``The whole proposed linkage that was included in (North's) plan
was disapproved, was not made, there was no `discreet emissary',''
Kozak said.
   In an admission-of-fact document prepared by North's lawyers and
the government, North ``linked a trip of the vice president that
was planned well in advance of even the preparation of this plan,
publicly announced, and which did occur, to a secret plan that was
never appproved,'' Kozak told the panel.
   Bush's talks with high-level officials, including Honduran
President Roberto Suazo, never mentioned the quid-pro-quo link, he
said. Kozak said he has seen memos outlining the conversations, and
``they're not talking about conditionality of the type that (North)
document implies.''
   Kozak said the Bush administration has been frustrated at not
being able to comment on the 42-page document since it was
introduced at North's trial on April 6. But he said he now could
comment on the admissions because North's jury is now sequestered
and can't be swayed by his comments.
   He said the paper was suggested by Judge Gerhard Gesell, who is
presiding over the North trial, and prepared by North and his
lawyers ``as an expedient way of managing the trial, avoiding
classification issues, avoiding long argumentation and calling
witnessess over material that might not be relevant to that trial.''
   ``When I saw this thing, I started walking around my office
shouting,'' he said. ``It was so distorted, so misleading... But I
was told that we had no role in being able to influence the content
of this document, other than to ensure that no classified
information was in there.''
