<FILEID>AP-NR-04-25-89 1424EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-HomeSales     04-25 0536</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Home Sales,530</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sales of Existing Homes Down for Third Straight Month</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Economy, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NANCY BENAC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sales of existing homes dropped 4.3 percent in
March, the third straight monthly decline, as rising mortgage
interest rates made more inroads into the housing market, a real
estate trade group said Tuesday.
   The National Association of Realtors said sales of existing
single-family homes dropped to a seasonally adjusted annual rate of
3.33 million units in March, the slowest pace since February 1988.
   Sales had dropped 2 percent in February and 9.4 percent in
January.
   The March figures were the latest in a series of reports that
indicate rising interest rates are slowing the economy and taking a
toll on home sales and residential construction. Last week, the
government reported that construction of new homes and apartments
declined 5.4 percent in March, the second straight monthly decline.
   Because housing usually slows down in advance of other sectors
of the economy, the weak performance has heightened fears that a
recession could come later this year or in early 1990. The Federal
Reserve Board for a year has been pushing up interest rates as part
of a campaign to slow the economy and keep inflation in check.
   ``This is another piece of evidence that things are softening
and that high interest rates do make a difference,'' Maury Harris,
chief economist for PaineWebber Inc., said of the latest housing
report.
   Fixed-rate home mortgages averaged between 10.86 percent and
11.22 percent in March, up a full percentage point from a year
earlier, according to the Federal Home Loan Mortgage Corp.
   Ira Gribin, president of the Realtors, said the higher rates are
having their biggest impact on first-time home buyers. He said they
are ``the first to leave the market and the last who are able to
get back in.''
   With fewer sales last month to first-time buyers, the median
price of existing homes sold rose $1,200 to $93,100, meaning half
the homes sold for more and half for less.
   ``What we are seeing is definitely a trade-up market,'' said
John A. Tuccillo, chief economist for the Realtors. ``People still
in the market are those with the incomes to withstand higher
monthly mortgage payments resulting from higher interest rates.''
   Economist Lyle Gramley of the Mortgage Bankers Association said
that while further declines lie ahead for the housing industry,
``this is not a collapse of the housing market.''
   ``Monetary policy used to clobber the housing market,'' Gramley
said. ``Now it's nibbling gently on the fringes.''
   Gramley said slower growth is ``just what the doctor ordered''
to dampen inflationary pressures and keep the economic expansion
alive.
   By region, the sharpest decline in home sales last month was in
the Northeast, where the resale pace was down 10 percent to a
seasonally adjusted annual rate of 540,000 units. Sales in the
Northeast had declined 15.5 percent during February.
   Sales last month were down 7.6 percent in the Midwest to an
annual rate of 850,000 units and fell 3.1 percent in the South to a
rate of 1.27 million units. The only increase was recorded in the
West, where sales rose 4.7 percent to an annual rate of 670,000
units.
</TEXT>
