<FILEID>AP-NR-04-25-89 1453EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-WrightProbe     04-25 0608</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Wright Probe,600</SECOND>
<HEAD>House Ethics Panel Abruptly Suspends Texas Inquiry</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID SEDENO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN ANTONIO, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ranking members of the House ethics
committee abruptly suspended their inquiry Tuesday after
businessmen failed to appear to testify about a lucrative oil
investment that benefited House Speaker Jim Wright's blind trust.
   Committee chairman Rep. Julian Dixon, D-Calif., said witnesses
scheduled to appear for questioning were being represented by a
Washington law firm, which told the panel the witnesses would not
be available.
   ``That law firm has informed us that the witness will not attend
today or tomorrow, so we have recessed our hearing,'' Dixon said.
He said the firm represented ``witnesses or a witness that would
appear today or tomorrow.''
   Rep. John Myers of Indiana, ranking Republican on the committee,
said, ``We don't have cooperative witnesses.''
   Dixon would not identify the witnesses or the law firm, but
Myers said San Antonio financier Morris Jaffe and his business
associate and son, M.D. (Doug) Jaffe Jr., had been scheduled to be
questioned Wednesday.
   Myers said refusal of a witness to appear before the panel is
not unique, and said he did not know when the committee would
resume taking depositions.
   Last week, the panel formally charged Wright with 69 violations
of House rules in his financial dealings with George Mallick, a
Fort Worth developer, and in sales of Wright's book, ``Reflections
of a Public Man.'' The panel said its inquiry remained open to look
into the oil deal, a drilling venture in Sabine Lake near the
Texas-Louisiana line.
   In Washington, Wright defended his book sales, saying ``I never
consciously considered that ... buying books as payment for my
making a speech.'' The ethics panel has alleged that he used bulk
sales of the book to evade limits on outside income from speaking
fees.
   Asked whether he would donate any excess earnings to charity if
the committee asked him to do so to correct the situation, Wright
said, ``Of course I'd do it.''
   The committee leaders arrived in San Antonio Monday to interview
witnesses as to how the Wright-Mallick partnership made a one-day
profit of $340,880 last May 10 on the oil well investment.
   The committee is studying ``the amount of profit over a few
hours' time,'' Myers said. ``It doesn't look good.''
   The ethics committee said it wanted to determine whether Wright
knew about the oil well deal, which involved the Jaffes, a West
German-owned firm, and the blind trust established for Wright in
1987, said Richard Phelan, the ethics committee's counsel.
   Dixon and Myers declined to say whether they would seek contempt
citations against the reluctant witnesses.
   Asked if he was upset, Myers said, ``Yes, we came down here to
Texas to expedite this, and find they are less than cooperative.''
   ``There is a possibility we will'' return to San Antonio, Dixon
said.
   The operator of the southeast Texas oil well, L.R. Brammer Jr.
of Brammer Engineering Co., was interviewed Monday.
   A Beaumont oil man told the Beaumont Enterprise the oil well in
question was located in an area of what he termed ``spotty
production'' in Sabine Lake.
   The wildcat venture was in an area that yielded few natural gas
wells and mostly dry ones, said Geneos ``Pete'' Cokinos, a
petroleum and geological consultant.
   Wright has denied any wrongdoing and pledged to fight the
allegations. Of the 1988 oil well transaction, Wright has said his
financial holdings were in a blind trust and he was unaware of the
deal.
   The panel is considering whether there is ``clear and
convincing'' proof of the 69 alleged violations and, if so, whether
to recommend disciplinary action to the House.
</TEXT>
