<FIRST>u i PM-Mexico-Earthquake 9thLd-Writethru a0616 04-25 0746</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Mexico-Earthquake, 9th Ld-Writethru, a0616,0768</SECOND>
<HEAD>Strong Earthquake Shakes Mexico City</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 3 grafs to update with report of death, injuries.
Picks up 3rd graf pvs ``The National Earthquake...'' </HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN WRIGHT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A strong earthquake shook Mexico City and
other parts of southern Mexico this morning, cracking buildings and
sending thousands of panicked people into the streets. At least one
death was reported.
   Ambulances raced around the capital, sirens blaring, after the
8:29 a.m. (10:29 a.m. EDT) tremor.
   The government news agency Notimex reported one man was
electrocuted and died and that two women were seriously injured
when they jumped from the second story of a swaying building during
the tremor. The death and injuries occurred in Mexico City, the
agency said.
   The National Earthquake Information Center in Golden, Colo.,
said preliminary readings indicated the quake registered 6.8 on the
Richter scale.
   The epicenter was 40 miles east of Acapulco, about 200 miles
south of Mexico City, seismologist John Minsch said.
   The tremor was felt strongly in Acapulco, causing brief power
failures and panic, said Francisco Guerra, advertising director of
the newspaper Novedades de Acapulco.
   ``I've never felt a tremor so strong in the city and I've lived
here for 30 years. I thought the building would collapse,'' he said.
   Miguel Angel Hernandez, spokesman for the Guerrero state
government, said ``there are no reports of loss of life or major
damage throughout the state,'' including heavily populated Pacific
Ocean tourist spots such as Zijuatanejo and Acapulco.
   ``Even though the quake was intensively felt, everything is
normal and there are also reports of no major damage. We did a
survey by radio,'' he said.
   In Mexico City, the earthquake began as a small jolt and stopped
momentarily, then buildings in the capital began swaying back and
forth, with plaster cracking.
   The tremor shook Mexico City at about the same time as the large
earthquake that struck in Sept. 19, 1985, killing at least 10,000
people and knocking down hundreds of buildings. That quake measured
8.1 on the Richter scale.
   Today's earthquake knocked out power and telephone service in
some parts of Mexico City and damaged water lines. Schools were
evacuated to check for damage.
   Many buildings in the capital were evacuated.
   The temblor cut off power to Televisa, the nation's largest
television network, for a few minutes.
   Service in Mexico City's subway stopped temporarily to check for
damage on the lines.
   A 19-story building that houses the Health Ministry's budget
office suffered considerable damage as plaster fell, according to
evacuees. The building had been rebuilt after the 1985 quake.
   Carlos Bravo, who works in the penthouse offices, said, ``It was
horrible. There was hysteria. Parts of the ceiling fell, but they
were not big enough to hurt anyone. Some of us calmed many people
and made them go down the stairway.''
   Associated Press correspondents reported broken windows and
panic in neighborhoods around the capital, including Polanco,
Condesa and Napoles.
   In Condesa, a resident said she heard ``cracking sounds,'' saw
``people running into the streets'' and ``could see the earth
moving.''
   Radio Red reported that a police helicopter spotted no collapsed
buildings.
   Eduardo Almeida waited in a park outside his office in the
Condesa neighborhood. ``When there's an earthquake, there can be
another one afterwards,'' he said.
   An office worker who gave her name only as Magdalena, said, ``It
sounded like hail was falling. It sounded really ugly, as if the
building was breaking.''
   Jesus Esquivel, a carpenter working on fourth floor of modern
apartment building that was damaged in 1985 quake, sat in the park,
his tools by his side. ``The apartment where I'm working cracked.''
He said there was a small separation where the wall joins the
ceiling.
   The Richter scale is a gauge of the energy released by an
earthquake, as measured by the ground motion recorded on a
seismograph. Every increase of one number means that the ground
motion is 10 times greater.
   A quake of magnitude 6 can cause severe damage in populated
areas. A quake of magnitude 7 is considered a major earthquake,
capable of widespread, heavy damage in populated areas.
   Today's quake was centered about 250 miles southeast of the 1985
earthquake, the U.S. Geological Survey in Washington said. The
agency said the earlier earthquake released 90 times more energy
than today's quake.
   An earthquake with a magnitude 5.9 was reported on July 15,
1987, 100 miles east of today's earthquake.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
