<FIRST>u a PM-SpottedOwlDinner 2ndLd-Writethru a0578 04-25 0744</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Spotted Owl Dinner, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0578,0766</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pickled Spotted Owl Eggs, Spotted Owl Dinners Signs of Frustration</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS grafs 6-7, `But the...' with 1 graf to UPDATE with U.S.
Fish and Wildlife Service confirming it will tell a federal judge in Seattle
that owl should be listed as a threatened species.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>EUGENE, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   At a tavern in Coburg, there's ``pickled
spotted owl egg'' and ``fried or broasted spotted owl'' on the menu.
   An Oakridge tavern held a spotted owl dinner two weeks ago, and
attracted a big crowd.
   A Springfield man plans to market ``spotted owl jerky.''
   The food isn't really owl meat, but the spoofs are signs of how
high emotions are running in Oregon's timber country over the
northern spotted owl and its habitat in old-growth forest coveted
by loggers.
   Bill Allison, publisher of High Lead magazine in Eugene, said
he's sold more than 600 T-shirts that feature a hairy logger
carrying an owl on a tray with the caption ``save a logger, eat an
owl.''
   Despite the protestations, the U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service
said today in Washington, D.C., it will tell a federal court in
Seattle next week that protection of the spotted owl as a
threatened species is warranted.
   Listing a species as ``threatened'' is slightly less restrictive
than listing a species as ``endangered,'' said George Leonard,
associate chief of the U.S. Forest Service. However, it still could
lock loggers out of much of the old-growth forest west of the
Cascade Range in Oregon and Washington.
   The Fish and Wildlife Service earlier decided against listing
the owl as endangered, but a reassessment was ordered by U.S.
District Judge Thomas Zilly in Seattle. Zilly found the earlier
decision was not supported by evidence compiled by Fish and
Wildlife.
   Under the Endangered Species Act, a species is considered
endangered if it is ``in danger of extinction throughout all or a
significant part of its range.'' A species is considered threatened
if it is ``likely to become an endangered species in the
foreseeable future throughout all or a significant portion of its
range.''
   Rolla Anderson, who works at the Bohemia Inc. plywood plant in
Vaughn, has written a poem about the owl. In it, he tells of a man
seeing a spotted owl contentedly sitting on a limb in a stand of
old-growth trees.
   ``Even tho I soon may lose my job
   And stand to lose my home
   I can't explain the peace I felt
   Like none I've never known.
   Standing there in that quiet place
   Far from the sound of cars
   I looked around, took careful aim
   Then blew his brains to Mars.''
   Environmentalists who say the owl is faced with extinction
because of logging, and timber industry representatives who say the
trees are needed to keep the industry alive in the Northwest, agree
that the spotted owl dinners, T-shirts and poems are signs of
frustration and fear.
   Karen Wood of the environmental group Earth First said anti-owl
sentiment has been caused by the timber industry.
   ``They find it convenient to turn their workers' heads around
and say, `Look, it's that owl that's taking your job,' when they're
sending logs overseas,'' she said.
   ``It's just a fear thing and I hope workers can look beyond the
fear to see what's happenning.''
   Allison said he's received only one complaint about his
T-shirts. That came from a timber industry official who said the
shirts are inappropriate and thought it would be better to show an
owl or other wildlife living in harmony with good forest practices.
   Allison accuses both sides of ``tunnel vision.''
   ``The spotted owl is a means to an end,'' he said. ``If it
wasn't that, it would be the pig-tailed titmouse. The
(environmentalists') goal is to save old growth.''
   As for the timber industry, he said, ``How can people like
Weyerhaeuser send (logs) to Japan, then go bid on federal timber?
That's not fair.''
   Anderson said he really doesn't advocate shooting spotted owls,
but he lost his job in California when Redwood National Park was
established.
   ``I just kind of got a new start and I'd hate to see it go down
the tubes here,'' he said.
   ``I'm not so dumb that I think the owl is the only problem,'' he
said. ``They're shipping logs (overseas), I realize that. There
might be a poem coming on that one of these days.''
   ``The owl gets focused on,'' he said, ``because it's kind of a
symbol.''
</TEXT>
