<FIRST>d a AM-BRF--LotteryAd     04-25 0170</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Lottery Ad,0173</SECOND>
<HEAD>State Pulls Plug On Lotto Commercial</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   State gaming officials have pulled a
Lotto television commercial that had some lawmakers fuming because
they believed it undermined the Yankee work ethic and promoted
sloth.
   The commercial depicted a man in a rowboat who starts out
talking about how he had never bothered to plan financially for his
twilight years. He bursts into a self-satisfied cackle after
revealing that he could live in the lap of luxury anyway because he
hit a multimillion-dollar Lotto jackpot.
   ``What happened is that this has become a matter of legislative
concern and we have decided to withdraw it,'' said William V.
Hickey, chairman of the state's Gaming Policy Board.
   J. Blaine Lewis Jr., the division's lottery unit chief, ordered
the state's lottery advertising agency to stop running the ad
Friday. He said Monday he was ordered to do so by William T.
Drakeley, the gaming division's deputy executive director.
   The ad cost the state $50,000 to produce, Lewis said.
</TEXT>
