<FILEID>AP-NR-04-25-89 1610EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-US-Germany     04-25 0555</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Germany,570</SECOND>
<HEAD>State Department Criticizes Soviets, Mounts Campaign Within NATO
To Bar Talks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States accused the Soviet Union on
Tuesday of trying to undermine NATO's nuclear defense and
instructed U.S. ambassadors in Western capitals to counter a West
German drive for negotiations to scale back short-range nuclear
missiles.
   The U.S. offensive is designed to rally the North Atlantic
Treaty Organization against any reduction in nuclear battlefield
weapons before President Bush meets with the 15 allied leaders in
Brussels at the end of May.
   West German Chancellor Helmut Kohl, trying to counter growing
support for disarmament in his country, sent Defense Minister
Gerhard Stoltenberg and Foreign Minister Hans-Dietrich Genscher to
Washington for talks Monday to try to persuade the Bush
administration tn negotiate with the Soviets over the missiles.
   But Secretary of Defense Dick Cheney and Secretary of State
James A. Baker III turned the West Germans down, saying it would be
a mistake to risk cutbacks in the short-range nuclear missiles and
artillery guns that fire nuclear-tipped shells while the Soviets
held an advantage in non-nuclear forces in Europe.
   Cheney described such negotiations as a ``dangerous trap.'' But
Kohl, whose political future could hinge on the missile issue, is
not backing off and will present his position formally to the West
German parliament on Thursday.
   In the meantime, the State Department sent cables to the
American ambassadors in all the NATO capitals instructing them to
present the U.S. argument against negotiations to the foreign
ministries there, a U.S. official said.
   The presentations, known technically as ``demarches,'' are
designed to forestall a drift toward the West German position,
which already enjoys some support in Norway, Belgium, the
Netherlands and Denmark.
   The official, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said West
German ambassadors were expected to mount a campaign for support in
all NATO capitals as well.
   Also, Rozanne L. Ridgway, the assistant secretary of state for
European affairs, will present the U.S. position to senior
officials of Spain, Greece and France in Madrid on May 16.
   That is two weeks before Bush and the leaders of the NATO
countries hold a summit meeting in Brussels.
   Margaret Tutwiler, the State Department spokeswoman, said ``it
would be helpful'' if the missile dispute could be resolved before
the meeting. ``There is more to discuss at the summit than SNF
(short-range nuclear forces),'' she said.
   But Ms. Tutwiler, who consulted with Baker, said ``the
discussions will continue'' and launched into an attack on the
Soviet Union.
   ``The Soviets clearly want to denuclearize and undermine NATO's
flexible response and forward-defense strategies,'' she said.
``Negotiations would provide them an opportunity to promote a third
zero.''
   The battlefield nuclear missiles are considered part of a
flexible strategy designed to keep the Soviets off-balance. The
theory is that uncertainty whether NATO would use nuclear weapons
deters a Soviet attack.
   The 1987 U.S.-Soviet treaty banning intermediate-range nuclear
missiles eliminated two categories of nuclear rockets in Europe.
This is known as the `'double-zero.''
   The statement read by Ms. Tutwiler at Baker's direction refers
to a third category of missiles _ those with a range below 315
miles _ and U.S. determination to keep them in Europe.
   ``The Soviets have already modernized their nuclear weapons, and
the alliance must also maintain up-to-date forces,'' she said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890425-0145 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-25-89 1613EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Israel 1stLd-Writethru a0620 04-25 0608</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0620,0623</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two Collaborators Killed; 1 Dead and 17 Wounded in Clashes</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 4th graf ``A Palestinian ...'' with 1 graf to UPDATE number
of wounded.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By G.G. LaBELLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Palestinian attackers on Tuesday stabbed to
death two men accused of collaborating with Israeli authorities,
Arab reports said.
   The deaths in the occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip follow a
call by Palestinian uprising leaders for attacks on Arabs
cooperating with Israel and an order by Moslem fundamentalists to
target drug dealers and prostitutes.
   Authorities confirmed one of the deaths.
   A Palestinian also was reported shot and killed Tuesday in a
clash with soldiers in the Gaza Strip, and 17 others were wounded
by army gunfire in the occupied territories, including a
13-year-old girl who was shot in the head.
   Army officials said they were unaware of the death and were
checking reports of clashes.
   In Jerusalem's Old City, Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir declared
that Israel would never surrender part of Jerusalem in a peace
settlement with Palestinians. The government said Foreign Minister
Moshe Arens would visit the United States in May for talks on
Shamir's plan to hold elections in the occupied territories to
advance the stalled peace process.
   Police said they had arrested three suspects in Tuesday's fatal
stabbing of Fauzi Muhareb in the Gaza town of Khan Yunis.
   Muhareb, 51, left his house accompanied by his wife, said police
spokesman Yigal Golan. ``There was a roadblock of burning tires.
Three to four young men ... attacked him with knives. They stabbed
him in the shoulder and heart.''
   Police said Muhareb had a criminal background but would not give
details.
   Palestinian reporters, who insisted on anonymity, said Muhareb
was a collaborator with Israel and a drug dealer.
   In the West Bank city of Nablus, Azam Al-Qadi was beaten and
stabbed to death early Tuesday, Arab reporters said. Al-Qadi, 21,
was accused by local Palestinians of giving information to the Shin
Bet security service, the Arabs said.
   The PLO-backed leadership of the 16-month Palestinian uprising
has repeatedly called for attacks on collaborabors. In its latest
leaflet, it declared Wednesday ``a day of accounting for the
collaborators.''
   In February, a leaflet from the fundamentalist Moslem movement
Hamas, or ``Zeal,'' urged Palestinians to ``deal with'' prostitutes
and drug dealers.
   Within the past week, five alleged collaborators were reported
killed in the occupied territories, but at least two victims were
also said to have criminal connections.
   Including Tuesday's deaths, 447 Palestinians and 18 Israelis
have been killed in the uprising.
   The latest victim was Khalid Musa Armelat, 22, who was shot in
the head during a clash with soldiers in the Gaza town of Rafah,
according to officials at nearby Nasser Hospital.
   A member of Israel's parliament meanwhile demanded an
investigation into an allegation that an army colonel bragged about
subverting an inquiry into the killing of a Palestinian by soldiers.
   Dedi Zucker of the left-wing Citizens Rights Movement said he
was told by a reserve soldier that during a briefing, the colonel
was asked what would happen to someone who shot a Palestinian.
   The reservist told Zucker that the colonel replied: ``Listen, I
have an example for you. Two weeks ago a Palestinians was shot at
close range and when the investigators came, we arranged it so
there would be no problem.''
   Zucker said he wrote Defense Minister Yitzhak Rabin three weeks
ago to ask for an investigation into the death in the West Bank
village of Deir Pazia but received no reply.
   Eitan Haber, a Rabin spokesman, said he was uncertain if the
letter was received.
</TEXT>
