<FIRST>r w AM-US-NewZealand     04-25 0432</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-New Zealand,390</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Criticizes Suggestion New Zealand May Pull Out Of Pact</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RUTH SINAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States on Tuesday disputed a
suggestion by Prime Minister David Lange of New Zealand that his
country may pull out of a security alliance with the United States
because of his nation's anti-nuclear policies.
   ``That is New Zealand's prerogative,'' said State Department
spokeswoman Margaret Tutwiler. But, she added, ``we take exception
to the prime minister's assertions that such action is justified by
the United States' refusal to consult with New Zealand'' in
accordance with terms of the ANZUS pact.
   ANZUS, created in 1951 as a defense alliance among the United
States, Australia and New Zealand, has been crippled since the
United States suspended guarantees for New Zealand's defense in
1986 over the Pacific nation's ban of ships carrying nuclear
weapons. U.S. policy is neither to confirm nor deny the existence
of nuclear weapons on its vessels.
   Even if New Zealand does pull out, ``ANZUS would continue to
exist as the foundation of our important and active security
relationship with Australia,'' said a State Department statement.
   ``We continue to hope that New Zealand will reassess its
anti-nuclear policies, which would enable it to return to full
participation'' in ANZUS, the statement said.
   The rift between the two countries led the United States to stop
sharing intelligence information with New Zealand and to cool its
diplomatic relations with the embassy here.
   Speaking at Yale University Monday, Lange said his country's
security relationship with the United States is a ``dead letter.''
   But the State Department disputed that view, saying that ``the
U.S. continues to maintain a security relationship with New
Zealand, albeit much diminished from the close military and
intelligence ties existing prior to the current dispute.''
   Observers here have noted that despite Lange's outspoken
comments at Yale and in several interviews he has granted since
arriving for a six-day visit, he has also emphasized that overall
relations between the two countries are good. Lange has stressed
that trade and tourism have grown.
   Responding to that tone, the State Department said ``the United
States and New Zealand now enjoy a constructive relationship on a
range of issues in which we share common goals and objectives.
   ``We regret, however, that the prime minister's remarks did not
more constructively address our difference of opinion on issues
raised by New Zealand's anti-nuclear policies,'' it said.
   Lange said Monday he would not come to Washington because the
U.S. administration had made it clear he was not welcome until his
government renounced its anti-nuclear policies.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
