<FIRST>r i AM-Poland-Gas     04-25 0479</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland-Gas,0494</SECOND>
<HEAD>Four Months After Rationing Ends, Shortages Start</HEAD>
<UNK>By DRUSILLA MENAKER ^Associated Press Writer</UNK>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government said Tuesday that a severe
gas shortage has closed some stations and caused long lines at the
pumps, forcing Poland to look to the West for extra gas supplies.
   The government blamed a 20 percent jump in gasoline consumption
on the end of gas rationing Jan. 1, a mild winter that allowed more
cars on the road and the government's refusal to allow prices to
rise high enough to discourage demand.
   ``If we were persistent in introducing the market economy,
prices would surely regulate the problem of lines,'' said deputy
government spokesman Zbyslaw Rykowski.
   Concern about gas shortages and price increases began spreading
across Warsaw by word of mouth last week.
   Confirmation came Tuesday in official newspaper reports the
government would tap hard currency supplies to buy about 163
million gallons of gasoline from Sweden, Austria and East Germany.
   Gas imports planned for the first half of this year from the
Soviet Union, Poland's largest supplier, arrived early and were
used up ahead of schedule, the Express Wieczorny newspaper reported
Tuesday.
   It will be several weeks before the new gas reaches Poland and
eases the supply problems, said Krzysztof Pilich, deputy manager of
the state oil department.
   But Pilich said rationing would not be introduced again.
   When rationing ended, the Ministry of Industry warned that
prices would increase if sales of gasoline outstripped supplies.
   The price at the time was 190 zlotys a liter, or $1.46 per
gallon. The price has been raised to 250 zlotys a liter.
   The average monthly salary is about $127 to $175.
   Disgruntled drivers waiting Tuesday at a Warsaw gas station had
differing opinions about the cause of the shortage, which is being
widely discussed in the informal network that keeps residents up to
date on supplies of goods.
   ``I think it is a matter of bad distribution,'' said one man.
   Another who had waited for four hours without success the night
before said he thought the government had created the shortage to
keep people from ``moving around the country'' during upcoming
elections, the first since 1947.
   ``I think it is done on purpose and a lot of people share this
view,'' he said.
   Rykowski said there could be some distribution problems but poor
planning did not cause the shortage. Instead, he said it stemmed
from a failure ``for justifiable, social reasons'' to use higher
prices to suppress demand in the style of a market-based economy.
   ``I am saying this with certain terror because I know that these
sorts of moralizing speeches are met with rejection,'' he said at
the news conference.
   ``I don't intend to continue this sermonizing and point out that
in countries with a market-oriented economy, when someone drives to
work he calculates how much that costs,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
