<FIRST>u i AM-Soviet-Georgia     04-25 0589</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Georgia,0609</SECOND>
<HEAD>Georgian Activists Cancel Protest After Warning of Trouble</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANN IMSE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TBILISI, U.S.S.R. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Activists said they canceled a
pro-independence rally Tuesday after authorities told them it could
spark a repeat of the bloody confrontation with soldiers in which
20 people died.
   ``There is a danger the tanks will charge again, and the
soldiers will shoot. So we postponed the meeting,'' said David
Nadiradze, a lawyer who advocates the secession of the republic of
Georgia from the Soviet Union.
   Nadiradze said independence activists received the warning from
sympathetic police officers, and political leaders advised that the
curfew and state of emergency that brought Soviet soldiers into the
city could be reinstated.
   About 5,000 people appeared at the flower-covered square in
front of Government House on Tuesday. Young people holding flowers,
candles or black flags of mourning guarded a shrine at the crash to
the victims of the April 9 clash.
   But no one stood up to address the group.
   Irakli Shengalaya, head of the Society of National Justice, an
informal political group, said he and other activists decided to
postpone the demonstration after Georgian Interior Minister Shota
Gorgodze warned earlier Tuesday that the curfew and state of
emergency that brought Soviet soldiers and tanks into the
republic's capital on April 7 could be reinstated.
   The soldiers and armor were withdrawn from the city last week,
but activist Tengiz Ordzhonikidze said they have been seen in
recent days at nearby lakes and in suburbs.
   Shengelaya and other activists said the interior minister's
statement, which was carried on local TV, appeared to be friendly
advice rather than a threat.
   Georgian Communist Party chief Givi Gumbaridze, when asked
Monday how he would react to future demonstrations, said: ``What
happened on April 9 can't happen again.''
   Gumbaridze on Monday confirmed accusations by activists that
some of the 20 deaths were caused by poison gas used by the
soldiers.
   In Washington, the United States on Tuesday condemned ``the use
of any chemical agents that cause serious injury or death when used
against peaceful protesters.''
   State Department spokeswoman Margaret Tutwiler urged the Soviet
government to ``investigate fully and openly what happened on April
9.''
   In Moscow, Georgy P. Razumovsky, a candidate member of the
ruling Communist Party Politburo who visited Tbilisi after the
violence, said the decision to break up the protest with force was
made ``by local authorities.''
   Razumovsky, at a news conference, criticized Georgian officials
for a ``constant lack of dialogue'' with young people and the
intelligentsia on the republic's problems.
   Activists said the demonstration, which had been planned for the
yard of the Kashveti Church, a 13th-century stone building across
the street from Government House, was postponed to May 21.
   Tiblisi Police Chief Roman Zvensadze said he had personally
suggested to activists that ``holding a demonstration during the
traditional 40 days of mourning would be unseemly.''
   The demonstration had been called to demand the release of seven
activists arrested hours after the April 9 clash and to ``demand
punishment of the murderers,'' said Nadiradze.
   They also sought were seeking annulment of a Kremlin decree
making it illegal to ``insult or discredit'' the government.
   Demonstrations in Georgia first began April 4 when protesters
criticized calls from members of the republic's ethnic Abkhazian
minority to break away because of alleged discrimination by
Georgians.
   Other protesters have demanded Georgia secede from the Soviet
Union because of alleged interference from the central government.
   The republic's senior party official, Dzhumber Patiashvili, took
responsibility for the April 9 attack and resigned.
</TEXT>
