<FILEID>AP-NR-04-25-89 1729EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-ChildPornography     04-25 0680</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Child Pornography,670</SECOND>
<HEAD>Publishing and Library Groups Attack Age-Documentation Law</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAY ARNOLD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A new law requiring publishers and
distributors to document the ages of nude models in photographs
``will have a truly devastating effect'' on free expression and
will not stem the flow of child pornography, a judge was told
Tuesday.
   The law poses near-impossible record-keeping burdens on
legitimate businesses and would impose a ``corporate death
penalty'' on distributors because all assets could be seized if
they violate the law with even one publication, said an attorney
for a coalition of publishing and library groups.
   The coalition claims the law would force librarians to remove
from their shelves any medical, sex education and sociological
texts showing full frontal nudity and stop magazines and TV shows
from using adult sexual material that is protected by the First
Amendment.
   ``It will have a truly devastating effect on entirely lawful,
protected speech of adults,'' said Bruce Ennis, an attorney
representing the American Library Association in a lawsuit against
the statute.
   The law requires that anyone who produces material with images
of sexual activity or ``lascivious exhibition of the genitals''
keep records showing the models depicted are at least 18 years old.
The law covers the reissue of any materials produced after Feb. 5,
1978 _ the date when a major federal child pornography law took
effect.
   Ennis said the word lascivious is too imprecise, the text of the
statute is too broad and the child porno industry is entirely
underground and would not be affected by the law.
   ``The government is concerned about an underground problem, but
they impose a solution on a legitimate above-ground industry,''
Ennis said.
   Richard Stearns, a Justice Department attorney, told U.S.
District Judge George Revercomb that publishers' First Amendment
arguments were ``overwrought'' and that they would be little
affected by the law.
   He said if mainstream companies weren't distributing child
pornography it must mean they already have adopted ways to prevent
such occurrences.
   Stearns said the government has the right to try to stop the
production of ``vast'' amounts of child pornography in this country
and the importation of child pornography.
   The new law would punish criminals, not suppress free
expression, he told the judge.
   Then-President Reagan signed the Child Protection and Obscenity
Enforcement Act last November, and the record-keeping requirements
were scheduled to start May 17, not Aug. 17 as published
incorrectly in the Federal Register, Stearns said.
   The act increases penalties for anyone facilitating use of a
child for producing sexually explicit materials, creates a new
federal offense for engaging in the business of distributing
obscene materials and provides mandatory forfeiture of the profits
of those convicted of being engaged in the adult obscenity business.
   House Speaker Jim Wright, D-Texas, has said Congress intended to
target only major dealers or producers of obscene materials who
were ``knowingly engaged for a long period of time.'' He said the
measure was not aimed at the bookstore owner who may have a single
volume judged to be obscene.
   Stearns said the problem in prosecuting child pornography was
the difficulty in determining the ages of models. He agreed with
Revercomb that the issue involved those aged 14 to 17 who can pass
for 19 and 20, such as actress Tracy Lords who made 75 porno films
starting when she was 14.
   Stearns said the law clearly defines illegal sexual acts and
``doesn't apply to all frank depictions of the human form.''
Medical texts, art books and news photos would not be in jeopardy,
he said.
   Revercomb took under advisement the coalition's request for a
preliminary injunction against the record-keeping and forfeiture
provisions. The Justice Department sought dismissal of the suit.
   The challengers include the American Library Association,
American Booksellers Association, Freedom to Read Foundation,
Magazine Publishers of America, American Society of Magazine
Photographers, American Society of Magazine Editors, Council for
Periodical Distributors Association, International Periodical
Distributors Association and the Satellite Broadcasting
Communications Association.
   The Association of American Publishers and the Video Software
Dealers Association also filed court papers arguing against the law.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
