<HEAD>With AM-100 Days-Bush Style Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PAGO PAGO, America Samoa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President Dan Quayle,
decked out in sweet smelling leis, declared a national holiday
Tuesday for this tropical island where he was greeted by cheering
locals.
   ``You all look like happy campers to me,'' Quayle said as he
spoke to about 2,000 natives gathered for his brief stopover
enroute to Australia. Quayle had flown here from Hawaii, where he
had spent several hours playing basketball and paying his last
respects to Col. Nick Rowe, the U.S. military adviser killed last
week in the Philippines.
   Quayle put on a dark suit to enter the cargo plane which carried
Rowe's body to Hickam Air Force Base in Honolulu. Declaring Rowe's
murder ``a cowardly act,'' Quayle said Rowe and other Americans
serve their country ``so we can have peace and freedom.''
   Leaving the plane in Pago Pago, the Quayles were greeted village
elders dressed in sarongs and carrying long walking sticks. About
2,000 school children waved small American flags and cheered as the
vice president and his wife, Marilyn, blotted sweat from their
brows in this tropical territory.
   After encouraging the Samoans to pursue their education, Quayle
said, ``I have the power to declare this a holiday _ you can have
the rest of the day off.''
   The crowd cheered with one man saying incredulously, ``It's a
public holiday.''
