<DOCNO> AP890425-0154 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-25-89 1752EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Mauritania     04-25 0490</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mauritania,0509</SECOND>
<HEAD>Curfew Ordered To Halt Violence Against Senegalese</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFFREY ULBRICH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NOUAKCHOTT, Mauritania (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gangs of angry Mauritanians armed
with sticks and clubs harassed Senegalese citizens and sacked their
shops Tuesday, forcing the government to impose a dusk-to-dawn
curfew.
   In the Senegalese capital of Dakar, 375 miles to the south,
anti-Mauritanian violence was not quelled until 4 a.m. Tuesday
after the army was called out and police resorted to tear gas.
   Both countries reinforced their troops along the Senegal River
border, as tensions mounted over a land dispute.
   Government officials in the two West African nations tried to
calm passions sparked by the April 9 killing of two Senegalese
farmers, allegedly shot by Mauritanian soldiers in Senegal's
Diawara border village. Two people have died in violence in Senegal
since then.
   Sporadic outbursts against Mauritanian shopkeepers in Dakar and
Senegalese in Nouakchott grew into widespread violence Sunday.
   ``Our compatriots must imperatively, no matter what pain they
have suffered, chase from their hearts the cowardly sentiment of
vengeance,'' Interior Minister Gibril Ould Abdallahy said in a
statement broadcast Tuesday on Mauritanian radio and television.
   He announced an 8 p.m. to 6 a.m. curfew in Nouakchott and
Nouadihbou, the principal port.
   A government source denied reports three people died in
Nouakchott violence, although he added officials do not have
complete casualty lists.
   Truckloads of police, some with riot helmets and shields, rushed
through the streets of this sand-blown capital of 500,000 people.
   Violence has been concentrated in poor quarters and shantytowns.
Angry crowds formed in dirt back streets, occasionally surging onto
a main artery to attack Senegalese and sometimes wreck or burn a
shop. Police broke up the crowds with tear gas and clubs.
   Knots of Mauritanians demanded to see ID cards and roughed up
those who did not prove they were Mauritanian.
   Mauritania straddles Arab north and black West Africa.
Two-thirds of its 2 million people are Moors of Arab-Berber
extraction. The rest are black, mostly from the southern river
region. Senegal's 7 million people almost all are black.
   In Dakar, many women and children sought refuge in the
Mauritanian Embassy, Ambassador Mokhtar Ould Zamel said. They were
escorted to the central mosque. Many have asked to be repatriated.
   Senegalese authorities said they arrested large numbers of
vandals, but did not confirm reports that hundreds have been
detained.
   This violence was sparked over the right of Senegalese to farm
on a Senegal River island.
   Even before the colonial period, the black Toucouleur people
farmed both sides of the Senegal River. After both countries became
independent from France in 1960, Senegalese Toucouleur continued to
farm the Mauritanian side they had considered their own for
generations.
   Moors to the north, traditionally nomadic herders, did not farm.
But the recent completion of two dams on the river has opened up
new farmland and spurred Mauritanian interest in agriculture. All
along the border, Senegalese are being forced off the land.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
