<DOCNO> AP890425-0155 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-25-89 1737EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-JFKStatue     04-25 0447</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-JFK Statue,0459</SECOND>
<HEAD>JFK's Daughter, Brother Help Launch Statewide Appeal For Statue Funds</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHELLE LOCKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Edward Kennedy joined a statewide appeal
Tuesday to raise money for a statue of his brother John, saying he
was glad the memorial focuses on the late president's birthday and
not the day he was assassinated.
   ``We do not want to relive my brother's death. We want to
remember his life,'' Kennedy said at a Statehouse news conference
that included the late president's daughter, Caroline Kennedy
Schlossberg, and Gov. Michael S. Dukakis.
   The 8-foot bronze statue is being created by artist Isabel
McIlvain of Sherborn, whose design was chosen through a nationwide
competition. It depicts Kennedy striding into a breeze, with his
left hand tucked in his pocket.
   State Rep. John MacGovern, co-chair of a special legislative
commission on the statue, said he was confident the sculpture would
be unveiled by May 19, 1990, the 73rd anniversary of Kennedy's
birth.
   ``At long last Massachusetts will properly remember and note the
wonderful contributions of this outstanding citizens and this
political hero for so many of us on both sides of the political
aisle,'' said MacGovern.
   About $60,000 has been raised so far of the overall fund-raising
goal, MacGovern said. The overall goal of $400,000 includes
maintenance funds and some scholarship money.
   Commission members say they want to raise the money in small
donations from each of the state's 351 cities and towns rather than
make corporate appeals. No public funds are to be used.
   ``They wanted this to be a presentation from the people. They
didn't want it just to be something the state was funding,'' said
Jim Burke, aide to state Sen. Paul White, co-chair with MacGovern.
   Although John F. Kennedy never served in the state government,
his brother said he had close ties to the Massachusetts political
tradition.
   He said the Kennedy family has been concerned that most tributes
to JFK focus on Nov. 22, 1963, the day Kennedy was shot, and he was
pleased with the planned May dedication of the sculpture.
   ``Now on the grounds of the statehouse he loved Jack will stand
... forever young,'' Kennedy said.
   Schlossberg spoke briefly, saying the statue will ``encourage
and inspire other people to dedicate their time and energy to
public service.''
   Dukakis said the statue and Kennedy's life commemorate the
importance of public service.
   ``One of the reasons I believe it's so important that we
remember this man in this place in front of this historic building
is it makes sure that here in the Commonwealth of Massachusetts we
have a constant reminder of what public service is all about,'' he
said.
</TEXT>
