<FILEID>AP-NR-04-25-89 1737EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-CatholicColleges     04-25 0515</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Catholic Colleges,0531</SECOND>
<HEAD>Educators Appeal for More Independence for Universities</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY BETH SHERIDAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VATICAN CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An international group of bishops and
educators urged the Vatican on Tuesday to safeguard academic
independence in Roman Catholic universities.
   The appeal came at the conclusion of a weeklong meeting to
assess a draft of a major Vatican document on Catholic higher
education. The draft has drawn sharp criticism from college
officials who charge it could undermine academic freedom.
   Delegates from the United States, which has the world's largest
Catholic college system, said at a news conference Tuesday they are
optimistic the Vatican will heed the representatives' wishes.
   But the final document must be approved by Pope John Paul II. In
a closing address to the conference, the pope called for a ``more
strict and faithful collaboration'' between the universities and
the Catholic hierarchy.
   The representatives, in a near-unanimous vote, said the document
should contain non-binding guidelines that are general and
inspirational, rather than specific.
   ``My impression is that the Congregation will do a major
rewrite,'' said the Rev. Raymond Fitz, president of the University
of Dayton in Ohio, referring to the Vatican's Congregation for
Catholic Education.
   The first draft of the education document, issued in 1985,
assigned church authorities some power over Catholic colleges and
universities to ensure that teachers adhered to church doctrine and
``uprightness of life.''
   Those teachers judged not doing so would be subject to dismissal.
   The document, circulated to educators and bishops, drew strong
protests, and a second draft was prepared and presented at the
meeting this week.
   About 175 college presidents, bishops and education experts from
40 countries discussed the draft with Vatican officials and came up
with 10 recommendations for a third version.
   The new proposals say the Vatican document ``should be positive,
inspirational and future-oriented'' and that Catholic universities
must be allowed to run themselves.
   ``Freedom of research and teaching must be recognized and
respected,'' the proposals said.
   Deciding how ``Catholic'' a Catholic university must be is a
touchy issue. The Vatican under John Paul is trying to eliminate
the confusion it blames on the teaching of dissident theologians
and to strengthen the church through emphasis on traditional
principles.
   At the same time, many universities say they must allow
exploration of new theories, however unorthodox, as part of their
role as centers of research and study.
   Many of the U.S. officials said they were surprised to find the
Vatican very receptive to their ideas.
   ``This is innovative as Vatican congregations operate _ far more
participatory,'' said the Rev. William Byron, president of Catholic
University of America in Washington, D.C. ``We've gotten a step
further down the line.''
   Several representatives and Vatican officials at the conference
formed a 15-member committee that will review the third draft of
the document this fall. U.S. officials said it was significant that
the Congregation would ask college officials for another opinion.
   But the college representatives and bishops at this week's
meeting play only an advisory role, and Vatican officials and the
pope will decide the shape of the final paper.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890425-0157 </DOCNO>
