<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Finland-Soviet     04-25 0156</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Finland-Soviet,0160</SECOND>
<HEAD>Finnish Physicians to Open Health Center in Leningrad</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HELSINKI, Finland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A private Finnish medical center will
open a branch in Leningrad for tourists, foreign residents and
Soviet citizens with hard currency, doctors said Tuesday.
   The health center will open in July and will employ Finnish
doctors and Soviet staff. The medicines and equipment will be from
western countries, and the center will have its own laboratory,
X-ray equipment and ultrasound scanners, doctors said.
   A visit to a physician will cost about $71, said Harri Eloranta,
a specialist at the Pinsetti Medical Center in Riihimaki, in
southern Finland. The center owns 70 percent of the joint venture
known as Lenfinmed.
   Eloranta said the goal was to provide reliable basic services.
   Lenfinmed has been given permission to expand to other cities in
the Soviet Union and will open similar centers in Moscow, Tallinn,
Vyborg and Shotshi, if the Leningrad experiment works, Eloranta
said.
</TEXT>
