<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Norway-Activists     04-25 0171</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Norway-Activists,0178</SECOND>
<HEAD>Environmental Activists Mobbed by Norwegian Villagers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SOKNDAL, Norway (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A mob of 100 villagers drove off
environmentalists who had chained themselves to a wharf for 19
hours to protest alleged pollution by the town's main employer,
news reports said Tuesday.
   The four activists were roughed up and sprayed with water from
firehoses after protesting against the ilmenite mine run by Titania
A-S, which they say dumps ecologically damaging waste into a nearby
fiord. The mine employs about 350 people in the town of 3,500
people.
   Environmentalists want the residues dumped on land instead of
the ocean but Titania has said it obeys state guidelines.
   Titania, owned by N.L. Chemicals Inc., of Hightstown, N.J., in
1983 became the object of Norway's first major protest against an
alleged industrial polluter.
   ``I don't understand why they were so furious. We have been
holding protests here since 1983 and know many of the villagers,''
said Rune Haaland, one of the activists.
   No one was injured, according to the Oslo newspaper Aftenposten.
</TEXT>
