<FILEID>AP-NR-04-25-89 1932EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-VocationalEducation     04-25 0232</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Vocational Education,200</SECOND>
<HEAD>House Panel Approves Program</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A House committee on Wednesday approved a $1.4
billion bill reauthorizing the federal vocational training program,
after first removing a requirement that certain amounts be set
aside for certain groups.
   However, the measure stipulates that the states are to make sure
the money is distributed in the most effective way that also
insures fair treatment for particular segments of the population _
such as the physically handicapped, single parents and those who do
not speak English.
   The Bush administration opposed writing into the law a specific
amount to be spent on certain categories of people and the panel
members had heard testimony prior to final action on the bill that
the set-asides had not proved effective.
   The Carl D. Perkins Vocational Education Act of 1984, which
expires Sept. 30, says 10 percent of the grants are to go to the
handicapped, 22 percent to the disadvantaged, 12 percent to adults,
8.5 percent to single parents and homemakers, 3.5 percent to
elimination of sex bias, and 1 percent to the incarcerated.
   The Bush administration had requested $949 million for fiscal
year 1990, up from the current $918 million. However, critics said
that level would amount to a cut because it would not keep pace
with inflation.
   The measure is expected to reach the House floor next month,
where easy passage is anticipated.
</TEXT>
