<FIRST>r w AM-Nixon     04-25 0349</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nixon,340</SECOND>
<HEAD>House Panel Moves to Impeach Imprisoned Judge</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A House committee acted Wednesday to impeach
federal Judge Walter L. Nixon of Mississippi before he is released
from federal prison and returns to the District Court to hear cases.
   ``I believe that Judge Nixon should have had the good grace to
resign when his appeals were exhausted,'' Rep. James Sensenbrenner,
R-Wis., said as the Judiciary Committee approved three articles of
impeachment 34-0.
   The full House is planning floor action on the articles of
impeachment this week. If they are approved, Nixon would stand
impeached and be tried later by the Senate with House members
acting as prosecutors.
   The Senate is currently preparing to hear evidence in the trial
of Judge Alcee L. Hastings of Florida, who was impeached by the
House last year even though he was acquitted in 1983 of plotting to
obtain payoffs.
   The articles accuse Nixon of lying to a federal grand jury and
Justice Department investigators looking into the oil and gas
investment that was arranged for him by a wealthy businessman,
Wiley Fairchild.
   Nixon is accused of bringing the federal judiciary into
disrepute and undermining its integrity by claiming he never played
any role in a case involving marijuana smuggling charges against
Fairchild's son.
   He already is serving two concurrent five-year perjury sentences
imposed after he was convicted in 1986. Since then, he has
collected $286,000 in federal judicial salary and plans, when he is
released in a few months, to return to the bench and try cases,
according to authorities.
   Defense attorney David Stewart says that some of the statements
cited as instances of perjury were factual and that in any case
Nixon never did anything that warranted impeachment. He says Nixon
was subjected to ``a sensationalized investigation and an unfair
trial.''
   Lawmakers said they were unable to agree with Stewart's
contentions in the course of their investigation of Nixon.
   ``His pattern of lies and deceit led ... to the inevitable
conclusion that he has to be impeached,'' said Rep. Don Edwards,
D-Calif.
</TEXT>
