<FIRST>r a AM-SeditionTrial     04-25 0491</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sedition Trial,0503</SECOND>
<HEAD>Odd Twists Mark Trial Of Three Radicals</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROLYN LUMSDEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SPRINGFIELD, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sworn statements about a dog that
understood Estonian and trysts between a defense attorney and
courtroom marshal are some of the odd turns a long trial of three
leftist militants has taken.
   Tuesday was day 37 of testimony and arguments in the federal
trial of two men and a woman accused of plotting to overthrow the
United States government by force. The charge also known as
seditious conspiracy rarely has been used since it was invoked
during the Civil War to prosecute Confederate loyalists.
   Despite the historical weight of the proceeding, which involves
some of the major violent radicals of the 1970s, the dozen or so
marshals guarding the courtroom usually far outnumber the few
spectators.
   The 17-member jury yawned and fidgeted through Monday's skirmish
between defendant Raymond Luc Levasseur, dressed in blue jeans, and
Georgia Hill, a gray-suited Detroit lawyer who was friends with
some associates of the defendants when she studied at Harvard Law
School a decade ago.
   Levasseur, who is serving as his own lawyer, has accused Hill
and others of informing on the radicals, who sometimes called
themselves the United Freedom Front and are accused of bombing
buildings and robbing banks around the Northeast from 1975 to 1981.
   ``I would like you to cooperate, although not as much as you did
with the FBI,'' Levasseur said, in the kind of bitter aside that
jurors have come to expect of him.
   Hill was the 91st witness on the stand, and prosecutors are only
a quarter of the way into their witness list.
   Levasseur, 42, faces a maximum of 60 years in prison if
convicted on three charges of seditious conspiracy, racketeering
and racketeering conspiracy. On trial on the same charges are his
wife, Patricia Gros Levasseur, 40, and Richard Williams, 41.
   There were seven defendants at the time of the initial jury
selection in March 1988. Prosecutors dropped charges against Thomas
Manning and Jaan Karl Laaman, already serving lengthy sentences on
other charges. Manning's wife, Carol Manning, pleaded guilty to
sedition and other charges, and a separate trial was ordered for
Laaman's wife, Barbara Curzi-Laaman.
   Assistant U.S. Attorney Michael Loucks questioned Hill on April
13 about a dog she said former co-defendant Jaan Karl Laaman had
taught commands in Estonian.
   ``Did you ever hear him talk to the dog?'' Young asked her.
   She replied: ``A couple of commands, like sort of `sit' and
`stop.'''
   Young later struck the comments, saying, ``I can't for the life
of me see how that would be a statement made in furtherance of the
conspiracy.''
   Ms. Curzi-Laaman's attorney, Linda J. Thompson, and a U.S.
marshal assigned to guard the courthouse during the trial were the
subject of an April 7 hearing for their love affair during jury
selection. A judge found that the pair had not discussed court
business during the liaison.
</TEXT>
