<FILEID>AP-NR-04-25-89 1939EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-North-NBC     04-25 0218</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-North-NBC,210</SECOND>
<HEAD>North Lawyers Ask ``Appropriate Relief'' After NBC Letters to Jurors</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-North Trial</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oliver North's lawyers asked the trial judge
Tuesday to determine after the verdict how jurors might have been
influenced by an NBC News request to interview them after the trial
ends.
   ``The defense further requests that the court grant appropriate
relief after the hearing,'' said the motion filed by Brendan
Sullivan while the jury was deliberating for the fourth day.
   On Saturday, NBC hand-delivered letters to the jurors' homes,
saying ``we would like to talk to you after the trial is over;
please call us then.'' Learning of this, U.S. District Judge
Gerhard A. Gesell convened a hearing and called the attempt ``most
inappropriate, improper conduct, quite disrespectful.''
   In his motion, Sullivan took note of Gesell's remark that one
``juror was angry and must have mentioned the fact to other jurors
who immediately showed similar concern.''
   Sullivan said the hearing should determine ``whether the jurors'
reaction to the letter has prejudiced defendant North.''
   An NBC News spokeswoman said after Gesell's remarks that the
network had meant no harm and had assumed the jurors wouldn't see
the letters until after arriving home after the trial. Until they
reach a verdict, the jurors are sequestered in a motel while not
deliberating.
</TEXT>
