<DOCNO> AP890425-0167 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-25-89 1856EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Quake-Tourists     04-25 0644</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Quake-Tourists,0672</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hotels Swayed Like Flagpoles in Quake, Some Tourists Leave</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Mexico-Quake, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRIS ANGELO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tourists said the capital's luxury hotels
swayed like flagpoles in Tuesday's earthquake and it felt like a
rollercoaster ride, frightening some so badly they cut short their
vacations and headed for more stable ground.
   ``We were in bed and she thought I was shaking the bed and I
thought the people next door were shaking the walls,'' said Les
Giddings of Miami as he and his wife, Maria, checked out of the
Hotel Krystal in the Zona Rosa tourist area.
   They were a day and a half into their honeymoon when the quake
hit at 8:26 a.m.
   ``Once it really got going you could hear a rumble. It felt like
a good rollercoaster ride,'' said Giddings.
   Two hairline cracks ran down the walls, one in the bedroom, one
in the bathroom, popping chips of paint off the walls. Running down
the stairs from their 10th floor room after the motion stopped,
they saw chunks of plaster scattered about.
   They had planned to go to the Pacific coast resort of Acapulco
but changed their minds when they heard the quake was centered near
there.
   ``We're going anywhere in the States,'' Mrs. Giddings said,
``It's a terrifying experience.''
   She said Disneyworld was one possibility.
   Tourists at other hotels said they saw other people checking
out, cutting vacations short because of the quake, which measured
6.8 on the Richter scale.
   Across the street, in the Century Hotel, Cobe Eekels-Bakker of
Amstelveen, the Netherlands, at first thought she was ill, then
noticed that everything was moving back and forth.
   ``I could see through my window stones and dirt coming down,''
she said.
   Although slowed by an already existing hip injury, she grabbed
her purse and cane to run down the steps from her eighth-floor room.
   ``Everybody was going past me. Then somebody took me and brought
me downstairs quickly,'' she said.
   ``I have cried,'' she said, sitting in the lobby more than an
hour later, still shaken.
   The quake sloshed water from the hotel's rooftop pool, over the
walls onto cars parked on the street 23 floors below.
   Three hours later, Sheila and Don Walters of Westport, Conn.,
who had been staying in the Maria Isabel Sheraton, said they
decided to continue their vacation and go on to Acapulco.
   ``I'm still actually dizzy from it,'' Mrs. Walters said. ``I
don't feel I have my legs under me yet.''
   She remembered sitting in their sixth-floor room, waking up with
a cup of coffee just before the quake.
   ``There was a Do Not Disturb sign on the inside of the door
wiggling. I was sitting there, trying to wake up, wondering what
was making the sign move.'' About five minutes later, the whole
building began shaking.
   ``I felt like I was going to pass out. I was really frightened,
it was a sort of panic attack,'' she said.
   But her husband, everyone agreed, stayed calm throughout.
   ``It was like being on the top of a flagpole,'' he said.
   Richard Cummings of Selden, N.Y., recovering from a two-day bout
of illness, tried to get out of bed when he heard the bathroom door
bang and felt the building sway.
   ``It was strong enough to make me fall back down on my bed when
I got up,'' he said. ``That's when I realized what was happening.''
   Lauren Wilson of Henley-on-Thames, England, had been in an
earthquake in Japan but said it was ``not as bad as this.''
   She called her husband Phil from the bathroom of their
15th-floor room.
   ``We sat on the bed and held each other,'' she said.
   ``We could just see our building moving relative to the other
buildings,'' he said. While it seemed like a lot, it looked like
about a foot, he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
