<FIRST>r a AM-CubanFamily     04-25 0428</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cuban Family,0438</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. May Allow Stranded Family To Return</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DARREN DOPP</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUFFALO, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Cuban family from Florida that was
stranded in Canada after a sightseeing trip five months ago may
soon be granted political asylum, U.S. immigration officials said
Tuesday.
   Carlos Fajardo has provided information that substantiates his
claim that he would face political persecution if returned to Cuba,
said Benedict Ferro, district director of the federal Immigration
and Naturalization Service.
   ``It is not a frivolous claim,'' Ferro said. ``We would not turn
people away under those circumstances.''
   Ferro would not discuss details of the case but did say that
pending a State Department review of the case, the Fajardos might
be allowed to return in a few weeks.
   Fajardo, his wife, Bermaida Zamora-Powers, and her two children,
Yoradlys Diaz and Yoandys Diaz, have lived on charity since Dec.
23, when they were denied re-entry into the United States at the
Rainbow Bridge in Niagara Falls because they are illegal aliens.
The couple told border authorities that they had driven north to
find snow for Christmas and had ventured into Canada to view the
falls.
   The family lived for several weeks in a Niagara Falls, Ontario,
motel, then in a Fort Erie apartment under the sponsorship of
Ontario refugee groups.
   ``It looks like we may finally be able to work something out,''
said Sister Kathleen Rimar, Fajardo's Catholic Charities attorney
in Buffalo.
   Last month, Ferro denied Fajardo's application to return to
Miami on humanitarian parole. Despite pressure from charitable
organizations and from Sen. Bob Graham, D-Fla., Ferro had insisted
that the family not be readmitted because of their record of
immigration fraud and other unspecified evidence.
   Immigration officials said Tuesday Fajardo and his wife still
are guilty of substantial fraud against the U.S. government and
other offenses. But they also said such violations can be
overlooked in light of concern over possible persecution.
   Information regarding the potential for persecution for Fajardo
in Cuba, they added, was not available until he was allowed to
enter the United States late last month for an interview with
immigration officials in Buffalo.
   Sister Rimar said that, for the first time since December, the
family has some hope of returning to the Miami area. But their stay
in Canada has exhausted their resources, she said.
   ``Their situation is a mess,'' she said. ``They have no home or
business to return to, and they're in danger of having their car
repossessed. They'll have to start off basically with nothing and
work their way back again.''
</TEXT>
