<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Hostages,0196</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviet Prisoner Killed, Hostages Unharmed in Attempted Camp Break</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police and KGB officers killed one inmate and
captured two others who had taken four woman hostage and demanded
to be freed from a prison camp in the Soviet Far East, Tass said
Tuesday.
   The escape attempt Monday was the second this month that
involved hostages and resulted in a prisoner's death, the Soviet
news agency said.
   The convicts at a camp in Khabarovsk took the women employees
hostage, and demanded safe passage, submachine guns and
bullet-proof vests, Tass said.
   After negotiations failed, KGB and police shot and killed one
prisoner and disarmed the other two, Tass reported.
   Tass said the women were released unhurt, but further details
were not immediately available.
   Khabarovsk is located on the Amur River near the Soviet border
with the Manchurian area of China.
   On April 12, two armed inmates of a Ukrainian prison colony
armed with home-made weapons sneaked into an administrative
building and took eight women hostage, demanding a bus and safe
passage. One prisoner was killed and the other wounded by police
gunfire, Tass said.
