<FILEID>AP-NR-04-25-89 1900EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-GingrichBook     04-25 0669</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Gingrich Book,630</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gingrich Denies Helping Book Investors With Their Government Problems</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID PACE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   House Republican Whip Newt Gingrich said
Tuesday that none of the 22 investors in a partnership created to
promote a book he co-authored ever received ``unusual or
extraordinary personal help'' from him in their dealings with the
federal government.
   But Gingrich, during a stormy news conference which his wife
left in anger, acknowledged that some of the investors had a direct
interest in legislation and that he had handled routine requests
from some of them.
   While House rules prohibit members from accepting gifts worth
more than $100 from people with direct interest in legislation,
Gingrich said the partnership did not violate House rules because
the $5,000 that each investor put into the deal did not constitute
a gift.
   Rep. Bill Alexander, D-Ark., has filed a formal complaint with
the House ethics committee alleging that the partnership involved
10 apparent violations of House rules. The committee has not
indicated whether it will launch a preliminary investigation of the
complaint.
   Gingrich, who initiated the investigation that led to House
Speaker Jim Wright's being charged with 69 violations of House
rules last week, said he was satisfied that each investor in the
partnership ``thought there was a reasonable chance that it might
make money.''
   In exchange for their investments, the 19 individuals and three
corporations that formed the COS Limited Partnership in 1984 were
promised half of the publisher's profits from the book, ``Window of
Opportunity,'' written by Gingrich; his wife, Marianne Gingrich,
and David Drake.
   According to hundreds of pages of financial documents and tax
returns released Tuesday by Gingrich, the partnership spent $51,571
to promote and advertise the book from 1984 through 1986, but the
publisher still had a net loss of $6,259 on the book by the end of
1987.
   Because the partnership received no profits from book sales, the
$104,185 loss it generated from 1984 to 1988 was distributed among
the partners, providing them with tax writeoffs.
   Mrs. Gingrich, as general partner of the partnership, received a
$10,000 payment in 1984 for setting up the organization, and later
received a 2 percent interest in the partnership and a $1,500
payment, according to the documents. She did not invest any of her
own money in the partnership.
   Alexander's complaint alleges in part that the payments and
ownership interest in the partnership that Mrs. Gingrich received
were gifts that violated House rules limiting gifts members may
receive.
   The complaint parallels the ethics committee's allegation that
the salary and benefits Wright's wife, Betty, received from an
investment corporation were actually gifts because there was no
evidence that Mrs. Wright did any work for the corporation.
   Mrs. Gingrich said Tuesday that she kept all the records for the
partnership, interviewed potential investors to ensure they were
qualified and handled the filings necessary to comply with various
state securities laws.
   She left the news conference abruptly after telling reporters
she was upset that no one seemed interested in going through the
350 pages of tax returns, financial records and incorporation
papers that she had put together in response to questions about the
book deal.
   Gingrich defended his wife, telling reporters that unlike Mrs.
Wright, ``she actually did the work for the money she got.'' He
said the 350 pages of documents ``represent her work product.''
   Gingrich said he was willing to concede that the book
partnership was ``unusual.'' But he said there was nothing
``unethical'' in the deal, which he described as markedly different
from the financial arrangements for Wright's book, ``Reflections of
a Public Man.''
   ``We wrote a real book, working with a real publisher
distributed to real bookstores and sold to real people for a
realistic, standard royalty,'' he said. ``Jim Wright did none of
those things.''
   Part of the ethics committee's charges against Wright allege
that he violated House rules on outside income limits though bulk
sales of his book, on which he received a 55 percent royalty.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
