<FILEID>AP-NR-04-25-89 1739EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Japan-Scandal     04-25 0486</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Scandal,0504</SECOND>
<HEAD>Future Of Longtime Governing Party Uncertain</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Japan, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID THURBER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The absence of strong, untainted leaders in the
governing Liberal Democratic Party was a big reason Prime Minister
Noboru Takeshita held on so long through a personally painful and
damaging scandal.
   Takeshita, 65, was in power only 18 months and had to deal from
his first days in office with the multimillion dollar scandal
involving the Recruit information conglomerate.
   He announced Tuesday he will resign. That had been expected, but
it still left the Liberal Democratic Party, which has been in
control since 1948, foundering.
   Takeshita was LDP president, and that assured him of becoming
prime minister in November 1987 when Prime Minister Yasuhiro
Nakosone retired.
   And although the new LDP president could expect to become prime
minister, the party is riddled with factions.
   ``Many of the leaders of factions inside the LDP are themselves
involved in the Recruit scandal, so it would be difficult to find
someone to take Takeshita's place,'' said Seisaburo Sato, a
political science professor at Tokyo University.
   Unlike questions of personal finances in the 1970s that led to
the resignation of Prime Minister Kakuei Tanaka, the Recruit
scandal has scarred virtually all the LDP factions.
   Political analaysts said the plunge of Takeshita's popularity in
public opinion polls to less than 4 percent reflected broad
opposition to the political system, often characterized by
back-room dealings.
   ``I feel deeply responsible for having fostered such distrust,''
Takeshita said in his resignation announcment. He said he would
leave office after parliament approves the budget for fiscal 1989.
   The Recruit scandal created a stalemate in Parliament with a
boycott of the budget debate by opposition members demanding former
Prime Minister Yasuhiro Nakasone be called for questioning about
payments and stock deals by Recruit to politicians and the LDP.
   For many people the scandal revealed the extent of unreported
money flowing between business and government. Analysts, noting the
years the LDP has governed, suggested a system of ``structural
corruption'' had been created.
   Some LDP members, including reform leader Masayoshi Takemura,
have said the party may not be able to end its dependence on large
sums of money from the business world and maintain its dominance.
   ``Sometimes I think we may have to dissolve the party and start
again from zero,'' Takemura said last week.
   Takako Doi, head of the Socialist Party, told other opposition
leaders at a strategy session this month that the scandal offered a
rare opportunity to wrest power from the LDP.
   ``This is a time of unprecedented importance,'' she said.
   Fuyuko Kamisaka, a prominent writer on women's and consumer
issues, suggested in a television interview that an independent
panel be appointed to supervise political reforms.
   ``I hope that someone not directly linked to the political world
can lead a fundamental reform of politics that will eliminate the
flow of `strange' money,'' she said.
</TEXT>
