<FIRST>r w AM-AM-Japan-Fighter 1stLd-Writethru a0676 04-25 0614</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-AM-Japan-Fighter, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0676,580</SECOND>
<HEAD>Resignation Held Likely to Delay FSX Project</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Japan, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Adds 2 grafs White House comment</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japanese Prime Minister Noboru Takeshita's
resignation likely will further delay action on the controversial
FSX fighter project, official sources said Tuesday.
   Some high-level sources suggested the end result could be a
weaker deal for the United States, or a complete unraveling of the
plan to jointly build a new fighter based on the American F-16.
   Takeshita's announcement that he would step down as a result of
an influence-peddling scandal brings new uncertainty to the
already-troubled FSX plan, said administration and congressional
officials, all of whom declined to be identified.
   The sources suggested it is now unlikely there will be any
movement in stalled negotiations on the project until a successor
to Takeshita takes office.
   ``It's not on the verge of being resolved now anyway,'' said one
administration soucre.
   ``We're continuing to try to clarify the conditions'' on the
project set down a month ago by U.S. negotiators. ``It's proven to
be a very difficult process.''
   Although President Bush signaled general support for the joint
venture in mid-March, Japanese officials balked at some of the
conditions he stipulated _ including a guarantee that U.S.
companies have a 40 percent share in the production of the new jet.
   The United States also wants assurances that any new technology
developed from the project would be available to the United States,
along with protection for U.S.-developed computer codes that help
fly and control the plane.
   The agreement to co-develop the FSX, which stands for Fighter
Support Experimental, was negotiated late last year between
Takeshita's government and the outgoing Reagan adminstration.
   Under the agreement, General Dynamics Corp. would build the
upgraded F-16 with Japan's Mitsubishi Heavy Industries.
   The plan encountered stiff opposition in the
Democratic-controlled Congress, where critics have called it a $7
billion giveaway of high technology to Japan _ suggesting the
United States would get little in return.
   Takeshita's resignation will make it ``harder to deal with the
issue,'' said Rep. Richard Gephardt, D-Mo.
   ``I think the position of the Japanese will be that, because
they're in a difficult circumstance, they can't give as much as
they might have on FSX,'' Gephardt said in an interview.
   He also said that the Japanese government might use the current
political turmoil there to its advantage in seeking U.S.
concessions in other U.S.-Japanese trade disputes.
   Proponents of the FSX project claim it represents a way to add
fighters to Japan's inventory in strategic northeast Asia at its
own expense and would give the United States access to
sophisticated radar technology developedby Mitsubishi.
   One congressional source involved in trade issues said that any
further delay in the project now would let Japan strengthen its
negotiating hand.
   ``Japan's final response on the FSX clearly had to be signed off
on by the prime minister. But there was divided counsel in Japan on
the terms and he (Takeshita) obviously has been preoccupied. This
will give them a chance to get their act together and play trade
hardball.''
   Any effort by Japan to demand further concessions from the
United States could jeopardize a project that already has thin
support in Congress, possibly torpedoing the plan entirely, said
both administration and congressional sources.
   Traveling with Bush in California, presidential spokesman Marlin
Fitzwater was asked what impact Takeshita's resignation might have
on the FSX project. ``We don't really know how it might affect that
deal,'' he said.
   Asked if the White House still favored moving ahead with the
agreement, with the new qualifications, Fitzwater said, ``Our
position is the same, we still hope so.''
</TEXT>
