<FIRST>r i AM-Suriname-Rebels     04-25 0239</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Suriname-Rebels,0248</SECOND>
<HEAD>Surinamese Rebels Shatter Lull With Village Attack</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARAMARIBO, Suriname (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jungle rebels broke a six-month lull
in their uprising by attacking a village, where they killed one
man, kidnapped two others, and set fire to homes, the state news
agency reported Tuesday.
   Witnesses said about 40 insurgents of a group known as the
Jungle Commando attacked Pokigron, about 100 miles south of this
capital city, early Sunday despite resistance by villagers armed
with shotguns.
   The attackers beat, stabbed, and then shot a man they suspected
to be an army spy, according to the state-run Suriname News Agency.
The victim later died in the hospital.
   The rebels also burned some homes and kidnapped the village
chief and a second man, the news agency said. The rebels doused the
chief with gasoline and threatened to burn him alive but halted
when villagers begged them to stop, the agency said.
   About 100 villagers fled to Paramaribo after the assault, the
news agency said. The insurgents reportedly escaped.
   The attack was the most serious in this former Dutch colony on
the northeastern coast of South America since cease-fire talks with
the government of President Ramsewak Shankar stalled in October
1988.
   Witnesses said Sunday's attackers were led by Ronny Brunswijk, a
one-time army private who began the uprising in 1986. More than 400
people, mostly civilians, have been killed in the rebellion.
   The insurgents have not publicly stated their grievances.
</TEXT>
