<DOCNO> AP890425-0175 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-25-89 1747EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Iran     04-25 0628</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Iran,0646</SECOND>
<HEAD>Iran Paper Supports Rafsanjani As Post-Khomeini Leader</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NICK LUDINGTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A prominent Iranian newspaper on Tuesday
backed Parliament Speaker Hashemi Rafsanjani to head a leadership
council that would eventually succeed the 88-year-old Ayatollah
Ruhollah Khomeini.
   The state-controlled Ettelaat daily said in an editorial that no
single possible substitute for Khomeini existed ``when it comes to
knowledge and jurisprudence especially in the area of government .
.. or when such other factors as record of struggle or political
intuition is concerned.''
   It suggested a leadership council made up of present state
administrators and leading religious authorities in which one
member ``would be capable of saying the last word on matters of
dispute and able to adopt decisions on his own responsibility.''
   ``If we were to make a decision on the basis of a grade point
average of a candidate it seems ... Rafsanjani has the necessary
qualifications for heading the leadership council,'' Etelaat said.
   ``In all countries and with every leadership council there is
one member entitled to veto the vote of the rest.''
   It was the first public backing for a Khomeini successor since
Khomeini forced Ayatollah Hossein Ali Montazeri to step down last
month as his officially designated successor.
   Rafsanjani is a leading candidate for president in elections
scheduled to be held this year to choose a successor to Ali
Khamenei, who is not permitted by the constitution to run for a
third four-year term.
   But under Iran's present system, the president divides power
with the prime minister and Parliament, all of them subject to the
authority of Khomeini. The revolutionary patriarch's separate
status as spiritual leader is unmatched and unlikely to be filled
after he dies, Iranian political experts say.
   Ettelaat's endorsement significantly boosts Rafsanjani's status
in current political infighting.
   Rafsanjani kept a low profile in a recent purge of moderates and
in the international outcry over Khomeini's death sentence decree
for British author Salman Rushdie. Rafsanjani is considered a
pragmatist able to maneuver between hard-line theologians and
others who wanted to soften the harsh Islamic revolution and end
Iran's international isolation.
   On Friday, he announced the discovery of a U.S. spy network
including senior Iranian naval officers, a move apparently aimed at
gaining points with the hardliners.
   On Saturday, Rafsanjani, 54, who also holds the post of acting
commander in chief of the armed forces, received backing for his
presidential campaign from an influential party of hardliners, the
Assembly of Combatant Theologians.
   And on Monday, Khomeini included Rafsanjani in a 20-man
committee given two months to ``rectify defects'' in Iran's 1980
revolutionary constitution. One task, Khomeini said, was to
consider the leadership question.
   Rafsanjani has been campaigning for a constitutional change
giving the president more power and abolishing the prime ministry.
   Prime Minister Hussein Musavi meanwhile said Tuesday that the
U.S. spy network which Rafsanjani reported uncovered recently had
direct contact with CIA offices in neighboring countries. Some
agents communicated with the Americans through West German
embassies in Europe, he said.
   Tehran radio, monitored in Nicosia, quoted Musavi as saying in
an interview with the state-owned Islamic Republic News Agency that
the West Germans ``should know their embassies are at the service
of the American spy network.''
   He said some agents were in ``sensitive positions'' with access
to top secret information which they passed on to the Americans,
the radio reported.
   Musavi said the purported U.S. actions violated the Algiers
agreement, which stipulates non-interference by the United States
and Iran in each other's domestic affairs. He was apparently
referring to a 1980 accord under which Iran released 52 U.S.
diplomats held hostage in Tehran for 444 days.
   Musavi said Iran would lodge a complaint against America at the
International Court of Justice at the Hague.
</TEXT>
