<DOCNO> AP890425-0176 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-25-89 1951EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-S&amp;Ls     04-25 0735</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-S&amp;Ls,690</SECOND>
<HEAD>Panel's Chairman Asks Members to Resist Lobbyists' Pressure</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The chairman of the House Banking Committee,
on the eve of public sessions to write savings and loan bailout
legislation, privately appealed to fellow Democrats Tuesday to
resist pressure from industry lobbyists or face the anger of
taxpayers.
   Rep. Henry B. Gonzalez, D-Texas, at a closed-door caucus of the
panel's Democrats, urged support for requiring S&amp;L owners to back
their lending with more of their own money, calling it ``the litmus
test on whether anything has changed'' and ``the guts of this whole
issue.''
   Capital investment from S&amp;L stockholders acts as a cushion,
absorbing losses that would otherwise have to be paid by government
deposit insurance. Gonzalez is attempting to persuade his 51-member
committee to toughen the standards passed earlier this month by the
panel's 47-member subcommittee on financial institutions, chaired
by Rep. Frank Annunzio, D-Ill.
   More than 100 amendments are pending before the committee, which
in sessions scheduled Wednesday and Thursday is expected to re-hash
many of the battles fought during during 32 hours of subcommittee
deliberations.
   Gonzalez, who is joined by Rep. Chalmers Wylie of Ohio, the
panel's senior Republican, would require institutions to hold $2.25
in ``tangible'' or ``real money'' capital for every $100 in loans,
compared with $1.50 in versions of the legislation passed by the
House subcommittee and the full Senate.
   ``Inadequate capital standards simply mean that we let the
industry, once again, roll the dice with the taxpayers' money,'' he
said in a statement prepared for delivery at the caucus.
   Gonzalez is trying to raise the visibility of the complex
capital issue, which is at the heart of President Bush's savings
and loan proposal. In the past, industry lobbyists have heavily
influenced congressional decisions on banking laws because most
voters don't follow the issues.
   With taxpayers picking up the bulk of the 10-year, $157 billion
S&amp;L bailout, however, Gonzalez told his colleagues that `the
decisions will be tough _ and they will be watched.''
   ``The choice may be difficult, but, as Democrats, we had better
be able to say, `When the choice was presented, we sided with the
taxpayers,''' he said.
   Rep. Barney Frank, D-Mass., predicted, ``The capital standards
are going to look pretty kosher to the president by the time we're
through.''
   ``There's intense lobbying by people in the industry, but I also
think ... there's a view that if the committee votes $100 billion
without a tough bill, sooner or later the public will react,'' said
Rep. Charles Schumer, D-N.Y., who is supporting Gonzalez' capital
amendment.
   However, Rep. John LaFalce, D-N.Y., argued that Gonzalez was
trying to precipitously impose ``lily white, absolutely pure''
standards on S&amp;Ls. He warned that if S&amp;Ls were not permitted to
gradually improve their condition, the government's list of
troubled institutions will swell.
   ``I honestly believe that if we prescribe this medicine for our
troubled financial system, the medicine will be so strong that it
will, if not kill the system, at least exacerbate the problem
multifold,'' he said.
   In addition to raising the tangible capital requirement,
Gonzalez is also trying to tighten two other standards: one
affecting an accounting item known as ``goodwill,''' the other the
treatment of S&amp;L subsidiaries.
   According to the Federal Home Loan Bank Board, more than
one-third of the S&amp;L industry's $60 billion in capital consists of
``goodwill,'' an intangible asset representing the value of an
institution's customer loyalty and name recognition.
   The Bush administration is seeking to eliminate ``goodwill''
value over 10 years, arguing that it is ``phantom capital'' and has
no worth when an institution is shut down. The bill passed by
Annunzio's subcommittee would permit goodwill, in some cases, to
remain on institutions' books for as long as 40 years. Gonzalez is
proposing it be phased out over 20 years.
   The Gonzalez plan gives S&amp;Ls five years to come up with extra
capital to back subsidiaries investing in risky areas such as
commercial real estate and junk bonds. The subcommittee bill did
not require the extra capital.
   The Associated Press, based on a staff document, reported Monday
that Gonzalez would permit subordinated debt _ money S&amp;Ls borrow _
to count for up to one-half of an institution's core capital. Aides
explained Tuesday, however, that while subordinated debt will be
permitted in capital, it will not be counted toward meeting the
very minimum, or core, requirement.
</TEXT>
