<FILEID>AP-NR-04-25-89 1959EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-SpottedOwl     04-25 0556</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Spotted Owl,520</SECOND>
<HEAD>Agency Will Tell Court Owl Worthy Of Protection</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LES BLUMENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service said
Tuesday it has dediced after all that the spotted owl is worthy of
protection as a threatened species.
   Environmentalists hope the decision will save the ancient
forests of the Northwest. The timber industry says the move could
lock up vast areas of the region to logging.
   A federal judge in Seattle had given the agency until Monday to
review its decision of more than a year ago not to list the owl
under the Endangered Species Act.
   ``We will present a finding to the court that listing of the owl
as a threatened species is warranted and begin steps to officially
propose it for listing,'' said Meg Durham, a spokeswoman for the
Fish and Wildlife Service.
   Once the owl is proposed for listing as a threatened species, a
year-long review will begin during which management plans for
protection of the bird could be developed and public comment sought.
   Ms. Durham offered no indication when the agency would actually
propose the listing, but said the ``best scientific evidence''
available confirms the owl was worthy of protection.
   The Fish and Wildlife Service in December 1987 refused to list
the owl and environmental groups filed suit. District Court Judge
Thomas Zilly ruled the initial decision not to list the owl was
``arbitrary and capricious'' and gave the agency until May 1 to
review its decision.
   The bird, which is thought to nest only in the old-growth
forests of Washington, Oregon and northern California, has become
the focal point of a raging dispute between environmentalists and
the timber industry.
   Environmentalists have sought to have the owl protected as part
of their campaign to halt logging in the old-growth forests of the
Northwest while the industry has claimed such protection would
close vast areas of the region to logging forcing dozens of mills
to close and the layoff of thousands of workers.
   Court orders in related cases have already put a halt to more
than 140 timber sales in the region's national forests. Forest
Service officals have said those injunctions would interupt half of
the harvest planned in the national forests this year and during
the long-term the harvest could drop by one-third.
   F. Dale Robertson, Forest Service chief, has said under a
``worst case scenario'' more than 31,000 workers could loose their
jobs and his agency's timber receipts from the region could be cut
in half.
   ``They should have done it a year ago, but better late than
never,'' said Mike Anderson of the Wilderness Society, adding his
his group believes listing the owl as an endangered species will
require an end to logging in most of the remaining old-growth
forests of the Northwest.
   Jim Pissot of the National Audubon Society said the decision
gives the Northwest an ``opportunity to focus on some of the real
threats to the timber industry rather than using the spotted owl as
a scapegoat.''
   Ward Armstrong, executive director of the Oregon Forest
Industries Council in Salem, Ore., said the industry was
``disappointed, primarily because we don't believe the facts
warrant it.
   ``We believe there will be ramifications to this decision we
just don't begin to understand yet,'' said Armstrong. ``We believe
it was a grave error.''
</TEXT>
