<FIRST>r w AM-Turner-Retirement 300   04-25 0316</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Turner-Retirement, 300</SECOND>
<HEAD>DC Pox Chief Leaving</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD KEIL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police Chief Maurice T. Turner, who plans to
retire in July, wants to work for federal drug czar William
Bennett, but on Tuesday he didn't rule out running for mayor of the
District of Columbia.
   Turner, 53, announced he will retire July 31, wrapping up a
32-year career with the police department. He said he had no
immediate future plans.
   On Tuesday, top business officials contemplated drafting Turner
to run in the 1990 mayoral election, while city officials said he
wants to work for Bennett.
   ``Mr. Bennett has not offered me a job,'' Turner said, ``But he
needs people who have been on the working level of a police agency
_ on the ground floor.''
   Asked about a mayoral candidacy, Turner said, ``That's a
possibility. There's nothing to throw out the window.''
   Turner's decision comes after a series of public clashes with
Mayor Marion Barry Jr. involving Turner's requests for more
officers to fight the city's drug problem. Barry initially said the
city had enough officers, but later asked for more personnel.
   However, Turner downplayed any differences with Barry.
   ``Obviously, we did not always agree, but I get along well with
the mayor,'' Turner said.
   Turner, who dealt extensively with Bennett while Bennett was
drawing up a special anti-drug plan for the district, has said
privately that he would accept a job in Bennett's office if it were
offered.
   But Bennett aide Don Hamilton said Tuesday, ``Director Bennett
likes and respects Chief Turner, but there are no current plans to
bring him aboard.''
   Meantime, several members of the Greater Washington Board of
Trade, an influential business leaders' group, said they may start
a movement to draft Turner for mayor.
   The board took the unprecedented step three weeks ago of
criticizing Barry for failing to stop the increase in crime.
</TEXT>
