<SECOND>AM-Greece-US,0286</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ambassador Denies He Interfering In Greek Politics</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. ambassador to Greece denied
Tuesday he was interfering in Greek politics after the conservative
opposition party accused him of supporting the governing Socialists.
   A statement issued by the U.S. Embassy in Athens said Ambassador
Robert V. Keeley had steered clear of local politics since he was
assigned to the country 3{ years ago.
   ``Ambassador Keeley has made it the foundation of his service in
Athens ... to make clear to everyone in this country that the
politics of Greece are for the Greek people alone to determine,
that the United States government does not take sides,'' the
statement said.
   The statement came after the conservative New Democracy party
protested a story in The New York Times on Sunday that quoted
Western diplomats and Greek political analysts as saying the party
leader, Constantine Mitsotakis, was less charismatic than Premier
Andreas Papandreou.
   A Western diplomat was also quoted as saying it was not yet
clear who would win the June elections, despite the Papandreou
government's loss of popularity because of allegations that
officials were involved in a multimillion dollar financial scandal.
   New Democracy said the diplomat was American, and it said Greek
journalists recognize ``the American diplomat is none other that
Ambassador Keeley.''
   ``The envoy has not ceased for four years to interfere in an
unfitting way in Greece's domestic affairs by acting as a
propagandist for Andreas Papandreou,'' the conservatives said.
   The conservatives did not, however, provide any evidence for the
accusation.
   The embassy said Keeley had not met Alan Cowell, The New York
Times correspondent that wrote the story, since July 1987.
