<FIRST>r i AM-Poland-Popieluszko     04-25 0238</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland-Popieluszko,0246</SECOND>
<HEAD>A Killer Of Pro-Solidarity Priest Freed After Serving Four Years</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A policeman sentenced to 14 years in
prison for the murder of pro-Solidarity priest Jerzy Popieluszko
has been freed after serving about four years, it was announced
Tuesday.
   Waldemar Chmielewski was one of four security officers convicted
of killing the Roman Catholic priest in 1984 and dumping the body
in the Vistula river north of Warsaw. The three other officers were
given longer sentences and remain in prison.
   Deputy government spokesman Zbyslaw Rykowski said Chmielewski
had been released, but he did not know when he left the
penitentiary.
   He said Chmielewski's sentence expired during the third week in
April. The Supreme Court, citing humanitarian grounds in a 1987
ruling, reduced the sentence to four years.
   Chmielewski was sentenced in February 1985 to 14 years.
   Popieluszko was an active supporter of Solidarity, the
independent union chartered by the communist government in the fall
of 1980 during nationwide strikes.
   Solidarity was suspended by the government in December 1981 and
subsequently outlawed by Parliament. But it was restored as a legal
union federation under an agreement between the government and
opposition groups led by Solidarity founder Lech Walesa earlier
this month.
   Popieluszko became a symbol of Solidarity's struggle, and his
grave at the Warsaw church where he served is a pilgrimage site for
Poles and foreigners.
   Walesa placed flowers on the grave last weekend.
</TEXT>
