<FIRST>r i AM-AsianQuakes     04-25 0259</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Asian Quakes,0267</SECOND>
<HEAD>Earthquakes Hit China, Japan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The second strong earthquake in nine days hit a
mountainous area of southwest China on Tuesday, destroying a bridge
and causing the top floors of five apartment buildings to collapse,
an official report said.
   There were no immediate reports of casualties from the quake
that struck in Sichuan province's Batang County, near Tibet, the
state-run Xinhua News Agency said.
   In Japan, a moderate earthquake rocked the Tokyo area early
Wednesday, but police had no immediate reports of injuries or
damage.
   The Chinese news agency said Tuesday's quake measured 6.7 on the
Richter scale, the same as an earthquake that hit the same region
April 16. Eleven people were killed in the April 16 earthquake and
its aftershocks.
   Xinhua said a bridge across the Jinsha River was destroyed and
an army vehicle loaded with relief supplies for Batang was damaged
by a landslide.
   The epicenter of the Japanese quake was an estimated 40 miles
below the surface in northern Chiba prefecture, adjoining Tokyo.
   It had a preliminary reading on 5.1 on the Richter scale, the
Central Meteorological Agency said. There was no danger of tsunami,
or huge ocean waves, generated by the quake, the meteorological
agency said.
   The Richter scale is a measure of ground motion as recorded on
seismographs. Every increase of one number means a tenfold increase
in magnitude.
   An earthquake of 5 on the Richter scale can cause considerable
damage in the local area. A 7 reading is a ``major'' earthquake,
capable of widespread heavy damage.
</TEXT>
