<FIRST>u i AM-UN-Panama     04-25 0367</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-UN-Panama,0380</SECOND>
<HEAD>Panama Asks Security Council Meeting On U.S. Actions</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Panama on Tuesday asked for an emergency
meeting of the Security Council to hear its claim of ``flagrant
intervention'' by Washington in its economy and political system.
   Panama's ambassador to the United Nations, Leonardo Kam,
requested the council meeting. A U.N. official, speaking on
condition of anonymity, said a meeting might take place later this
week.
   Kam, in a letter, did not specify the cause of the complaint,
referring only to U.S. actions against Panama's ``sovereignty,
political independence, economic security and territorial
independence.''
   U.S. News &amp; World Report said in its May 1 issue that President
Bush secretly approved a $10 million fund for Panamanian opposition
candidates in the May 7 elections.
   Opposition candidate Guillermo Endara on Monday denied receiving
any campaign funds from the United States. Endara is running
against Carlos Duque, who is backed by Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega,
Panama's Defense Forces commander and de facto ruler.
   The opposition has accused Noriega of planning to rig the May 7
vote, in which Panamanians will choose a new president, two vice
presidents, 67 legislators and 510 local representatives.
   The New York Times reported this week that President Reagan
approved a plan to have U.S.-supported Panamanian exiles overthrow
Noriega, but the Senate Intelligence Committee balked at the plan.
   The Times, quoting government officials, reported the Senate
Intelligence Committee rejected the coup plan, however, on grounds
that Noriega might be assassinated. A presidential order forbids
U.S. participation in assassinations.
   Asked about the U.S. News report, White House officials refused
comment, saying it involves covert operations.
   Last year, the Reagan administration imposed economic sanctions
in an attempt to force out Noriega.
   The sanctions were imposed after Noriega was indicted on U.S.
drug trafficking charges in Florida and he orchestrated the ouster
of President Eric Arturo Delvalle. Delvalle had tried to fire
Noriega after the February 1988 indictment.
   Noriega denied the drug charges.
   Noriega has blamed the United States for Panama's economic
problems and accused Washington of trying to renege on a treaty to
transfer control of the Panama Canal to Panama by the end of the
century.
</TEXT>
