<FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     04-25 0346</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0359</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thunderstorms In Ohio, Snow in California</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Strong thunderstorms swept across Ohio and West Virginia on
Tuesday, and a spring storm dumped 5 inches of snow on the
mountains of California.
   Golf-ball sized hail clattered on Parkersburg, W. Va., and wind
gusted up to 60 mph at Cleveland's International Airport.
   Intense thunderstorms developed across western Wisconsin and
northeast Iowa, and showers fell across the central Pacific Coast.
   At Reedley, Calif., a small tornado flipped over a carport.
   Five to 6 inches of snow fell over the higher elevations of the
Sierra Nevada. Snow was expected at Yosemite National Park and the
Lake Tahoe area, and in the the southern Cascades of Oregon.
   An inch of snow fell in six hours in Great Falls, Mont.
   Much of the central portion of the nation heated up again, with
readings in the 80s or 90s across the southern Plains, in the
Mississippi Valley and Gulf Coast states.
   Record high temperatures for the date were reported in Atlanta,
which tied its mark of 88 degrees set in 1896; Topeka, Kan, with 90
degrees (89 in 1987); and Nashville, with 88 degrees (87 in 1986).
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 34
degrees at South Lake Tahoe, Calif., to 92 degrees at Fort Myers,
Fla., and Lubbock, Texas.
   The nation's low Tuesday morning was 17 degrees in South Lake
Tahoe.
   Wednesday's forecast called for scattered showers and
thunderstorms from the Plains to the upper Mississippi Valley, the
southern Great Lakes region, the central Appalachians and sections
of the mid-Atlantic Coast. Rain showers were predicted from the
central Pacific Coast to the northern Rockies, with snow at high
elevations in northern Arizona.
   High temperatures were predicted in the 40s and 50s across the
northern Rockies, in North Dakota, the northern Great Lakes and New
England; the 80s and 90s across much of the Plains, the Mississippi
and lower Ohio valleys and the Gulf and southern Atlantic coasts;
and in the 60s and 70s in most of the rest of the nation.
</TEXT>
