<FIRST>r w AM-CommoditiesProbe 1stld-writethru a0752 04-25 0322</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Commodities Probe, 1st ld-writethru, a0752,310</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs 7th graf to CORRECT that panel recommended against rules
changes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The federal agency overseeing the nation's
futures markets on Tuesday recommended against increasing penalties
for violating trading laws and called for more study on other
suggested reforms.
   The Commodity Futures Trading Commission, in response to
questions posed by Sen. Patrick Leahy, D-Vt., said it ``does not
believe that proposals for treble damages and punitive damages
would significantly enhance deterrence of violative conduct.''
   Leahy, chairman of the Senate Agriculture Committee, is
exploring proposals to tighten regulation of futures markets in the
wake of revelations that the FBI has conducted a two-year
undercover investigation of alleged abuses at the two largest
futures exchanges, the Chicago Board of Trade and the Chicago
Mercantile Exchange.
   Leahy's panel, and its counterpart in the House, have been
conducting hearings into the matter and on whether or not Congress
should extend the CFTC's authorization to continue operating after
Sept. 30.
   The commission did not recommend increased penalties but it
recommended removing a requirement that it consider a firm or
trader's financial condition before levying a penalty.
   The commission, chaired by Wendy L. Gramm, said the exchanges
themselves should increase their surveillance programs, but noted
that a number were already doing so.
   It said Congress should increase the agency's staff by 20
positions, but recommended against changing the rules to offer
higher pay to attract more qualified professionals. Instead, the
CFTC said pay should be raised across-the-board for professional
positions in the federal government.
   It said it would support increasing the physical presence of
CFTC on exchange floors, but said it was reviewing its staff to
determine if that could be done without hurting other efforts.
   In another area, the CFTC said it plans to monitor the
composition of the boards that govern the exchanges to ensure that
the public, in addition to floor traders, are adequately
represented.
</TEXT>
