<FIRST>r i AM-Turkey-Iran     04-25 0265</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Turkey-Iran,0273</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gunmen Attack Turkish Diplomat's House in Iran</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ANKARA, Turkey (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   At least five gunmen fired repeatedly at a
Turkish diplomat's house in the Iranian city of Oroumieh but
inflicted no casualties, the Foreign Ministry announced on Tuesday.
   It said the attack occurred Monday at the residence of Selami
Demirbas, the administrative attache at the Turkish Consulate in
Oroumieh, and Demirbas and his wife were inside the house at the
time.
   The Iranian charge d'affaires was summoned to the Foreign
Ministry Tuesday, told of Turkey's concern and asked that Iran
guarantee the safety of Turkish diplomats in that country, the
statement said.
   Foreign Ministry officials declined to speculate on the
identities of the attackers in Oroumieh in northwestern Iran near
the Turkish border. But a government source, speaking on condition
he not be identified, said the attack might have been carried out
by Armenians.
   Many Armenians commemorate on April 24 the massacre of more than
1 million Armenians in Turkey during World War I.
   Turkish and Iranian relations became strained this month when
Iran's fundamentalist Islamic government officially objected to a
Turkish constitutional court decision barring Turkish university
women from wearing Islamic-style headdresses.
   Both countries are predominantly Moslem but Turkey became a
secular state when the republic was formed in 1923 following the
disintegration of the Ottoman Empire. Religous courts were
abolished in 1924 and Islam ceased to be the official state
religion in 1928.
   Turkey accused Iran this month of interfering in its internal
affairs and recalled its ambassador from Tehran for consultations.
   Iran then called home its ambassador to Turkey.
</TEXT>
