<FIRST>r i AM-Brazil-BankStrike     04-25 0332</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brazil-Bank Strike,0342</SECOND>
<HEAD>Central Bank Workers Strike</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAO PAULO, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of workers at the country's
Central Bank went on strike Tuesday, and a bank spokesman said
foreign debt payments and other financial transactions were
jeopardized.
   The Central Bank strike broke out as other government bank
employees and workers at private banks entered the sixth day of a
separate strike.
   Murilo Murca de Carvalho, a Central Bank spokesman, said by
telephone from Brasilia that ``a significant number'' of the bank's
7,000 workers around the country stopped work.
   Nanci Toffoli, a spokeswoman for the Central Bank Workers Union
in Sao Paulo, said at least 5,000 workers across the country joined
the strike.
   Carvalho said the strike was ``already causing difficulties and
could eventually force our operations to come to a standstill.''
   The Central Bank, Brazil's equivalent of the U.S. Federal
Reserve, controls short-term market investments, the domestic money
supply, government bond trading, foreign exchange operations, and
investments of Brazil's hard currency reserves in the international
financial market.
   The strike could affect Brazil's foreign debt payments,
depending on how long it lasts, Carvalho said without elaborating.
   Brazil, the largest nation in Latin America, is the third
world's largest debtor nation. It has a foreign debt of $115
billion.
   Central Bank workers are federal employees who earn salaries
averaging $680 a month. They are demanding a 150 percent pay
increase to keep pace with annual inflation of more than 1,000
percent.
   The other strike, involving government and private workers,
closed 15 percent of the country's banking institutions, according
to Adilson Lorente, spokesman for the Brazilian Banking Federation.
The spokesman said by phone that 20 percent of about 700,000
Brazilian bank workers were on strike.
   However, the national strike command said at least 75 percent of
the bank workers joined the work stoppage.
   These bank workers earn salaries ranging from $145 a month to
about $1,400 a month. The banks have offered a 29 percent wage
increase, but the strikers want 81 percent.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
