<FIRST>r i AM-VirginIslands-Lewis     04-25 0529</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Virgin Islands-Lewis,0548</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ex-Government Consultant Convicted Of Drug-Peddling</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHARLOTTE AMALIE, U.S. Virgin Islands (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A key figure in two
federal investigations involving Washington Mayor Marion Barry was
convicted Tuesday of drug trafficking stemming from an undercover
FBI operation.
   An eight-woman, four-man jury deliberated for 90 minutes before
finding former Virgin Islands government consultant Charles Lewis
guilty of all four drug counts against him. The U.S. District Court
trial took two days.
   Lewis, 48, was charged with two counts of drug possession and
two counts of distribution in the sale of $550 worth of crack, a
cocaine derivative, to undercover FBI agents last month.
   U.S. Attorney Richard Harris said each count carries a maximum
sentence of 20 years and $1 million.
   Chief U.S. District Court Judge David V. O'Brien set sentencing
for June 14 and released Lewis on unsecured bond of $10,000. Lewis
left the courtroom accompanied by his brother and sister.
   Lewis had pleaded innocent but did not testify.
   Lewis faces 10 felony charges in Washington in a separate case
in which District of Columbia police reportedly were called off an
attempted drug buy from Lewis while Barry was visiting his hotel
room in the city.
   A federal grand jury is looking into the circumstances of
Barry's visit to the hotel.
   A second investigation involving Lewis and Barry focuses on the
District of Columbia's joint personnel project with the Virgin
Islands last year. Lewis headed the $266,000 project for the U.S.
territory until he was fired by Gov. Alexander Farrelly in April
1988 because of cost overruns.
   In the current case, the FBI accused Lewis of selling 0.12
ounces of crack worth $550 to two undercover agents March 2 and 3
at a luxury hotel on St. Thomas, one of the U.S. Virgin Islands.
   Special FBI agent Mary Ann Krauss, who allegedly bought crack
from Lewis with agent Joan Burns, testified that the FBI believed
Lewis had been using and selling cocaine for a long time.
   ``The purpose of the undercover operation was to prove or
disprove Mr. Lewis' association with drugs,'' she said.
   The agent said she and Ms. Burns were introduced to Lewis March
2 by a Patricia Teal, identified in court only as a ``cooperating
citizen,'' and bought two $25 bags of crack the same day.
   Ms. Krauss said arrangements were made to buy $500 worth of
crack and a $15 pipe for smoking the drug to be delivered to a room
at the Frenchmen's Reef Hotel.
   ``Our scenario was to suggest a party to Lewis,'' the agent
testified.
   Defense attorney Leonard Francis argued that the FBI used female
agents to entice Lewis into the illegal drug transaction.
   ``Was it coincidence that Lewis that there were three people _
three ladies _ awaiting him to see if he can buy drugs?'' Francis
asked the jury.
   Before closing arguments Tuesday, however, Judge O'Brien denied
a defense motion to dismiss the case on ground of entrapment.
   Psychiatrist Olaf Hendricks, testifying for the defense, said
Lewis told him he was a longtime abuser of alcohol and was
psychologically addicted to crack.
   O'Brien told the jury that drug addiction could not be cited as
a reason for acquittal.
</TEXT>
