<FIRST>r i AM-Britain-Jets     04-25 0174</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-Jets,0179</SECOND>
<HEAD>Order Check For Jet Engine Cracks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   British and U.S. aviation authorities on Tuesday
ordered checks on British Aerospace 146 jets, which are used here
by Queen Elizabeth II, after cracks were discovered in their
American-built jet engines.
   The Civil Aviation Authority and the U.S. Federal Aviation
Administration issued the order after the cracks were discovered
when the engines were stripped down in the United States, British
authorities said.
   The CAA said compressor discs connecting with the turbine fan
blades were found cracked in the U.S.-built Avco Lycoming ALF-502
engines of the British Aerospace 146 jets.
   It ordered airlines using the plane to strip down and inspect
the discs within the next 250 flights.
   Two of the four-engine BAe-146 planes are in the Queen's Flight,
as the royal aircraft are collectively known. The queen flew to
China in a BAe-146 in 1986.
   The 100-seat BAe-146 is a steady seller to airlines around the
world, with many used on short commuter routes in the United States
and 10 in China.
