<HEAD>Previn Resigns As Director of LA Philharmonic</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES throughout to confirm that Previn resigning, adds details,
background; no pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD DE ATLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Andre Previn resigned Tuesday as music
director of the Los Angeles Philharmonic amid reports of clashes
with his boss, but will continue as a guest conductor for the next
three seasons.
   ``In the current structure of the Los Angeles Philharmonic, it
has become obvious to me there is no room for a music director,''
Previn, 60, told the board, according to a release from the
philharmonic.
   The philharmonic, however, said a search for a new music
director would begin immediately.
   Previn, who became music director in 1985, had two years left on
his contract. His resignation was effective at the end of the
season.
   He had clashed with Music Center director Ernest Fleischmann
over everything from guest conductors on recordings and how Previn
edited musical works to cutbacks on office supplies and coffee, the
Herald Examiner reported Tuesday.
   ``Nonetheless, because of my love for the orchestra, I am
perfectly happy to continue making music with them,'' Previn said
in the statement. He said he planned to conduct the Philharmonic
for seven weeks next season and six weeks each for the 1990-1991
and 1991-1992 seasons.
   Previn also will take up the baton for some recordings, a May
1990 U.S. tour, and for the opening concert of the Carnegie Hall
centennial season in September 1990.
   A message seeking comment was left for Fleischmann, but there
was no immediate response.
   Michael J. Connell, president of the Philharmonic Association's
board of directors, said Previn's resignation was accepted with
regret.
   Previn, an Academy Award-winning composer and conductor, stepped
down as the Pittsburgh Symphony's music director to take the Los
Angeles post, replacing Carlo Maria Giulini.
   It was a triumphant return to Los Angeles for Previn, whose
parents brought him to the city in 1939 after fleeing Nazi Germany.
He began his composing career at MGM studios at age 16, and
eventually wrote scores for more than 30 movies.
   He won Oscars for ``Gigi'' (1958), ``Porgy and Bess,'' (1959),
``Irma La Douce,'' (1963) and ``My Fair Lady,'' (1964).
   He also has won seven Grammys from the National Academy of
Recording Arts and Sciences, has recorded on several labels, and
led many of the top orchestras of the United States and Europe.
   During his tenure as music director, the philharmonic recorded
10 records, toured Japan and many Western cities, and made East
Coast appearances at Carnegie and Avery Fisher halls in New York
and the Kennedy Center for Performing Arts in Washington, D.C.
   Previn also reorganized the philharmonic's Chamber Music
Society, and appeared as pianist in nine of the chamber's
performances at the University of Judaism's Gindl Auditorium.
   One of Previn's original compositions was performed each season
during his directorship, including ``Principals For Orchestra,
Every Good Boy Deserves Favor,'' a piece for actors and orchestra
written with playwright Tom Stoppard.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
