<FIRST>r w AM-CubanFarewell     04-25 0419</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cuban Farewell,420</SECOND>
<HEAD>Friends Bid Farewell to Cuban Envoy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT M. ANDREWS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Several hundred friends, associates and
diplomatic colleagues said goodbye Tuesday to Cuban envoy Ramon
Sanchez Parodi, who said the lack of ``a political will'' is
blocking improved relations between his country and the United
States.
   At a buffet reception given by Sanchez Parodi in the ornate old
Cuban Embassy building on 16th Street, the departing envoy offered
scant hope of warmer U.S.-Cuban relations under President Bush.
   Asked about the prospects, he replied, ``That is for the
administration to say, not for us.''
   ``There is a need for a political will to improve relations,''
said Sanchez Parodi, who leaves Thursday to become Cuban's deputy
foreign minister after nearly 12 years as Fidel Castro's diplomatic
representative in Washington.
   He will be succeeded by Jose Antonio Arbezu, vice chairman of
the Central Committee of the Cuban Communist Party for American
affairs, who is scheduled to arrive in May.
   Among those offering best wishes to Sanchez Parodi in his new
post were Rep. Ted Weiss, D-N.Y.; Mrs. Claiborne Pell, wife of the
chairman of the Senate Foreign Relations Committee, and Washington
lawyer R. Sargent Shriver, who also is chairman of Special Olympics
International.
   Shriver, a Democratic vice presidential candidate in 1972, said
he thanked Sanchez Parodi for Cuba's participation in Special
Olympics athletic games for the mentally retarded and handicapped
for the past eight years.
   ``This gentleman has been very helpful in maintaining good
working relations between the Special Olympics and the Cuban
government,'' Shriver said. ``I'm just here to wish him well in his
new job.''
   Although Sanchez Parodi was invited to several White House
social events during the Carter administration after he opened a
small Cuban diplomatic mission here in the summer of 1977, he was
given the deep freeze during President Reagan's eight years in
office.
   No Bush administration official attended the Cuban mission's
farewell party for Sanchez Parodi, who had been officially snubbed
by the White House and the State Department throughout the Reagan
administration.
   His last invitation to a White House social event was when he
attended a reception for the Washington diplomatic corps shortly
after Reagan took office in January 1981.
   Sanchez Parodi refused comment on a memorandum that Secretary of
State James A. Baker III sent to U.S. diplomatic posts last month
in which he declared that improved relations with Cuba were
impossible until Cuba stops fomenting subversion in the Western
Hemisphere and supporting Soviet expansionism.
</TEXT>
