<FIRST>r a AM-ChristExhibit 2ndLd-Writethru a0702 04-25 0671</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Christ Exhibit, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0702,0682</SECOND>
<HEAD>Group: Government Supports Bigotry With Art Exhibit</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 1 graf after 11th graf, ``Expression not ...,'' to ADD
comment from NEA; picks up 12th graf, `Stefan Stux ...'' Note language.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RON HARRIST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JACKSON, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The creator of a large photograph of a
crucified Christ submerged in urine said Tuesday his critics were
flattering the work by creating a furor over it.
   An organization in Tupelo has condemned the federal and private
funding of the artist and an exhibit of his work, saying it
reflected bigotry against Christians.
   The creator of ``Piss Christ'' was a winner in The Awards in the
Visual Arts funded by The Rockefeller Foundation, the Equitable
Foundation and the National Endowment for the Arts.
   The American Family Association said Monday that tax dollars
should not have gone toward the $15,000 award for the artist,
Andres Serrano. His was one of 10 such awards last year.
   ``The person at the National Endowment for the Arts responsible
for approving federal tax dollars for promotion of the `work of
art' should be fired,'' said the Rev. Donald E. Wildmon, a United
Methodist minister who heads the Tupelo-based association.
   Wildmon said the Equitable Foundation, a section of Equitable
Life Assurance Society of the United States, and the Rockefeller
Foundation ``owe Christians a public apology and assurance that
they will not be a party to such anti-Christian bigotry in the
future.''
   Serrano said Tuesday from New York that he expected some
opposition to his work, primarily because of the title.
   ``I feel when people attack a work of art to such a great
extent, they imbue it with a far greater power than when they
ignore it and, in that, I'm flattered that they think it deserves
such attention.''
   As winner of the stipend, the artist selects a work for a
national tour. The 38-year-old New York artist said ``Piss
Christ,'' the piece he selected for tour, was a limited edition of
four prints. One print, he said, already has been sold to a private
collector for $3,600. The work is not currently on exhibit.
   Joseph Slye, a National Endowment for the Arts spokesman,
defended the award.
   ``Expression not prohibited by federal law is protected by the
First Amendment,'' he said. ``Moreover, the endowment is expressly
forbidden in its authorizing legislation from interfering with the
artistic choices made by its grantees.
   ``The national Endowment for the Arts supports the right of
grantee organizations to select, on artistic criteria, their
artist-recipients and present their work, even though sometimes the
work may be deemed controversial and offensive to some
individuals,'' Slye said. ``We at the endowment do, none the less,
deeply regret any offense to any individual.''
   Stefan Stux, owner of the Stux gallery in New York which handles
Serrano's works, said the photograph was created by immersing an
image of the crucified Christ in a glass container of ``urine he
had collected from himself.''
   ``When you look at it, you would never know that, all you can
see is the image of Jesus Christ in a kind of hazy, yellowish mist,
a kind of poetical image. If you did not know the title of it, you
could be very enraptured by the beauty of it. It is very pleasing,
poetic and spiritual.''
   He said the artist uses other body fluids in his art, including
blood. ``He was born in the Christian faith, he feels very much a
part of that,'' Stux said. ``He has deep religious feelings, but he
does not express them exactly the way every other guy does.''
   Rockefeller Foundation president Peter Goldmark said in New
York: ``I respect the right of any individual to object to a work
of art, and the parallel right of artists to express themselves and
of exhibitors to show works that they deem interesting and
meritorious artistically. I think tolerance and mutual respect for
such rights may be the qualities we most need in order to get along
together on this planet.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
