<SECOND>AM-Country Awards, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0775,0476</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cable Channel Honors Country Music Performers</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 16 grafs to UPDATE with winners, quotes; picks up
10th graf, `The inaugural ...'</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto staffing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOE EDWARDS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Randy Travis was voted favorite
entertainer and Ricky Van Shelton won three country music honors
Tuesday night at the second annual Viewers' Choice Awards presented
by The Nashville Network cable channel.
   Travis, who has dominated country music awards for the past
three years, also won Best Album for ``Old 8 X 10.''
   Travis said he has not tired of winning awards for his
relatively short four-year professional career. ``You can always
find room for another one,'' he said.
   In voting by country music fans, Shelton won favorite male
vocalist, No. 1 video and favorite song, both for ``I'll Leave This
World Loving You.''
   Shelton, a former pipefitter, said he was especially pleased to
earn the vocalist honor.
   ``That's what I am,'' he said. ``I consider myself a singer; I
don't dance or do anything like that.''
   Reba McEntire outpolled rising star K. T. Oslin to earn favorite
female vocalist.
   ``This feels pretty dadblamed good,'' she said backstage
afterwards.
   The Oak Ridge Boys were voted favorite group for the second
straight year, and the quintet Shenandoah won favorite newcomer on
the basis of its No. 1 song, ``The Church on Cumberland Road.''
   Roy Acuff, 85, was presented a special award named after Grand
Ole Opry comrade Minnie Pearl to honor his lifelong humanitarian
endeavors.
   ``I hardly know what to say except it makes my heart feel
good,'' Acuff said after receiving a standing ovation from the
4,400 people watching the live broadcast at the Grand Ole Opry
House.
   Finalists for favorite entertainer besides Travis were Shelton,
the Judds, McEntire, George Strait and Hank Williams Jr.
   The awards were chosen by 200,000 viewers of The Nashville
Network, which is seen in 44.8 million households.
   Winners of eight categories were chosen by cable TV viewers who
cast their votes by telephone. The finalists were chosen by a
committee of journalists, broadcast industry representatives and
country music fans.
   The Nashville Network broadcast a live, 30-minute special after
the presentations with reactions from the winners at a post-show
party.
   More than 200 radio stations also carried the awards program.
   The inaugural 1988 awards drew 300,000 votes. Travis was the big
winner, sweeping all five categories in which he was nominated.
   The 6-year-old cable TV network broadcasts to more than 43
million cable TV households. Much of its programming is country
music along with sports shows and Western movies.
   It was the second country music awards show this month. The Los
Angeles-based Academy of Country Music announced its honors in an
NBC TV special April 10.
</TEXT>
