<FIRST>u a AM-Bush 2ndLd-Writethru a0713 04-25 0964</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0713,1000</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Blends Various Themes as He Barnstorms California</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Adds new graf 17 to show later Bush activities</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERENCE HUNT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP White House Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>EL TORO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush barnstormed California on
Tuesday, sending a message to drug dealers that ``you are going to
be out of business'' and asking the entertainment industry to raise
its voice against illegal narcotics.
   ``I never want to see a movie again that makes drug use into
something humorous,'' Bush said. ``It is time that they got behind
this crusade.''
   He also campaigned for smaller budget deficits and lower taxes
on capital gains.
   Bush blended a variety of sharply different themes in a
three-stop series of appearances in northern and southern
California on the second day of a busy four-day trip through six
states.
   The journey took him from a Ford Aerospace plant in Palo Alto to
a remote ranch in Orange County seized from an alleged drug kingpin
and finally to Los Angeles for an appearance before a Hispanic
audience.
   Opening the day, Bush started to say he was in North Carolina
but quickly caught himself and corrected it to north California.
   Later, Bush toured the 213-acre Rancho Del Rio, described by the
White House as once housing the largest marijuana network in the
United States. Now it is used by Orange County as a training
facility for drug enforcement officers.
   Bush did not propose any new federal initiatives but called on
the entertainment industry to use its influence as a tool against
drugs.
   He said entertainers ``have raised your voices so effectively in
the cause of so many issues. Can you not raise them once more, in
support of a cause so important?''
   He turned over to law enforcement officials $10 million
recovered from drug dealers.
   He called the money ``the bounty of defeated drug criminals''
and said ``let these funds go to fighting the war they once
financed. ...
   ``And let us send a message, loud and clear to every drug
merchant in America _ you are going to be out of business.''
   Bush said: ``We won't build a better America until we win the
war on drugs.'' He said drug users were living lives without hope
or meaning.
   ``We're looking at a desperation that money alone will never
cure. We won't win this one with our wallets alone _ we will win it
through our collective effort and our collective will.''
   In Los Angeles, Bush met with Republican Hispanic supporters. He
said Hispanics were building a better America ``through family,
church, love of country and belief in the value of hard work.''
   He said: ``As America's fastest-growing minority in the 21st
century, you, more than ever, will help tell the American story.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End embargoed material</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   After the Hispanic reception in Los Angeles, Bush flew by
helicopter to Anaheim to watch a baseball game between the
California Angeles and the Baltimore Orioles. He was to remain in
Los Angeles overnight and meet Wednesday with former president
Ronald Reagan.
   At his first stop of the day, Bush said the best investment for
America's future would be to cut the huge federal budget deficit,
warning that ``tough talks still lie ahead'' to achieve that goal.
   He said the nation must be more competitive to sustain the
economic recovery that has produced nearly 20 million jobs over the
last seven years.
   Bush spoke to workers at Ford Aerospace's space systems division
in Palo Alto. The facility, which employs 2,000 people, produces
communications satellites, tactical weapons systems, space systems
and other high-tech products.
   After touring the aerospace facility, Bush told the audience
that ``the best investment in the future is to slash the federal
deficit. Every dollar the government does not borrow means more
capital available for investment.''
   He noted that he recently concluded a sketchy agreement with
Congress to cut the deficit to $99.4 billion in the fiscal year
beginning Oct. 1. The blueprint does not provide much detail about
how the reduction will be achieved.
   ``Now this plan's an agreed outline,'' Bush said. ``Tough talks
still lie ahead.''
   He said: ``Think of deficit reduction as an exercise, like
walking the dog every day. Believe me, I know, exercise keeps you
at the top of your game.''
   While challenging the nation to become more competitive in
technological innovation, Bush did not offer any new initiatives.
   He made a new pitch to reduce the capital gains tax rate to 15
percent from its current level of 28 percent. ``Lower capital gains
taxes will create jobs for those who don't have jobs and help build
a better America.''
   He laced his speech with television sound-bite lines such as ``I
want to give the high-five symbol to high tech. And I want to do it
by investing in competitiveness.''
   Ticking off some of his proposals, Bush noted he has proposed a
permanent extension of tax credits for research and
experimentation, and has asked Congress for an increase of $2.4
billion for NASA.
   ``Let us use our own technological prowess to expand free and
fair trade,'' Bush said. ``I'm talking about excellence in such
fields as microcomputers, superconductivity and, yes, aerospace.''
   Before an audience of white-collar workers, Bush also extolled
his proposal for a child-care tax credit for low-income parents.
   His plan would provide a credit of up to $1,000 for each child
under age 4 in poor families.
   ``Our proposal urges a nex tax credit to make child care more
affordable,'' Bush said. ``And it puts money in the hands of the
low-income parents, limits federal intervention and increases
options.
   ``A church can help or grandparents or professional nursery,''
he said. ``When it comes to child care, we say, let the parents
decide. Keep the family strong and we must do that.''
</TEXT>
