<FIRST>u a AM-Super7Fever 2ndLd-Writethru a0787 04-25 0589</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Super 7 Fever, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0787,0602</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lottery Fever Knows No Borders</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 6th graf, ``The jackpot ...,'' to UPDATE with final sales
figure.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto HX2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CASSANDRA BURRELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SHARON, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   At the drug store straddling the
Pennsylvania-Ohio line, the big money Tuesday moved to Carol
McGhee's lottery machine in Pennsylvania and ignored Debbie
Trinckes' machine in Ohio. The difference was a fortune.
   The Super 7 jackpot soared to $100 million in Pennsylvania and
its upper reaches were limited only by the deadline for the drawing
Wednesday night.
   Miss Trinckes sold a few tickets for the Ohio Lottery's Super
Lotto game, worth a mere $3 million. But even she crossed the line
to plunk down $20 for 20 tickets in Pennsylvania.
   ``I don't even play their lottery,'' she said, ``but since it's
so high, I decided to.''
   Lottery fever heightened not just in Pennsylvania but around the
country as state officials upped the ante in the Super 7 Lottery
drawing to at least $100 million based on ever-speeding ticket
sales from the Delaware River to the Penn-Ohio Drug store off U.S.
62.
   The jackpot is the result of six straight weekly drawings with
no winner and international publicity, which generated ticket sales
Monday of $19 million and a state record for daily sales of $24.34
million Tuesday. Last week's jackpot was $46 million.
   A single winner of the $100 million would receive almost $3.85
million a year for 26 years, lottery officials said.
   Pennsylvania's Super 7 game lets players choose seven numbers
from 1 to 80 for $1. If those seven are among 11 numbers selected,
the combination wins the jackpot, a chance lottery officials put at
9.6 million to 1.
   Out-of-state players drove to Pennsylvania, and many even flew
commercial flights into Pittsburgh and Philadelphia to get a chance
for the biggest-ever jackpot in North America.
   The line outside the two-state store, northeast of Youngstown,
Ohio, grew to 150 people at times, sometimes stretching all the way
across the state line, as patrons waited for the store's two
Pennsylvania lottery machines to crank out up 2,000 tickets per
hour together.
   Store Senior Vice President Bob Annis suggested to customers at
the end of the line that they may have more luck _ at least buying
tickets _ in nearby Mercer, about 20 miles into Pennsylvania.
   ``We want your business, but we're running at capacity. Come
back tomorrow,'' he said.
   Most Ohioans were not deterred.
   ``You can tell everybody that the winning ticket is going to
Cleveland,'' said James Casey, 36. ``I've been a police officer for
12 years and if I win, I'm going to retire.''
   Harry Brandt, 52, of Ravenna, Ohio, admitted he may be foolish
to take the longest of long shots, but said, ``What else are you
going to do, not play?''
   Miss McGhee, 40, of Sharon, said selling the tickets was not as
hectic as it appeared. She noted clerks get a chance to rest when
the machine prints tickets for large orders of 20 or more.
   She was able to rest Tuesday morning when one player ordered 200
tickets. And on Monday, one player bought 672 tickets. Co-workers
still talked about a man who put up $1,400 for tickets last
Thursday and gave them a 52-minute break.
   Miss McGhee said she only bought five tickets herself.
   Miss Trinckes, 31, of Hubbard, Ohio, complained of boredom
because she sold only 168 Ohio lottery tickets Tuesday morning.
``Normally, by this time, we would have sold 400 or 500.''
</TEXT>
