<FIRST>r i AM-Nicaragua-Defector     04-25 0206</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nicaragua-Defector,0212</SECOND>
<HEAD>Reports Nicaraguan Pilot Defected With Plane To Costa Rica</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN JOSE, Costa Rica (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former Nicaraguan air force pilot
who vanished last week with a private plane has defected to
neighboring Costa Rica and is requesting asylum, a government
spokesman said Tuesday.
   The Interior Ministry spokesman, who spoke on condition of
anonymity, identified the pilot as Reinado Antonio Aranda Guido,
27. He said police were interrogating Aranda to determine if he
qualified for asylum.
   Aranda landed Friday in a single-engine Cessna-180 in Puerto
Limon, a town on the Caribbean coast, after he diverted it from a
domestic flight.
   In Managua, Nicaraguan Foreign Ministry spokesman David Silva
would not comment on the report of the defection. He said his
government was awaiting details from the Costa Rican government..
   Silva said Aranda had been a 2nd lieutenant in the Nicaraguan
air force but had returned to civilian life. He was working for
Special Air Services, a private Nicaraguan company, Silva said.
   Aranda was flying alone from Bluefields, the main port on the
Caribbean, to Corn Island, also in the Caribbean, when he
disappeared Friday. The plane belonged to Special Air Services.
   There was no immediate word on why Aranda would have fled
Nicaragua.
