<FIRST>u a AM-SightReunion 1stLd-Writethru a0708 04-25 0610</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sight Reunion, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0708,0624</SECOND>
<HEAD>Deaf Vietnamese Girl Reunited With Parents</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Eds: LEADS with 17 grafs to UPDATE with parents arriving in
Houston; picks up 7th graf, `During a visit ...'
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL L. GRACZYK</BYLINE>
<UNK>Associated Press Writer</UNK>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 16-year-old Vietnamese girl made deaf by a
nerve ailment realized a dream Tuesday when she got to see her
parents again before the disease takes her eyesight as well.
   Thao Phan, who last saw her parents nine years ago when her
father smuggled her aboard a boat heading for Thailand, hugged her
mother and father as they arrived in Houston on a flight from
Bangkok and London.
   Thao and other family members applauded and wiped away tears.
   ``I have never been so tired,'' Geri Konigsberg, the Houston
woman who helped reunite Thao with her family, said after making
the 24-hour flight with the girl's parents.
   Ms. Konigsberg, a spokeswoman for Houston Lighting &amp; Power Co.
who took an interest in Thao's plight two years ago after she was
contacted by school officials two years ago to see if the utility
could arrange for clothing donations for the girl.
   ``I asked her what else she wanted. And she said she wanted her
mother,'' said Ms. Konigsberg, who worked to grant Thao's wish.
   Thao journeyed to Thailand in the false bottom of a boat, then
spent two years in a refugee camp before coming to the United
States to live with a brother, one of two who arrived in Houston in
1980.
   Thao suffers from Usher's Syndrome, a congenital nerve disease
that took away her hearing and soon will leave her blind. She now
has a sight range of only 15 inches and has no peripheral vision.
   Ms. Konigsberg said Thao's father took the extreme measure with
his daughter because handicapped people in Vietnam are considered
worthless.
   ``He did it out of love,'' she said, saying he hoped U.S.
doctors could help.
   Thao should lead a healthy life, although she is deaf and her
loss of sight will eventually be complete, Ms. Konigsberg said.
   Thao speaks English in sign language. Her father, Lac Van Phan,
58, and mother, Mo Thi Nguyen, 55, speak only Vietnamese, as do a
sister, Hong, 17, and two brothers, Sohn, 10 and Ngoc, 7. They
lived in Vung Tau, a fishing and farming village about 60 miles
from Ho Chi Mihn City.
   ``It's the start of a new life for them,'' Ms. Konigsberg said.
``They're going to learn English now.''
   Thao, wearing a blue skirt and a blue and white striped shirt,
clutched a bouquet of roses and a red, white and blue Texas flag as
she embraced her mother when the woman came off the airliner.
   Ms. Konigsberg said the Phan family was terrified in London when
they boarded an elevator for the first time at Heathrow Airport,
but loved the in-flight movie, ``Who Framed Roger Rabbit.''
   Ms. Konigsberg got U.S. Rep. Mickey Leland, D-Texas to use his
influence to trim the red tape in getting the family to the United
States, which has no diplomatic relations with Vietnam.
   During a visit to Hanoi last fall, Leland told Vietnamese
Foreign Minister Nguyen Co Thach about Thao's family and mentioned
the girl again when the foreign minister visited New York.
   In November, Leland's office was notified the Phan family would
be allowed to leave. British Airways agreed to pick up the costs of
bringing the family from Thailand to Houston.
   Despite her hearing disability, Thao has learned English through
sign language. She attends classes for the hearing impaired in the
Aldine School District, just north of Houston, said Onita Vaughan,
an educational diagnostician.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
