<DOCNO> AP890425-0224 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-25-89 1151EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a a PM-APonTV-BillW Adv26   04-25 0806</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-AP on TV-Bill W, Adv 26,0827</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv26</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Wednesday PMs, April 26, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Woods, Garner Reunite To Tell AA Founder's Story</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY NEUMEISTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three years after James Garner and James Wood
starred in an award-winning television special about schizophrenia,
the actors have reunited for a production that can best be
described as sobering.
   ``My Name Is Bill W.,'' which airs Sunday on ABC-TV, tells the
story of Bill Wilson, the late co-founder of Alcoholics Anonymous.
   ``This is a very unsentimental version of Bill Wilson's life,''
said Woods, 42, who plays Wilson. ``There are scenes in this
picture that I think are literally hair-raising. There was no
sentimental restraint placed on us.
   ``They allowed us to show the true story ... and it's a
devastating story and it's not an easy story to watch,'' he added.
   The story focuses on the struggles of a stockbroker whose health
and success are destroyed by twin calamities _ the stock market
crash of 1929 and his own alcoholism.
   It details the days when Wilson was unable to stop drinking
despite the efforts of a devoted wife, Lois (played by JoBeth
Williams). Strapped to a hospital bed, he realizes he is helpless
to defeat alcoholism alone.
   Most of the two-hour movie shows the horrors Wilson faced before
he met Dr. Bob Smith, an Akron, Ohio, surgeon and drunk played by
Garner.
   A church arranged for the two men to meet after Wilson, only
sober for a short time and struggling to rebuild his life, arrived
in Akron. He was lonely, uptight and tempted by other drinkers.
   Smith, thinking Wilson came to lecture him to stop drinking, was
suspicious.
   ``Just what do you think a man like you can do for me?'' Smith
asks.
   Wilson cries out: ``I didn't come here to help you. I came here
to help me.''
   Garner calls Wilson and Smith ``two of the greatest men of this
century, two drunks who got together to help each other and ended
up helping millions of others.''
   Filmed in Richmond, Va., the Hallmark Hall of Fame presentation
was written by William Borchert, who read his script to the
97-year-old Mrs. Wilson on the back porch of her Bedford Hills,
N.Y., home last fall.
   ``When I got finished she reached for my hand, put her arms
around me and we shed tears together. She said, `I'm very happy
this story will finally be told to the world.' Twenty one days
later she passed away,'' he said.
   The production was the idea of Peter Duchow, co-producer with
Garner.
   Duchow met Wilson in the 1950s and was convinced by 1953 the
story should be told. But he could not pursue it for 30 years.
   Garner and Duchow discussed the project in 1983 but five scripts
were rejected.
   ``Because there is a tendency to beatify Bill Wilson, most
writers really are influenced by the size of the membership and
what all of that means,'' he said. ``Our feeling was always let's
personalize by simply telling the story of Bill Wilson, which was
very difficult to get on paper.''
   Garner and Woods had worked together more than once. As a
fledgling actor, Woods played the villain in the first episode of
Garner's ``The Rockford Files.''
   And in ``Promise,'' another Hallmark special broadcast in 1986,
Garner played a carefree man forced to care for his schizophrenic
brother, played by Woods, after the death of their mother. It lost
in the ratings to a Dolly Parton television movie, but won five
Emmy awards.
   Woods recalled hearing Duchow and Garner ``mumbling about their
next project'' in a coffee shop at the end of filming for
``Promise.''
   ``I kind of cocked an ear and thought there could be a job in
this. I said, `Heh. I'm Bill W. I could be Bill W.' I didn't quite
realize what I was about to embark on,'' he said.
   ``I have friends and people I love very dearly who in the course
of work are alcoholics. Most of them have found Alcoholics
Anonymous and a few have not and some are dead,'' he said. ``I just
hope the few who aren't members will find their way in.''
   Even before the production aired, it had an impact. After Garner
and Woods appeared on television talk shows to promote the movie,
Woods was stopped by a woman outside his hotel in New York; she
said the actors had convinced her brother to join AA.
   A day earlier, Woods had told a luncheon gathering, ``If we can
save one life, then we will go greatly beyond what we hoped to do,
which was great entertainment, some information. If there's a life
or two along the way that we can save, then we will indeed be
blessed.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Wed PMs, April 26</NOTE>
