<FILEID>AP-NR-04-25-89 1255EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a a PM-BusinessMirror Adv26   04-25 0570</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Business Mirror, Adv 26,0583</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv26</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release PMs Wednesday, April 26</HEAD>
<HEAD>Corporate Dividends Are Rising</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN CUNNIFF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Analyst</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Whatever IBM does, it's bound to attract
attention and provoke discussion, and maybe even spur others to do
the same. Investors who depend on dividends are hoping so.
   IBM raised its common stock dividend this week for the first
time in 4{ years. The 11-cent increase to $1.21 a share raises the
annual yield to 4.2 percent from 3.9 percent and enriches
shareholders by $250 million a year.
   Will others follow? Perhaps. But in this instance IBM isn't so
much a leader as a follower. Without the excitement that often
attends increases in share prices, corporate dividends have been
moving higher for the past year.
   In fact, Commerce Department and independent analysts' data show
it has been many months, even years, since such increases have been
seen. There are suggestions that improvements will continue through
the year.
   Wright Investors' Service, which analyzes stock performance,
notes that for the 12 months through March dividends for the
Standard &amp; Poors 500 stock index rose 11.5 percent.
   First-quarter action in the current year also was strong,
according to Wright, with 521 companies raising dividends and 116
paying extras, ``the highest total of favorable dividend actions of
any first quarter since 1982.''
   If you use the Dow Jones average of 30 industrial stocks as a
measuring stick, the dividend news is even more impressive _ 26
percent for the first quarter, 17 percent for the past 12 months _
until you know the reason why.
   Wright points out that these growth rates were inflated by two
unusual actions, one being a $1.12 a share extra dividend by Alcoa,
the other a 75 cents a share dividend paid by Texaco, which was
undergoing bankruptcy court reorganization a year earlier.
   Commerce Department data verify the improved performance,
indicating that recent dividend growth has been in the range of 10
percent to 12 percent. All in all, the activity has been the best
since 1979-1980, but with a difference.
   That difference is a big one. In the earlier period the
inflation rate was close to 10 percent and dividend growth was
merely keeping pace. Inflation is lower today. Real dividend growth
is more than 5 percent, highest in 12 years.
   Despite the sharp increases, the growth of dividends over the
past year has trailed corporate profit growth, and dividend yields
_ the payout compared to earnings _ remain well below the long-term
norms.
   Wright points out, for instance, that the 11 percent dividend
increase for the S&amp;P 500 in the past 12 months compares with a
profit rise of more than 30 percent. The increases, it states,
result in a dividend payout rate of 41 percent of profits, compared
with 50 percent for the post-World War II period.
   Wright's explanation: ``The current low payout rate is in large
part cyclical. Dividend growth normally lags in periods of strong
profit recovery, with payout catching up as profit growth slows.''
   While this would suggest futher dividend increases to come,
Wright is a bit cautious, limiting itself to forecasting ``a
reasonably good pace through 1989.''
   For this cycle, it explains, the rate of dividend payouts may
improve more slowly than normal, because funds that corporations
normally set aside for dividends may be siphoned into stock
repurchase programs.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PMs Wednesday, April 26</NOTE>
</DOC>
