<FILEID>AP-NR-04-25-89 1552EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>s e BC-WKD--DisneyStudio Adv30   04-25 1193</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-WKD--Disney Studio, Adv 30,1223</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv30</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, April 30 and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Studio Theme Park is Centerpiece of Building Boom at Florida Resort</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By IKE FLORES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LAKE BUENA VISTA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A $400 million blend of big-league
film making and Hollywood stargazing is making its debut as
Florida's top entertainment resort opens its newest attraction _
the Disney-MGM Studios theme park.
   The 135-acre complex at Walt Disney World combines working
movie-TV sound studios with backstage tours for the public, a
mixed-media ride-through show and special effects adventures.
   It's all ``themed'' to the flamboyant ambience of Hollywood's
Golden Age in the 1930s and '40s, when a small group of moguls ran
the studios with a firm hand. Art deco and ``California Crazy''
dominated the architectural styles.
   The park has its own entrance admission and more than enough
activities to fill a visitor's entire day, Disney officials say.
   Visitors will walk through re-creations of palm-lined Hollywood
Boulevard and Grumman's Chinese Theater, peek at movies under
production, take a role in an ongoing television show, make their
own music videos, get a screen test and rub elbows with the stars
at the Brown Derby restaurant.
   Movie and television production began last summer with the
``Superboy'' syndicated TV series and parts of several large-screen
films, while construction continued on the tourist portion. Workers
were still putting finishing touches on it prior to the opening on
May 1.
   Chairman Michael Eisner describes it as one of the Disney Co.'s
most exciting projects.
   ``It is a theatrical environment that is very close to the
original conception by Walt Disney,'' he said in a recent
interview. ``It's been on the shelf since the 1940s and is the
culmination of a company dream. This attraction is unlike anything
else we have.''
   The grand opening to the public is preceded by a weekend of
glitzy celebrity parties and previews that include a special on
NBC-TV (April 30), and ``live'' tapings of the TV special and the
new ``Mickey Mouse Club'' television series.
   Dick Nunis, president of Walt Disney Attractions, believes
bringing a bit of Hollywood to Florida will lure new fans and
encourage former visitors to return.
   ``We talked of doing a studio tour when Walt was alive,'' said
Nunis. ``We've wanted to do this for a long, long time. It's a
dream come true.''
   Disney will get a full year's jump on its formidable
competition, Universal Studios Florida, which won't complete the
tour portion of its $500 million complex until May 1990.
   Situated just a few miles down the road, Universal is billed as
the nation's largest working studio outside of Hollywood. Movie and
TV production is already under way at the facility owned by MCA
Inc. and Rank Organization PLC of London. It is built on a 440-acre
site.
   Universal will feature what it calls a ``total experience'' of
Hollywood-style filmmaking to the public, making the visitor a
participant in the action. It expects to attract up to 6 million
visitors a year. Disney officials do not project attendance.
   Despite their well-publicized rivalry, Disney and MCA officials
downplay the situation, insisting the competition is good for each
other as well as Florida.
   ``We've always had competition _ from Sea World, Busch Gardens,
Cape Canaveral, Boardwalk and Baseball and many others,'' Eisner
said. ``We welcome competition. It's good for Central Florida.
Disney does things in its own way, and we feel comfortable that we
will have our niche in the community.''
   The Disney-MGM theme park is the centerpiece of a $1
billion-plus renaissance of the 27,400-acre resort situated in the
pine woods and citrus groves of Central Florida near Kissimmee and
Orlando.
   Not that a rebirth is needed.
   After earning a record $3.4 billion in revenues and $522 million
in profits in fiscal 1988, the Walt Disney Co. has on tap a number
of ``openings'' at its Florida resort this year in addition to the
studios.
   On schedule to open this fall is part of what it calls the
largest convention-hotel complex in the Southeast. Making their
debut this summer will be Typhoon Lagoon (``the world's largest
water park'') and the Pleasure Island nighttime entertainment
district.
   Built for the teen-age crowd, Nunis says Typhoon Lagoon will
make all other water attractions as obsolete as Disneyland made
amusement parks in 1955.
   ``We're finally going to be able to make waves,'' says Nunis.
``Surfing, a 100-foot mountain, a saltwater snorkling reef,
including sharks and other live critters (in an enclosed area). I
can hardly wait to put on my bathing suit.''
   Pleasure Island is for those who still have energy left at the
end of an exhausting day at the Disney-MGM Studios park, Epcot
Center or the Magic Kingdom. The complex of restaurants, shops and
nightclubs is built on a six-acre island at the Disney Village.
   On track to open this fall is the 770-room Swan Hotel, which
along with the larger Dolphin Hotel will form the lodging side of
the convention-hotel complex going up near Epcot Center. The
1,500-room Dolphin is to open in July 1990. Together, the two
hotels will cost about $375 million and provide 2,300 guest rooms
and 200,000 square feet of convention space beside a 50-acre lake.
   The more modestly priced Caribbean Beach Resort hotel opens an
additional 800 rooms this summer for a total of 2,112. The 907-room
Grand Floridian Beach Resort, a luxury Victorian-style hotel,
opened last summer.
   Also set for completion this fall will be a new Epcot pavilion,
the Wonders of Life, featuring a simulated ride through the human
bloodstream and a movie that takes a viewer from conception through
birth.
   Disney does not release attendance figures, but from early
indications at Walt Disney World _ and with the debut of its new
attractions and hotel rooms this year _ it may surpass the record
year of 1987. Its Florida parks racked up some 24 million
admissions then.
   Disney World's building spree is boosting its employment rolls
and its prices as well. Disney's minimum wage is $5 an hour and it
has little trouble attracting prospective employees.
   One of its most-popular spots these days is its employment
office, which is currently hiring 2,500 new workers to help staff
some of the new attractions. This will boost Disney's work force of
25,500 by 10 percent in one month.
   Shortly after the new park opens, Disney's total of 28,000
year-round ``cast members'' will be twice what it was eight years
ago. This figure is swelled by some 5,000 employees of companies
that run hotels, restaurants and shops on Disney property, plus
parttime workers during seasonal peaks, the company says.
   The new studio attraction has also prompted a $1 increase in
one-day admission prices at the Magic Kingdom and Epcot Center, and
the introduction of a new four-day passport good at any of the
three theme parks, effective May 1.
   The new ticket will cost $94 for adults and $77 for children 3
to 9 years old. It provides unlimited admission to the three parks
for four days. New single-day admission prices for any one park
will be $29 for adults and $23 for children.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, April 30</NOTE>
</DOC>
