<SECOND>BC-WKD--Home Video, Adv 00,0341</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv00</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Anytime</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Video View: Home Video Reviews</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATRICIA BIBBY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   
   ``Eight Men Out'' (Orion Home Video. VHS-Beta, $89.98. Rated PG)
   
   Who's on first. What's on second. I don't know is on third.
Abbott and Costello made the skit a classic in 1945, and viewers of
``Eight Men Out'' might just revive it.
   The movie, as earnest as it may be in trying to present the
whole tangled scandal of the Chicago White Sox throwing the 1919
World Series, has enough faces and characters in it to pack a
locker room. And it would take extra innings to comprehend who's
doing what to whom.
   ``Eight Men Out'' begins just as the White Sox are about to meet
the Cincinnati Reds in the World Series. The team is owned by a
penny-pinching, manipulative Charles Comiskey, who has driven
morale into the ground with his cheap wages.
   Enter scheming, sleazy gamblers to capitalize on the discontent.
The ball players are approached by a cast of underworld types, and
the deal is hatched for the team to allow the Reds to win the
series.
   During the conspiracy, director John Sayles introduces the eight
crooked players, their wives and sundry girlfriends, at least two
gambling kingpins and their assistants, the team's manager and
somebody's father.
   It takes a score card to keep track of the rest.
   The White-Sox-turned-Black-Sox yarn is a good one, but this
movie has too many loose threads.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Motion Picture Association of America rating definitions:
   G _ General audiences. All ages admitted.
   PG _ Parental guidance suggested. Some material may not be
suitable for children.
   PG-13 _ Special parental guidance strongly suggested for
children under 13. Some material may be inappropriate for young
children.
   R _ Restricted. Under 17 requires accompanying parent or adult
guardian.
   X _ No one under 17 admitted. Some states may have higher age
restrictions.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Release Anytime</NOTE>
</DOC>
