<DOCNO> AP890425-0235 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-25-89 0649EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a e BC-WKD--RecordReviews Adv00   04-25 0597</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-WKD--Record Reviews, Adv 00,0619</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv00</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Anytime</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>In the Groove: Record Reviews</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   
   Symphony in B-flat; Psalm 23; Alexander Zemlinsky; Riccardo
Chailly conducting the Radio-Symphonie-Orchester Berlin and
Kammerchor (London)
   
   It's always a pleasure to come across an unfamiliar performer
giving a familiar work a superlative reading. It's even better to
discover exciting, lesser-known music, particularly when the
performance is as excellent as that of Chailly and the RSO on this
disc.
   Zemlinsky (1871-1942) was a prominent teacher, composer and
international conductor whose musicial life centered in Vienna. He
moved to Prague in 1938, escaped during the war to this country and
died, oddly, in Larchmont, N.Y., a suburb of New York City.
Schoenberg was his brother-in-law and pupil, and Webern also
studied with him. Mahler was a friend and supporter, and Brahms
recommended Zemlinsky to his own publisher. No lack of favor from
the musical community here.
   He wrote a quartet of string quartets, a half-dozen works for
orchestra and chorus, seven operas and three symphonies, including
the B-flat in 1897 _ the year of Brahms' death.
   The work sounds at times like a cross of the better halves of
Brahms and Mahler, though without their depth. But Zemlinsky has
his own world of orchestral sound. Chailly understands that. He
also seems to understand exactly what to do with each phrase, even
more so at times than Zemlinsky, whose style can seem fragmented.
   Psalm 23 sounds more Mahler-esque, maybe because of the chorus.
   The recorded sound of the orchestra is crystal clear and nigh
perfect. Instruments blend but stand out when need be, never out of
balance. The RSO musicians play difficult music with panache.
   Buy this disc not because no collection is complete without
Zemlinksy, but because no listener is complete without a desire to
hear the new and unfamiliar. And buy it because Chailly and the RSO
deliver a great performance.
   _ By Daniel Wakin, Associated Press Writer.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   
   ``Blast Off'' (EMI USA) _ Stray Cats
   
   Now this is the way to do a rock 'n' roll reunion. Invite a
couple of buddies over, turn the speakers up real loud and _ to
steal a phrase _ blast off.
   The Stray Cats, pinup boys and rockabilly revivalists in the
long ago days of President Reagan's first term, drifted apart when
the hits stopped coming. Now they're back with ``Blast Off,'' an
unexpectedly delightful reunion LP that kicks, snarls, scratches
and bites.
   Unlike most ponderous reunions where middle aged rockers check
their lawyers at the door, ``Blast Off'' sounds like that jam
session with old friends where someone left a tape recorder on.
   Sure, it's more complicated than that. But it doesn't sound that
way, and that's the key.
   Age hasn't diminished the Cats' skill and spirit. It may even
have helped; singer Brian Setzer's voice has deepened into an
effective growl with none of the precocity of his youth.
   And producer Dave Edmunds, the ultimate kindred spirit, was a
perfect choice to guide this project. His voice brightens the
catchy singalong, ``Bring It Back Again.''
   Don't look for particularly deep statements. The Stray Cats must
set a record for most songs on one 10-song album with the word
``rock'' in the title (4). ``Everybody Needs Rock 'n' Roll,''
``Rockabilly Rules,'' ``Rockabilly Worlds'' and ``Rockin' All Over
the Place'' are all high octane.
   For what it aspires to _ the soundtrack for a terrific party _
``Blast Off'' is a howling success.
   _ By David Bauder, Associated Press Writer.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Release Anytime</NOTE>
