<HEAD>For Release Weekend Editions, May 5-7 and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Music Makers: He Loves To Do That Wild Thang</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD DE ATLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tone Loc, the raspy-voiced rapper whose bawdy
``Wild Thing'' went to the top of the charts, didn't think the tune
about a pickup artist on a streak of amazing luck was hit material.
   ``The record company (Delicious Vinyl) did. I didn't. It's not
my style of rap,'' the 22-year-old Los Angeles native said in a
recent interview. ``I mean, `Loc'd After Dark' is really my style
of rap _ slow and funky, that's how I like it.''
   The song was a No. 1 hit for Loc, whose real name is Tony Smith.
Loc is short for loco, a gang term for a crazy man who likes to
fight.
   But Loc, who grew up in a two-story house on the affluent west
side of Los Angeles and went to University High School and Santa
Monica College, had to travel by bus to the city's tough south side
to get his reputation.
   He was uncomforable dwelling on gangs during the interview.
However, in the past he has said he was involved with a gang during
his teens but withdrew because a girlfriend asked him to _ a choice
kids locked into the southside scene usually don't get.
   But his commuter-gang experience had nothing to do with his
interest in rap, he said. ``I found it out on my own, clear out of
the blue.''
   Loc said a friend from New Jersey came to Los Angeles about
eight years ago with a tape that he rapped along to.
   ``I never saw anybody rap live before. It was pretty new,
especially out here. I went home and tried to write one of my own,
and it sounded pretty cool,'' he said.
   All the original big rappers, such as Kurtis Blow and Kool Moe
Dee, were from the East Coast. Only recently have West Coast
rappers been taken seriously in the genre. Early 1980s acts such as
the LA Dream Team failing to take hold. Loc said the West Coast
rappers now have developed their own laid-back style rather than
trying to imitate the uptempo hip-hop from the East.
   ``We've grown tremendously out here,'' he said. ``We've got a
groove that slow. I'm a slower, more mellow type.''
   Loc's own rap experience came during high school, with a group
called the Triple A's because all the members first names began
with ``A.''
   ``There really wasn't too much happening with it. I think we
were too good for our time,'' he said. Loc was a rap retiree by age
20, but took it up again when the Los Angeles rap scene began to
heat up. A cousin introduced him to Matt Dike and Mike Ross,
founders of the small Delicious Vinyl label, and two of Loc's
records, ``I Got It Goin' On'' and ``I'm on Fire,'' received play
on local station KDAY.
   But it was the crossover appeal of ``Wild Thing,'' which got
play on new wave station KROQ in Los Angeles last fall, that helped
launch Loc, Los Angeles rap, and Delicious Vinyl, now distributed
by Island Records.
   As for ``Wild Thing,'' Loc said he pieced the song together
pretty much from personal experience.
   ``You change a little bit here and there, but the idea comes
from something that happened to you,'' he said.
   Does he get any static for the lyrics?
   ``Nah. All the girls I know love it,'' he laughed. ``Besides,
they know it's all true.''
   Loc is currently on tour for his album ``Loc'd After Dark,''
which is climbing the Billboard pop and black charts, facing crowds
of up to 18,000 in arenas.
   ``I was playing clubs in January and February,'' he said. ``It's
different, but it's the same. I really like the hype.''
   And the crowds join in on ``Wild Thing.''
   ``They rap right along with it,'' Loc said.
   Loc is casual so far about his own success. When asked, he
didn't know exactly where his records were on the charts, except to
say ``I know a lot of people are buying them.''
   There is also street recognition for the husky 6-foot-1 Loc, who
appears in the heavy rotation ``Wild Thing'' video clip, which
borrows the expressionless all-woman band from Robert Palmer's ``I
Didn't Mean to Turn You On.''
   Loc's own stock is soaring, and he finds some things more
difficult to do, such as shopping in a mall.
   ``When I'm shopping or eating, I get swarmed. You can hear
people saying `Is that Tone Loc? Yeah, that's him.' But they're
always nice to me and stuff, and I love that. Plus, I can get into
a lot more clubs now,'' he said laughing.
   ``It's nothing like Michael Jackson or anything, but I can
definitely tell the difference,'' he said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Weekend Editions, May 5-7</NOTE>
