<FIRST>r f PM-BusinessHighlights    04-25 0877</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Business Highlights, </SECOND>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eastern Airlines would slash its workforce by 43
percent from pre-strike levels and raise $1.8 billion from asset
sales under a new business plan presented to the airline's
creditors.
   The proposal, which must be approved by creditors and a federal
bankruptcy judge, calls for Eastern to reduce its fleet size to 157
aircraft from 255 and the number of cities served to 77 from a
pre-strike 102.
   Eastern President Phil Bakes on Monday would not specify all the
cities where Eastern would cut service, but said the company would
sell its Philadelphia hub, a total of 117 unspecified airport gates
and 28 landing slots, and de-emphasize some foreign routes.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Exxon Corp.'s first-quarter earnings fell 13
percent as rising crude oil prices took a bite out of refining
margins and the Alaskan oil spill took a toll mostly on the
company's image.
   For the three months ended March 31, earnings at the nation's
biggest oil company declined to $1.3 billion, or 99 cents a share,
from $1.5 billion, or $1.06 a share, in the first quarter of last
year. Revenue rose 1 percent to $22.2 billion compared with $22
billion in the 1988 period, Exxon said Monday.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LUXEMBOURG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States and the European Economic
Community are near an agreement in their dispute over an EEC ban on
imports of U.S. beef treated with growth-boosting hormones, a Dutch
official said.
   U.S. officials have agreed to let the EEC certify U.S. beef due
to be exported to the EEC as having been raised without the use of
hormones, Dutch Secretary of State for Foreign Affairs Yvonne van
Rooy said Monday.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CHARLOTTE, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   NCNB Inc. said it has dropped its $2.4
billion bid to acquire Citizens &amp; Southern Corp. because the
Atlanta bank refused to discuss the proposal.
   The Charlotte, N.C., banking company launched the takeover bid
last month. It was promptly rejected by the C&amp;S board, which turned
down appeals by NCNB Chairman Hugh L. McColl to negotiate a new
deal. McColl withdrew the offer in a statement Monday.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Noboru Takeshita announced today he
will resign to take responsibility for a massive influence-peddling
scandal involving stock trading that he said has led to growing
public distrust of politicians.
   The scandal and a widely criticized sales tax that took effect
April 1 sent his popularity rating skidding to a rock-bottom 3.9
percent and made him Japan's most unpopular prime minister since
World War II.
   Takeshita, 65, spoke at a nationally televised news conference
after telling a Cabinet meeting he would end his 18-month tenure in
office, half of it a downhill slide due to a scandal named after
the Recruit Co. conglomerate.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court has refused to intervene in
the controversy over Alar, rejecting attempts to revive a lawsuit
by Ralph Nader and others aimed at banning use of the chemical on
apples.
   The suit, which the justices let die Monday without comment, had
sought to force the Environmental Protection Agency to immediately
ban Alar, used primarily to enhance apples' color, ripening and
shelf life.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court has left intact a $101
million refund some of the nation's telephone companies were
ordered to pay customers for excessive charges in 1978.
   The court, without comment, Monday rejected arguments that the
Federal Communications Commission overstepped its authority in
ordering the refunds.
   The commission in 1976 allowed American Telephone &amp; Telegraph
Co. to set phone rates designed to yield a rate of return of up to
10 percent a year. AT&amp;T's earnings in 1978 exceeded the 10 percent
figure by $101 million, the commission ruled in 1984.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Swiss drug manufacturing giant F.
Hoffmann-La Roche &amp; Co. Inc. said it will modernize its share
structure and reorganize its corporate framework.
   The changes announced Monday would make it easier to invest in
the company and conform to pending changes in Swiss corporate law.
Hoffmann-La Roche failed in a takeover bid for Sterling Drug Inc.
last year, and the streamlining could help the company in other
U.S. takeover attempts, some analysts said. The company's U.S. arm
is based in Nutley, N.J.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   First Boston Corp. is reducing its staff by
about 200 employees in the latest cutback by Wall Street firms
attributed to a weak securities market.
   The nation's sixth largest investment firm said Monday the
reductions were being made this week through a combination of
attrition, voluntary departures and layoffs. Spokeswoman Monica
Prihoda declined to say how many people were being fired or from
which departments the cuts were being made.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>By The Associated Press</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices posted spotty losses Monday as traders cashed in
some of the market's recent gains. The Dow Jones industrial
average, up 72.40 points last week, slipped 6.78 to 2,402.68.
   The dollar drifted higher against most major currencies.
   Bond prices finished little changed.
   Weekend showers in one of the driest parts of the Corn Belt
triggered a steep sell-off of corn and soybean futures; oats closed
lower; wheat futures gained slightly; energy futures plunged;
precious metals advanced; and livestock and meat futures were mixed.
