<FIRST>r f PM-FirstBoston-Cuts     04-25 0281</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-First Boston-Cuts,0294</SECOND>
<HEAD>Investment Bank To Reduce Staff By 200, Citing Slow Business</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   First Boston Corp. said the Wall Street slowdown
has prompted the investment firm to reduce its staff by about 200
employees through a combination of attrition, voluntary departures
and layoffs.
   The nation's sixth-largest investment firm said Monday the
reductions were being made this week.
   Spokeswoman Monica Prihoda declined to say how many people were
being fired or from which departments the cuts were being made.
   First Boston Chief Executive William Mayer said in a memo to the
company's workers that the cuts were being made ``to reflect
current business conditions.''
   ``For well over a year, nearly every area of business has been
impacted by a weak market,'' Mayer said. ``Those of you who have
been in the industry for longer than five years are familiar with
up and down cycles. First Boston is not alone: all securities firms
are feeling the pressure.''
   The cuts trim First Boston's payroll to 4,700, about 1,000 fewer
than before the October 1987 stock market crash.
   The firm said it would remain active in all current areas of
business.
   The reductions come amid a series of announcements of earnings
declines and losses on Wall Street.
   On Monday, Salomon Inc. reported a $28 million first-quarter
loss, with its energy business compensating for $150 million in
losses by securities and commodities segments. Several other firms
earlier reported earnings drops.
   Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. last week announced it would sell
its retail brokerage unit, which has 2,300 workers, because of poor
business. A deal with Smith Barney Harris Upham &amp; Co. was reported
close Monday, but both firms declined to comment.
</TEXT>
