<FIRST>r f PM-Fairchild     04-25 0198</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Fairchild,0208</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fairchild To Sell Industrial Product Operation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHANTILLY, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fairchild Industries Inc. has announced it
will sell one of its industrial product operations to a group of
senior managers.
   The terms of the sale, disclosed Monday, were not announced.
   The operation, Fairchild Industrial Products Co. of
Winston-Salem, N.C., makes pneumatic and electronic controls for
industrial and commercial markets.
   The operation, which employs about 150 workers, accounted for 10
percent of the revenues and 15 percent of the profits of the
company's industrial products division, according to Deborah
Tucker, a company spokeswoman.
   The overall division, which has two other components,
contributed $150 million in revenues and about $19.7 million in
profits to the parent firm last year, Ms. Tucker said.
   Fairchild put the three companies in the division up for sale in
1987. When no acceptable offers were submitted by last year, Ms.
Tucker said, the operations were pulled from the market, although
quiet negotiations continued.
   Fairchild and The Carlyle Group, a Washington-based merchant
bank, are negotiating for a sale of the entire company. Ms. Tucker
said the sale of the division was not related to those ongoing
talks.
   Fairchild is a diversified aerospace company.
</TEXT>
