<FILEID>AP-NR-04-25-89 0205EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-IBM     04-25 0547</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-IBM,0566</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sales Stagnate In U.S., Akers Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EARL BOHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   International Business Machines Corp. can
revive its stagnant U.S. sales and pull away from competitors by
getting closer to its customers, Chairman John F. Akers told
shareholders at their annual meeting.
   ``IBM must become a company ... that won't rest until every
customer is not just satisfied, but delighted, with every
association with IBM,'' he said here Monday. ``Everything else will
follow, market share, revenue, profit, returns and stockholder
value.
   ``We intend to accomplish all this ... not by selling them
smaller and faster machines to replace more clerical duties, but
rather working more closely with them to get an ever deeper
understanding of their businesses,'' he said.
   IBM's revenue in the United States, the largest single market
for the world's largest computer manufacturer, declined 0.7 percent
last year to $25.3 billion.
   Measured in local currencies, South American sales grew 21
percent last year, the most among IBM's major geographic markets,
Akers said. Revenue in local currencies grew by 14 percent in Asia
and the Pacific, and by 9 percent in Europe, the Middle East and
Africa.
   Because of changes in the value of the dollar in terms of
various foreign currencies, the dollar value of foreign revenue was
different from the value in local currencies.
   Overall, revenue outside the United States increased 15.5
percent to $34.4 billion when measured in dollars. By the same
measure, the greatest revenue growth was 27.7 percent in Asia and
the Pacific, followed by growth of 21 percent to $3.9 billion in
the Americas, according to the company's annual report.
   Akers said IBM is battling rapid advances in computer
technology, growing needs of customers and thousands of competing
companies, from the small and nimble to the big full-line vendors.
   ``As a result, the industry is under a good deal of stress as
evidenced by pressure on profitability and decline in stock prices,
including IBM's stock price, over the last several months,'' he
said.
   IBM, based in Armonk, N.Y., remains ``the most profitable
company in the world and continues to lead all American companies
in market value,'' Akers said.
   First-quarter profit totaled $950 million, or $1.61 per share,
on revenue of $12.7 billion. After adopting a new treatment of
deferred taxes, IBM restated its 1988 first-quarter profit as $1.2
billion, or $1.57 per share, on revenue of $12 billion.
   Without the accounting change, the 1989 first quarter would have
represented a 1.8 percent increase in profits.
   While in Pittsburgh for the annual shareholders meeting Monday,
the board increased the regular quarterly dividend 10 percent, from
$1.10 per share to $1.21 per share.
   Management received overwhelming support for a proposal to
expand a program of awarding stock options to executives. The
company's Long-Term Peformance Plan will enable the top officers to
receive stock as well as cash.
   Shareholders rejected a proposal to force IBM to discontinue
selling computers and services in South Africa, where it no longer
owns a subsidiary. The proposal was supported by 14.5 percent of
the shares voted.
   A proposal that would have required management to report to
shareholders on any ways in which IBM supports painful laboratory
experiments on animals received 7.8 percent of the shares voted.
   Management opposed both proposals.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
