<BYLINE>Eastern Before And After Proposed Downsizing</BYLINE>
<HEAD>With PM-Eastern, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is a look at Eastern Airlines before the strike that
started March 4 and under management's plan proposed Monday to
sharply reduce the carrier's size and sell $1.8 billion in assets.
Eastern is under Chapter 11 bankruptcy protection from creditors
due to the strike by its Machinists and sympathy walkouts by its
pilots and flight attendants. The plan must be approved by
creditors and a federal bankruptcy judge.
   --- 
   Owner: The 60-year-old airline has been owned by Texas Air
Corp., headed by Chairman Frank Lorenzo, since 1986.
   Headquarters: Miami. Would remain there under proposed
streamlining.
   Employees: Before strike: 31,200, including 3,600 pilots. Under
plan: 17,000, including 1,700 pilots.
   Size of fleet: Before strike: 255 jets. Under plan: 157.
   Cities served: Before strike: 102, with major markets in South
Florida, the Caribbean, East Coast and Latin America. Under plan:
77, unspecified.
   Number of daily scheduled flight hours: Before strike: 2,076.
Under plan: 1,473.
   Passengers: Before strike: 100,000 average daily. Under plan:
unknown.
   Target date for emergence from Chapter 11: September 1989.
