<FIRST>r f PM-Minorco-GoldFields     04-25 0513</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Minorco-Gold Fields,0533</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Judge Ties Up Massive British Takeover Battle</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The clock is running out for South Africa-linked
Minorco S.A. _ the world's largest gold producer _ to complete its
hostile takeover of Consolidated Gold Fields PLC of Great Britain,
the No. 2 gold concern.
   U.S. District Judge Michael B. Mukasey, who issued a preliminary
injunction barring the takeover bid in October, on Monday rejected
another request by Minorco to lift or modify his order.
   Minorco's $4 billion bid expires at 1 p.m. London time
Wednesday, and unless the Luxembourg-based conglomerate is able to
acquire half of Gold Fields' shares by the deadline, it would be
barred from attempting another takeover for one year under British
law.
   Minorco controls 29.6 percent of the stock of Gold Fields.
   Last month, the 2nd U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals in Manhattan
upheld Mukasey's original injunction against further Gold Fields
stock acquisition by Minorco because it might violate U.S.
antitrust laws.
   Minorco, through its various holdings, ``is the largest producer
of gold in the non-communist world, accounting for 20.3 percent of
all gold production,'' according to court papers.
   Last fall, Minorco, which is largely controlled by two South
African corporations, Anglo American Corp. of South Africa Ltd. and
De Beers Consolidated Mines Ltd., launched a hostile takeover bid
for Gold Fields.
   But Gold Fields resisted and filed an antitrust action in New
York, sparking one of the largest takeover battles in British
history.
   Mukasey's preliminary injunction last fall prevented Minorco
from proceeding with its tender offer until the antitrust issue is
resolved.
   Just before Mukasey's ruling, the bid was referred to Britain's
Monopolies and Mergers Commission to consider possible
anti-competitive consequences in the United Kingdom on such
strategic metals as titanium and zircon.
   British law prohibited further action on the takeover bid until
Feb. 2, when the commission held that acquisition of Gold Fields
would not be against the British public interest.
   With that ruling, Mukasey's injunction remained the only legal
obstacle to Minorco's offer.
   Last week, Mukasey rejected a Minorco bid to lift or modify the
stay.
   To eliminate antitrust conflicts, Minorco offered to sell
substantial Gold Fields subsidiaries _ Gold Fields of South Africa,
U.S.-based Newmont Mining Corp. and Australian-based Renison
Goldfields Ltd. _ and not buy them back for 10 years.
   But Mukasey said there was no guarantee the other Minorco-linked
entities _ DeBeers and Anglo American _ wouldn't buy back the
subsidiaries and keep the transactions secret under sympathetic
South African laws.
   He noted at the time that he ``enjoined the takeover because the
resulting combination would control 32.3 percent of the
non-communist world gold market.''
   On Monday, Minorco, Anglo and DeBeers offered to put up a total
of $300 million bond and pledged not only to sell the previously
mentioned properties but to not buy them back for at least 10 years.
   But Mukasey rejected that offer because, he said, ``members of
the Anglo group other than Anglo, DeBeers ... remain free to
purchase shares in the three companies.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
