<FIRST>r f BC-NCNB-C&amp;S-Chronology     04-25 0268</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-NCNB-C&amp;S-Chronology,0281</SECOND>
<HEAD>Key Events In NCNB-C&amp;S Merger Maneuvering</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-NCNB-C&amp;S, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHARLOTTE, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is a summary of offers,
counteroffers and refusals made since Charlotte-based NCNB Corp.
first made its bid for The Citizens &amp; Southern Corp. of Atlanta:
   March 30 _ NCNB Corp. makes a $2.4 billion merger proposal to
The Citizens &amp; Southern Corp., which would create the nation's
sixth-largest banking company.
   April 3 _ C&amp;S board of directors rejects the NCNB offer. NCNB
Chairman Hugh McColl says the bank will continue to pursue
negotiations on the merger, and asks the board to reconsider.
   April 7 _ NCNB announces that it would like a face-to-face
meeting with C&amp;S officials, but C&amp;S continues to call the offer
inadequate.
   April 11 _ McColl announces that NCNB will continue to pursue
the acquisition.
   April 13 _ McColl visits Atlanta, saying his offer is friendly,
but does not meet with C&amp;S officials.
   April 15 _ NCNB offers a plan to move the firm's Southeast
headquarters to Atlanta to encourage C&amp;S directors to engage in
friendly negotiation. C&amp;S officials say they have nothing to talk
about.
   April 17 _ McColl offers to increase bid by an unspecified
amount, but only if there is a face-to-face meeting between NCNB
and C&amp;S officials.
   April 18 _ C&amp;S shareholders meet in Atlanta; McColl does not
attend. C&amp;S Chairman Bennett Brown tells shareholders that NCNB
cannot afford C&amp;S.
   April 20 _ Sen. Wyche Fowler Jr., D-Ga., asks Congress to
introduce legislation designed to block the NCNB takeover bid.
   April 24 _ NCNB announces that it will withdraw its bid to
acquire C&amp;S.
</TEXT>
