<DOCNO> AP890425-0249 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-25-89 0214EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Eastern Bjt   04-25 0644</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Eastern, Bjt,0664</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eastern Could Have Much Different Shape Under Plan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCY GORDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The contours of strike-torn Eastern Airlines
could be markedly changed under management's proposed plan to
rebuild as a smaller carrier and sell $1.8 billion in assets.
   The plan presented Monday to Eastern's major creditors, which
must be approved by them and a federal bankruptcy judge, would
slash the airline's work force by 43 percent from levels before the
strike that started March 4. Eastern's unions as well as U.S.
Bankruptcy Judge Burton R. Lifland have been pushing for a sale of
the entire carrier by its parent, Texas Air Corp.
   If management's plan were approved, Miami-based Eastern would
cut its fleet size to 157 aircraft from the current 255 and the
number of cities served to 77 from a pre-strike 102.
   Eastern President Phil Bakes would not specify all the cities
where Eastern would cut service, but told a press briefing the
company would sell its Northeast shuttle service and Philadelphia
hub, along with a total of 117 unspecified airport gates and 28
landing slots, and de-emphasize some foreign routes.
   While keeping many of the plan's details under wraps, Bakes did
say Eastern would retain its Atlanta hub, its routes linking
Northeast cities with Florida and some or all of its Caribbean
service. The Atlanta hub, which vies with Delta Air Lines, accounts
for 35 percent to 40 percent of Eastern's total revenue.
   ``I think it's very aggressive but I think it's possible,'' said
Raymond Neidl, a securities analyst at McCarthy, Crisanti &amp; Maffei
Inc. who follows Texas Air.
   Neidl and other observers believe the plan could strip Eastern
down mainly to its heavy North-South routes on the East Coast,
eliminating its East-West runs. As the airline's network is
currently structured, the East Coast is densely covered but routes
become much sparser as they move west _ they mainly include cities
such as Los Angeles, San Francisco, Phoenix, Seattle, Portland,
Ore., and Salt Lake City.
   Eastern also could sell its South American routes and part of
its Caribbean service, possibly including its hub in San Juan,
Puerto Rico, Neidl suggested.
   Eastern has been flying substantially reduced schedules since a
March 4 strike by its Machinists union, which was joined by
Eastern's pilots and flight attendants unions. The company sought
federal bankruptcy court protection from creditors on March 9.
   Under the new plan, Eastern would emerge from Chapter 11 by
September, Bakes said _ a target that Neidl called overly
optimistic.
   Fleet size would be reduced by aircraft sales and by leasing
planes to other carriers, Bakes said.
   Employment at the scaled-down Eastern would total about 17,000,
down from a pre-strike 30,000, Bakes said. The total would include
1,700 pilots, down from 3,600 before the strike, he said.
   Eastern would cut its daily scheduled flight hours to 1,473 from
2,076 under the plan.
   Dan Ashby, a spokesman for the Air Line Pilots Association, said
the plan would not work, partly because Eastern would not be able
to get enough pilots to fly its planes.
   Bakes said Eastern plans to hire and train new pilots at the
rate of 200 a month.
   Eastern indicated that by yearend under the plan it would have
$1.8 billion in net cash from asset sales, giving it a net cash
balance of $774 million after paying creditors and pension
obligations.
   Texas Air Chairman Frank Lorenzo has insisted he no longer is
interested in selling all of Eastern, following the collapse of a
proposed $464 million deal with a group led by former Baseball
Commissioner Peter V. Ueberroth.
   The federal bankruptcy examiner for Eastern said Monday that
further bids to acquire the airline could be made as early as this
week by suitors who include hotel executive Jay Pritzker and Trans
World Airlines Inc. Chairman Carl C. Icahn.
   

</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890425-0250 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-25-89 0231EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-NCNB-C&amp;S Bjt   04-25 0699</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-NCNB-C&amp;S, Bjt,0724</SECOND>
<HEAD>NCNB Drops C&amp;S Takeover Bid That Would Have Been Largest Bank Merger</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL NOWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLOTTE, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rather than wage a bitter battle with
Citizens &amp; Southern Corp. of Atlanta, NCNB Corp. has withdrawn its
$2.4 billion takeover attempt, scuttling what would have been the
largest merger in U.S. banking history.
   ``I recommended to our board of directors that we terminate the
offer,'' NCNB Chairman Hugh McColl said Monday.
   ``I did so because, as was evident in our proposal and
throughout subsequent communications, we were committed to a
friendly merger,'' he said. ``The management and directors of C&amp;S,
for reasons satisfactory to themselves, have decided not to accept
our offer. I see no benefit in continuing it.''
   The announcement was made after the close of trading Monday on
the New York Stock Exchange. NCNB had risen 25 cents a share to
$36.37{ and Citizens &amp; Southern had fallen 62{ cents a share to $34.
   The merger, which consisted of a stock swap, would have created
the nation's sixth-largest banking company. But the Atlanta bank
refused to discuss the proposal.
   C&amp;S chairman Bennett Brown said he ``believed from the beginning
that this offer was not in the best interests of our shareholders,
customers, employees and communities, and that it would meet
significant regulatory difficulties and public policy concern.''
   ``Both these fine institutions can now get back to the business
of banking and serving their communities,'' Brown said.
   One analyst said he wasn't surprised by McColl's decision to
drop the bid because NCNB needed the merger to be friendly.
   ``They wanted to retain the management strengths of C&amp;S,'' said
the analyst, Dennis Shea of Morgan Stanley &amp; Co. in New York.
   Just four months ago, NCNB, which has assets of more than $50
billion, effectively doubled its size when it was selected by the
Federal Deposit Insurance Corp. to acquire the largest bank in
Texas, First RepublicBank Corp.
   Since 1982, NCNB has expanded aggressively into new markets in
Florida, South Carolina, Georgia and Tennessee. The First
RepublicBank move was the biggest until the C&amp;S offer.
   Tony Davis, a bank stock analyst with Wheat First Securities in
Richmond, Va., agreed that NCNB could not go ahead with the
takeover bid without the support of C&amp;S's managment.
   ``I think you have to take them at their word,'' he said. ``They
said they wanted a friendly merger. It was important as they
approached the Georgia market that they had the endorsement of the
folks at C&amp;S.''
   Chris Davis of Wheat First's Charlotte office added that NCNB
needed a friendly merger because ``they have a full plate in
Texas.''
   Shea said NCNB was going after a respected bank with a strong
management team that could have offered the Charlotte bank
considerable help down the road in its expansion into Texas and
Florida.
   ``If C&amp;S continued to refuse to negotiate, NCNB was not going to
pull off a friendly merger,'' he said. ``I think NCNB realized that
it could not negotiate in a vacuum. They couldn't just keep upping
the price.''
   Shea also suggested that NCNB may have underestimated C&amp;S's
unwillingness to participate in the deal.
   NCNB made the offer, which would have created a banking company
with assets of $76 billion, on March 30, and on April 3, the C&amp;S
board rejected the offer. At the time, C&amp;S called the bid
``inadequate,'' and said C&amp;S' present management was better able to
serve the bank's customers, shareholders and communities than NCNB.
   NCNB continued to court C&amp;S, asking for face-to-face meetings,
and adding different elements to the proposals, including a plan to
move NCNB's Southeast banking headquarters to Atlanta.
   On April 13, McColl visited Atlanta and vowed to continue to
pursue to the offer, though he did not meet with any C&amp;S officials.
Five days later, C&amp;S Chairman Bennett Brown urged shareholders to
support the C&amp;S board in its rejection of the NCNB offer.
   ``Let me put it bluntly,'' Brown said at the time. ``NCNB cannot
afford C&amp;S.''
   Last week, McColl announced that his bank would increase its bid
if C&amp;S officials agreed to meet with NCNB executives. McColl did
not indicate how high the offer would go.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
