<DOCNO> AP890425-0251 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-25-89 0256EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Northwest Bjt   04-25 0691</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Northwest, Bjt,0714</SECOND>
<HEAD>NWA Board Rejects Davis Offer, Amends Court Complaint</HEAD>
<DATELINE>EAGAN, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Calling parts of oilman Marvin Davis' $2.7
billion bid for Northwest Airlines illegal and unfinanced, NWA
Inc.'s board of directors unanimously rejected the offer and moved
to take further court action to block the efforts.
   The board on Monday reaffirmed its willingness to negotiate with
suitors, including Davis, ``in the interest of producing a
transaction that is in the best interests of all NWA
shareholders.'' But it said it will seek a quick hearing on a
motion to enjoin Davis' $90-a-share tender offer.
   The board also said it is working with an undisclosed number of
other parties that have indicated an interest in acquiring
Northwest, the nation's fourth-largest carrier.
   NWA stock closed at $102.75 Monday, up 25 cents a share in New
York Stock Exchange composite trading.
   In an amended complaint in U.S. District Court in Minneapolis,
the NWA board said Davis' financing plan would exceed federal
margin rules aimed at limiting the amount of credit used to buy
stock. The board said $1.25 billion in preferred stock financing
planned for Davis' buyout actually should be considered debt.
   The motion also claims Davis' tender offer actually was an
illegal proxy solicitation that provided insufficient information
to shareholders regarding the source and availability of $450
million in equity Davis said he would provide for the buyout.
   In addition, Minnesota Commerce Commissioner Michael Hatch said
Monday he found Davis Acquisition Inc.'s registration statement
offering to purchase all of NWA Inc.'s outstanding shares deficient.
   Hatch said Davis failed to disclose the manner in which he would
operate NWA so as to expand its operation and not dispose of
``strategic'' assets of the company or lay off employees.
   Additionally, the commissioner said, Davis did not disclose
plans relating to an Airbus maintenance facility that he said he
intended to locate in Minnesota.
   Hatch scheduled a hearing on the matter for this evening, and
said the registration would be suspended Friday if the deficiencies
are not corrected.
   Jim Fingeroth, a Davis spokesman, said the acquisition company
had no comment on the order.
   Davis' attorneys, meanwhile, were shoring up their efforts in
Delaware, where NWA is incorporated. His lawyers argued in a
Wilmington, Del., court against a provision in NWA's ``poison
pill'' takeover defense that is hindering his efforts to put a new
NWA board of directors in place.
   The defense effectively would block a new board of directors
from selling NWA for 180 days.
   The prospect of a long delay would discourage shareholders from
supporting Davis in the proxy fight planned at NWA's May 15 annual
meeting, attorney Gilchrist Sparks told the hearing.
   NWA Chairman Steven Rothmeier has said he prefers to see the
airline remain independent or find a ``white knight'' investor to
work with current management.
   In letters to the 5,000 union pilots at Northwest, Rothmeier
said last week that ``there are alternatives available to us from
friendly investors.''
   But, he said, the assistance is contingent upon a contract
settlement with the pilots, who have been working under two
separate contracts since Northwest acquired Republic Airlines in
1986.
   Davis' Delaware court action altered the course of his fight
against the Northwest poison pill. He initially sought to
invalidate the entire poison plan, which would more than double the
cost of a potential acquisition by a hostile bidder by flooding the
market with new NWA shares.
   But Sparks said Monday that Davis would like to retain the pill
for his own use in the event he gained control of the board.
   Rothmeier has declined to identify any potential friendly
investors, but the company has said a group holding 4.9 percent of
NWA's 29.1 million shares outstanding is interested in a leveraged
buyout. In a leveraged buyout, a company is bought with largely
borrowed funds.
   The group includes Los Angeles-based investor Alfred Checchi and
former NWA board member Gary Wilson, now an executive for Walt
Disney Co.
   The New York Times reported Monday that Kelso &amp; Co., a small
investment bank based in New York, is considering a bid for the
airline. Spokesman for Kelso and Northwest declined to comment.
</TEXT>
