<FIRST>u f PM-Dollar-Gold     04-25 0294</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Dollar-Gold,0308</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar, Gold Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar rose in quiet early European trading
today. Gold prices also were higher.
   Foreign currency dealers said they were waiting for the 8:30
a.m. EDT release of U.S. durable goods orders for March. A rise of
1.5 percent or more could send the dollar higher, dealers said.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day
begins, the dollar fell 0.21 yen to a closing 131.17 following
Prime Minister Noboru Takeshita's announcement he intends to
resign. Later, in London, it was quoted at 131.35 yen.
   Dealers in Frankfurt said Takeshita's announcement did not
affect European exchange rates because the markets had been
expecting it for a week.
   ``It's very quiet today,'' said Alfred Zapfel, a trader at Bank
of Boston in Frankfurt. ``The dollar isn't doing very much ...
We'll have to wait for durable goods to see if something will
happen.''
   Other dollar rates at midmorning, compared with late Monday's
prices, included: 1.8658 West German marks, up from 1.8575; 1.6460
Swiss francs, up from 1.6395; 6.3165 French francs, up from 6.2975;
2.0001 Dutch guilders, down from 2.0960; 1.1889 Canadian dollars,
down from 1.1890.
   In London, one British pound cost $1.7018, cheaper for buyers
than $1.7050 late Monday.
   Markets were closed in Italy for a national holiday.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $385.50 a troy ounce, up
from $384.90 bid late Monday. At midmorning, the city's five major
bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $385.85.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $385.50, up from $384.65 bid late
Monday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold rose $1.51 to close at a bid $386.57.
   Silver was quoted in London at a bid price of $5.80 a troy
ounce, down from Monday's $5.81.
</TEXT>
