<FIRST>u f PM-Japan-Scandal-Glance     04-25 0335</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Scandal-Glance,0346</SECOND>
<HEAD>A Glance At The Government-Toppling Recruit Scandal</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Japan-Politics Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is a glance at the Recruit scandal, which
claimed its biggest victim today when Prime Minister Noboru
Takeshita announced his intention to resign:
   THE ORIGIN: In late 1986 Recruit Co. offered bargain-priced
shares in a real estate subsidiary to more than 150 leading
politicians, bureaucrats, business leaders and media executives.
The shares doubled in value after they went on public sale,
yielding big profits to the holders who sold.
   Prosecutors, who have arrested 14 people, allege the
transactions were bribes in which Recruit sought special favors
from government bureaucrats in a position to influence or regulate
Recruit's businesses in job-placement magazines or
telecommunications. No politicians have been arrested.
   TAKESHITA'S LINK: Like most other politicians, Takeshita's name
was not on share transactions, but an aide and a relative profited
to a total of $192,000.
   The prime minister also acknowledged that he received more than
$1 million in political donations and contributions to fund-raising
parties from Recruit.
   He told Parliament the donations were legal and sought to put
the matter behind him, but over the weekend he also said he
received a loan of $381,700 from Recruit in 1987 and was
embarrassed at having to change his story.
   ALSO LINKED: Former Prime Minister Yasuhiro Nakasone, under
whose administration the share transactions took place. His aides
reportedly received 29,000 shares and were estimated to have
profited to the tune of $460,000.
   RESIGNATIONS: Three members of Takeshita's Cabinet resigned
because of money links to Recruit. They were Finance Minister
Kiichi Miyazawa, Justice Minister Takashi Hasegawa and Ken Harada,
director general of the Economic Planning Agency.
   ARRESTS: Recruit's founder, Hiromasa Ezoe, faces multiple
charges of bribery along with several executives of the
conglomerate and its subsidiaries. Among others charged with
accepting bribes are Hisashi Shinto, former chairman of Nippon
Telegraph and Telephone Corp., Japan's giant telecommunications
utility; Kunio Takaishi, former vice minister of education; and
Takashi Kato, a former vice minister of labor.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
