<FIRST>r f PM-Limited-LernerWoman     04-25 0393</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Limited-Lerner Woman,0408</SECOND>
<HEAD>Clothing Retailer To Sell Larger-Sizes Discount Chain</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MEG REYNOLDS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Women's clothing retailer Limited Inc. is
selling its larger-sizes discount chain Lerner Woman, freeing up
the company to concentrate on its higher priced specialty apparel
outlets.
   Lerner Woman, created in 1986 as an offshoot of Lane Bryant,
will be sold for an undisclosed price to a management group led by
the division's president, company spokesman Alfred Dietzel said
Monday.
   Dietzel said the selling price, in cash and securities, was
expected to approximate the book value of Lerner Woman's assets.
   The deal is expected to be completed in June, the company said.
   Lerner Woman, which merged with discount chain Sizes Unlimited
in 1987, operates under the store names Lerner Woman, Sizes
Unlimited, Smart Sizes and Sizes Woman.
   Aimed mostly at discount shoppers seeking larger sizes, the
382-store chain had sales of $223.7 million in 1988.
   Donald Trott, a retail analyst for Dean Witter in New York, said
Monday the deal meant Limited would continue to provide the
Rochelle, N.J.-based Lerner Woman with computer and distribution
services and management information, for a fee.
   ``They don't lose any earnings, and yet through the sale of this
they free up some of their assets,'' Trott said. ``It's a fair deal
all the way around.''
   Columbus-based Limited, with $4 billion in sales last year,
operates more than 3,400 apparel stores nationwide, including The
Limited and Limited Express, Ambercrombie &amp; Fitch, Victoria's
Secret and Henri Bendel.
   Most of the stores _ with the exception of Lerner Woman _ are
full-price outlets that tend to be located in regional shopping
malls, while Lerner Woman stores generally are located in smaller
shopping strips.
   ``Lerner Woman just had never worked,'' said retail analyst Fred
Wintzer of Alex. Brown &amp; Sons Inc. in Baltimore. ``They've got to
find a niche, a customer that isn't being serviced by other chains.
   ``The top management at The Limited just didn't have the time to
concentrate on that division,'' Wintzer said.
   Limited acquired the Sizes Unlimited chain in 1982 and Lane
Bryant in 1986, said a woman at Limited headquarters who declined
to give her name.
   Equity of the new corporation initially will be shared equally
by Lerner Woman's management, led by president Raphael Benaroya,
The Limited and Centre Capital, the company said in a statement.
</TEXT>
