<FIRST>r f PM-SearsRelocation     04-25 0441</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Sears Relocation,0454</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dallas On `Short List' For Sears Relocation, Sources Say</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sears, Roebuck and Co., the nation's largest
retailer, has narrowed possible relocation sites of its
merchandising group to three or four cities, including Dallas,
sources say.
   The sources said Monday that the Chicago-based retailer now has
a ``short list'' of possible sites, but said Charlotte, N.C., has
emerged as the leading contender. It could not be immediately
determined what other cities were still under consideration, the
Dallas Times Herald reported today.
   Sources told the newspaper that Sears officials are expected to
visit Dallas within the next two weeks to look at the area and meet
with economic development officials.
   ``All of us are operating on feelings, but we believe that we
are definitely on the list,'' said Scott Eubanks, who heads Dallas
Partnership, an economic development agency. ``The big unknown is
Illinois, and I don't want to sell them short.''
   Chicago-area officials have been working to keep Sears in the
city where it grew up since the company announced in October it
wanted to build a campus-style headquarters complex for its
merchandising group. That division now has headquarters in the
110-story Sears Tower in downtown Chicago. At the time, the company
said it would look at other cities but preferred to stay in the
area.
   Though Sears is selling the 15-year-old tower, the company has
said its corporate headquarters will remain there after the
merchandise group is gone. Even so, the move would involve 6,700 of
the group's 8,000 employees.
   Eubanks said he expects the company to make a decision within
the next few weeks. ``I think it's real close,'' he said.
   A Sears spokeswoman said the company has not set a deadline for
its decision and that she could not comment on the relocation.
   Other cities under consideration, sources say, include Denver,
Kansas City, Mo., Atlanta; and Pittsburgh.
   Economic development officials in North Carolina would not
comment Monday on Sears. ``I've got nothing to say,'' said Alvah
Ward, director of business and industry development for the state's
Department of Commerce.
   Dallas has attracted GTE Corp. of Stamford, Conn., to relocate
its consolidated Telephone Operation to Las Colinas in suburban
Irving and J.C. Penney, the nation's fourth-largest retailer, to
move from New York City to suburban Plano.
   The GTE relocation means 1,000 new jobs in the area and the
Penney is bringing another 3,000 jobs.
   Sears' merchandise group, which oversees the retailer's stores
and catalog operations, accounts for more than half of the
company's size. Sears also owns Allstate Insurance, Dean Witter
Financial Services and Coldwell Banker Real Estate, none of which
is being relocated.
</TEXT>
