<FIRST>r f PM-SalesOutlook 2ndLd-Writethru f0059 04-25 0605</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Sales Outlook, 2nd Ld-Writethru, f0059,0620</SECOND>
<HEAD>Are Incentives Working Or A Dud? Today's Figures Should Tell</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 15th graf pvs, `Meantime, Ward's ...' with 4 grafs to UPDATE
with GM second-quarter production cuts.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Today brings another critical test for the auto
industry _ the first full sales period of the latest round of
incentives _ and carmakers are looking for the consumer response
that so far has eluded them.
   ``I'm holding my breath a little on this one,'' auto analyst
Douglas Laughlin of Bear, Stearns &amp; Co. of New York said Monday.
   Sales during March were lower than expected, prompting General
Motors Corp., Ford Motor Co. and Chrysler Corp. to institute new,
expensive incentive programs. Partially because of those
enticements, car and light truck sales during early April were 28.3
percent higher than the same period last year.
   But sales during the first 10 days of April last year were among
the lowest of the year, distorting comparisons with this year's
performance.
   Sales rebounded in mid-April 1988, meaning today's year-to-year
comparisons will give a better snapshot of how sales are faring
compared to the same time in the second-best sales year in industry
history.
   Automakers had counted on strong March and April sales to shrink
inventories and put off the need for large-scale production
cutbacks.
   ``I guess you'd say they (incentives) are working but not as
well as they used to,'' analyst David Healy of Drexel Burnham
Lambert Inc. said Monday. ``If that's so, mid-April sales were
better than the March rate but not as good as early April.''
   Laughlin said he was watching interest rates particularly
closely.
   ``If interest rates start to trend down, I think that would
alleviate some of the concern (among automakers) about the impact
of this particular (incentive) program, '' he said. ``It would
suggest that things will be easier in the next few months.
   ``If interest rates hang up here, it may be a source of concern
for the industry.''
   One of the first places any industry concern would be noted is
in the companies' production schedules. GM, Ford and Chrysler held
to ambitious production levels through the first quarter of this
year, leading some analysts to speculate that production rates
would have to be changed later this year, especially at
model-changeover time in the third quarter.
   Today, Ford analyst Ray Windecker said the nation's No. 2
automaker was cutting about 2 percent from its second-quarter
production schedule as part of ``fine tuning.''
   ``Our market share continues to move up, but we will cheerfully
admit the industry is a little softer than we thought it would
be,'' he said. The cuts, Windecker added, would come in overtime
Ford has been running at all but one of its 18 U.S. and Canadian
assembly plants. The company's Oakville, Ontario, plant, which
makes the Ford Tempo and Mercury Topaz, is operating on straight
time.
   Windecker said third-quarter production schedules are due out
later.
   Meantime, Ward's Automotive Reports, a weekly industry
newsletter, said in Monday editions that GM had cut its production
schedule by 60,000 cars for the third quarter of 1989.
   GM spokesman Tom Pyden refused to comment on the report, saying
final production figures for the July-September period aren't set.
However, he confirmed the nation's largest carmaker had cut its
second-quarter production schedule by about 3 percent.
   ``The vast majority of it is elimination of some of our planned
overtime,'' he said. ``This does not change our yearlong sales
forecast for 1989. We will approach 15 million units.''
   Chrysler's original production schedule for mid-1989 was scaled
back from first-quarter levels.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890425-0265 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-25-89 1123EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-Bush     04-25 0942</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bush,0973</SECOND>
<HEAD>For release at 12:30 p.m. EDT _ set by source</HEAD>
<HEAD>Bush Renews Plea for Cut in Capital Gains Tax</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PALO ALTO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush said today that critics
``couldn't be more wrong'' when they call his proposed cut in
capital gains taxes ``a tax break for the rich.''
   Rather, he said, that proposal and other new investment
incentives are needed to help America compete in the global economy.
   Bush took note of the criticism of his proposal in Congress and
elsewhere in a speech prepared for managers and employees at Ford
Aerospace's Space Systems Division here.
   ``Well, they couldn't be more wrong,'' he said. ``Lower capital
gains taxes will create jobs for those who don't have jobs, and
help build a better America.''
   Capital gains taxes are levied on the profits that businesses
and individuals make on investments. The president wants to cut the
33 percent maximum tax on capital gains to 15 percent and to exempt
entirely the gains accrued by people with incomes under $10,000 a
year.
   When fully effective in 1995, the tax break for capital gains
would apply to assets held for 36 months or longer.
   Senate Majority Leader George Mitchell, D-Maine, and other top
congressional Democrats have criticized Bush for pushing the
capital-gains reduction, which they term ``a tax break for the
rich,'' while opposing legislation to increase the minimum wage to
$4.55 an hour from the current $3.35.
   In his Palo Alto speech, Bush also put in a fresh plug for his
proposed tax credit aimed at making child care more affordable for
the poor.
   This came a day after it was disclosed that he had come out
against a reduction in the surtax paid by older Americans for
Medicare coverage of catastrophic illiness.
   The president noted that demographic changes in the American
labor force indicate that the majority of new job-seekers in the
years ahead will be females, minorities and immigrants.
   To keep abreast of the rapidly changing technologies and the
change in the labor markets, he said, businesses must have
incentives to make the kinds of investments that will create new
jobs _ and he suggested that many of these new jobs will come in
the high-technology area.
   ``Lower capital gains taxes will create jobs for those who don't
have jobs, and help build a better America,'' he said. ``So let us
act to lift revenue, help savings, and free American businesses,
without distorting world markets.''
   ``My friends, I want to give the high five to high-tech. And I
want to do it by investing in competitiveness,'' he said.
   The president was coupling his Northern California economic
speech today with a pep talk downstate to officers at a
narcotics-enforcement training institute in Rancho del Rio.
   The disparate themes of the four-day Bush trip, which will
conclude Thursday in Florida, seemed aimed at projecting an active
president in the final seven days of the first 100 _ a milestone
that has been used to report first impressions of the president's
stewardship of national affairs.
   Bush has sought to minimize the importance of the 100-day marker
for presidential performance. But during a speech Monday to the
annual luncheon of Associated Press newspaper publishers in
Chicago, he went ahead anyway.
   ``We've made a good start these first three months,'' Bush said.
``So while I'm pleased with all we've accomplished in these three
months, there's a long road ahead of us.''
   Meanwhile, in a letter made public Monday, the president came
out against any quick moves to reduce the surtax for Medicare
coverage of catastrophic illness.
   In the letter, released by Rep. Dan Rostenkowski, D-Ill., Bush
said it would be ``imprudent to tinker'' with the program even in
light of a congressionally projected surplus in its reserves.
   Sen. Lloyd Bentsen, D-Texas, chairman of the Senate Finance
Committee, last week raised the possibility of a reduction of up to
16 percent in the surtax.
   Bush, however, said in the letter that financial reserves for
the program ``are not excessive'' and may actually be ``too thin.''
He said the surplus projections are based on uncertainties in a
program that is only a few months old.
   The president set aside the Ford Aerospace plant speech today to
laud the more than 75-month recovery from the 1981-82 recession and
the nation's 5 percent unemployment rate, which is at the lowest
level in 15 years. But Bush also wanted to warn anew of an America
that is declining competitively in the global economy.
   The merchandise trade deficit fell from $152.1 billion in 1987
to $118.7 billion last year _ a 22 percent reduction which
represented the first annual improvement since 1980.
   But the deficit has been on an upward trend more recently, with
the red-ink figure at $10.5 billion in February, which was more
than 20 percent above the January figure.
   ``We had a tremendous improvement in the trade figure last year,
but we're now seeing a pause,'' said Michael Boskin, chairman of
the president's Council of Economic Advisers. ``When you go through
a very substantial growth in exports, as we did last year, you
often see such a pause and an adjustment.''
   Speaking to reporters en route here on Air Force One, Boskin
said that many businesses and industries are still trying to build
up to capacity production.
   Bush will travel to Los Angeles on Wednesday to be reunited with
the president he served as vice president for eight years, Ronald
Reagan.
   Later in the week, the president will address the Texas
Legislature in Austin and make drug-related appearances in Miami
and Clearwater, Fla., before returning to Washington late Thursday.
</TEXT>
