<FIRST>u f PM-UMW-Pittston 2ndLd-Writethru   04-25 0681</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-UMW-Pittston, 2nd Ld-Writethru,0702</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hundreds Arrested, Setting Off Rally That Shuts Down Town</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 3 grafs, picking up 3rd graf pvs, and SUBS 9th graf,
``UMW District 28,'' with 5 grafs to recast and UPDATE with high school
students rallying in support of miners.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK PAXTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CLINTWOOD, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   High school students walked out of class
and rallied today in support of miners on strike against Pittston
Coal Group, a day after the walkout turned nasty with the arrests
of at least 200 miners.
   Seven striking members of the United Mine Workers said they were
injured in Monday's arrests. Many strikers accused Virginia state
troopers of being unnecessarily rough.
   Most of the town's businesses closed for Monday's daylong rally
in support of the strike, now in its 20th day.
   ``It's not criminal to stand up for what you believe in,'' Marty
Hudson, executive assistant to the union vice president, told about
300 people at the rally in this western Virginia town of about
1,400 people. ``There's going to be a lot more people in jail
because it ain't over.''
   State Police Sgt. B.I. Sparks said about 200 miners and their
supporters were arrested and charged with obstructing a free
passage, Route 773, and were being released on their recognizance.
   Union members estimated the number arrested at closer to 300. An
exact count was not immediately available because the numbers
overwhelmed local officials, forcing them to turn a courtroom into
an impromptu holding cell.
   ``There's not enough cells to hold us,'' Hudson said.
   The 1,400 Pittston employees in Virginia and 300 in West
Virginia went on strike April 5, accusing the company of unfair
practices during contract talks. The miners had been working
without a contract since February 1988.
   About 200 union members gathered today at the McClure mine but
did not block the road or mine entrances. No one was arrested.
   However, ``I think all of them here were prepared to go to jail
if necessary,'' UMW District 28 President Jackie Stump said today.
   Also, about 150 Clintwood High School students walked out of
class today and rallied at the Dickenson County Courthouse in
support of the miners, officials said.
   ``They're sort of walking around in the street in front of the
courthouse,'' waving signs and chanting, said deputy county clerk
Lula Large. She said a single police officer watched the students
for a while, then left.
   ``The principal came down and talked to the children and asked
them to go back to class,'' but the students refused, Large said.
   A secretary at Clintwood High said she was instructed to tell
callers that school officials had no comment.
   Monday's arrests capped a day of civil disobedience by the
union, which used more than 1,000 members to block entrances to
Pittston's Moss No. 3 preparation plant and 200 others to block the
Lambert Fork mine, both in Russell County, in addition to the
McClure mine.
   Also Monday, the union expanded its strike against Pittston to
temporarily include Westmoreland Coal Co., which it accused of
plotting to provide Pittston with 200,000 to 300,000 tons of coal
to fulfill contracts. Westmoreland has denied that charge.
   The Pittston employees on strike in Virginia were joined on the
picket lines by about 750 Westmoreland employees who are taking off
three of the 10 ``memorial days'' _ or personal days _ allowed by
their contract.
   State police treatment of those arrested infuriated some union
members and supporters, some of whom displayed signs that said
``Welcome To Poland'' and ``Cut State Police Pay and Benefits.''
   Sparks said he was aware of some reports of injuries. ``They
were just complaints of injuries,'' he said. ``We don't know
whether there were actually injuries.''
   Six miners who said they received cuts and bruises while being
arrested were treated and released at Dickenson County Medical
Center in Clintwood. A seventh was admitted with reports of blurred
vision, and was held for observation.
   Pittston Coal Group President Michael Odom and company
spokeswoman Susan Copeland did not return phone calls from The
Associated Press on Monday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
