<HEAD>Crop Futures Open Lower On Forecasts For More Rain</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures prices were mostly
lower this morning on the Chicago Board of Trade on forecasts for
more rain in key crop-growing areas during the next week to 10 days.
   ``There's more agreement right now than there's been,'' said
John Frazier, a grain-market analyst in Chicago with Balfour
Maclaine Corp., referring to the wide disparity in forecasts last
week.
   The National Weather Service predicted normal temperatures and
normal rainfall for the Corn Belt in a six-to-10-day forecast
issued late Monday.
   Meteorologists also predicted increased precipitation in the
Great Plains, where the winter wheat crop has been severely damaged
by dry weather.
   Early declines in the wheat market are also linked to reports
that the Agriculture Department rejected Egypt's bid for 300,000
metric tons of U.S. wheat.
   In early trading, wheat was 1\ cents lower to \ cent higher with
the contract for delivery in May at $4.14{ per bushel; corn was 1\
cents to 3 cents lower with May at $2.67\ per bushel; oats were 1\
cents to 2{ cents lower with May at $1.94{ per bushel; soybeans
were 7{ cents lower to 1 cent higher with July at $7.45 per bushel.
   Cattle futures were lower, while pork futures were mixed during
early trading at the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .25 cent to .62 cent lower with June at 70.15
cents per pound; feeder cattle were .05 cent to .55 cent lower with
May at 75.65 cents per pound; live hogs were .13 cent lower to .35
cent higher with June at 45.95 cents per pound; frozen pork bellies
were .30 cent lower to .35 cent higher with May at 31.65 cents per
pound.
   Livestock and meat futures settled mixed on Monday.
</TEXT>
