<FIRST>r f PM-RanksHovis-GoodmanFielder     04-25 0492</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Ranks Hovis-Goodman Fielder,0510</SECOND>
<HEAD>Britain's Ranks Hovis Launches Bid For Australian Food Firm</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ranks Hovis McDougall PLC has made a takeover bid
of about 1.4 billion pounds for Goodman Fielder Wattie Ltd., the
Australian food concern that failed in its hostile attempt to
acquire Ranks Hovis last year.
   Turning the tables on the Sydney-based company, the British food
group emphasized Monday its bid did not stem from last year's
takeover battle or from fears it might be revived.
   Ranks Hovis characterized its proposal, which values the
Australian company at the equivalent of about $2.4 billion, as part
of its own plan to expand internationally. Goodman Fielder is the
largest food company in Australia and New Zealand.
   Goodman Fielder said it wasn't informed of the takeover bid in
advance and advised shareholders to keep their shares while its
directors examine Ranks Hovis' proposal.
   There was mixed speculation on what Goodman Fielder would do.
Several analysts said they consider Ranks Hovis' offer fair and one
analyst speculated that Goodman Fielder would welcome it.
   Goodman Fielder's corporate affairs director, Greg Russell, said
``Clearly there are synergies between the two companies.''
   This same point was made last year by the Australian company
when it was pursuing Ranks Hovis.
   John Elston, an analyst with James Capel &amp; Co., said Goodman
Fielder could block the British bid if it chose to because a large
portion of its shareholders are loyal to current management.
   ``In practical terms, you either have an agreed deal or you
don't have a deal at all,'' Elston said.
   Goodman Fielder's attempted takeover of Ranks Hovis last year
was thwarted by Britain's Monopolies and Mergers Commission because
of its dependence on debt and on possible anti-competitive grounds.
   The attempt left Goodman Fielder with 29.9 percent of Ranks
Hovis' shares. A Goodman Fielder official said the company has held
discussions with several interested parties about selling the stake
but the talks are on hold while Goodman Fielder considers the Ranks
Hovis proposal.
   Ranks Hovis said its bid is contingent upon acquiring more than
50 percent of Goodman Fielder's common stock. The British company
also said its offer carries a condition that Goodman Fielder not
enter into any new financial obligations exceeding a certain
monetary threshold.
   The transaction would have to be endorsed by Ranks Hovis
shareholders and would be subject to review by government
regulators. Ranks Hovis said it did not anticipate any problems
with Australian authorities.
   Besides Britain, Ranks Hovis has interests in Australia, New
Zealand, Asia, Europe and the United States. It makes bread, flour,
cakes and a wide range of other food products.
   Goodman Fielder holds about 35 percent of the Australian
flour-milling market and has a 50 percent share of that market in
New Zealand. It controls 60 percent of the Australian margirine and
cooking oil market is the third largest gelatin maker in the world.
It also owns Meneba NV, a Dutch flour, bakery and poultry company.
</TEXT>
