<HEAD>Goldome Reports $38.8 Million Loss</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUFFALO, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Goldome bank, one of the nation's leading
thrifts, reported a loss of $38.8 million, or $1.41 per share, for
its first quarter ending March 31, company officials said today.
   Goldome lost $12 million or 45 cents per share during the same
period last year.
   Chief Executive Officer Ross Kenzie told shareholders at the
company's annual meeting in Buffalo that the loss _ which follows a
loss of $119 million in 1988 _ was due to continued high interest
rates and a decrease in income from non-banking subsidiaries.
   Kenzie, who is retiring this summer, said the company would
continue restructuring efforts under the leadership of Thomas
Cooper, the former head of the Bank of America who was recently
named his successor.
   ``I have no doubt this company will triumph in the 1990s,''
Kenzie said before turning the meeting over to Cooper.
   Goldome, with assets of $14.5 billion, has operations in two
dozen states.
</TEXT>
