<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-QuakerOats     04-25 0209</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Quaker Oats,0217</SECOND>
<HEAD>Quaker Oats' Quarterly Profit Down 9 Percent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Quaker Oats Co. today reported a 9.2 percent drop
in its third-quarter earnings, citing an extraordinary expense of
$20.7 million stemming from the consolidation of its European
food-manufacturing operations.
   Quaker reported net income of $68.1 million, or 85 cents a
share, for the three months ending March 31, compared with $75
million, or 94 cents a share, for the same period in 1988.
   Revenues for the quarter totaled $1.38 billion, a 3 percent gain
from last year's sales of $1.34 billion, the Chicago-based company
said in a news release.
   Excluding the one-time charge of $20.7 million, operating income
would have been $158.4 million, 5 percent above a year ago, the
company said.
   Chairman William D. Smithburg said the results reflected a
continued strong performance by Gatorade thirst quencher and
Quaker's domestic cereal business, which more than offset lower
results from the company's Pet Foods and Fisher-Price toys
subsidiaries.
   For the first nine months of fiscal 1989, Quaker reported $158.2
million, or $1.99 per share, compared with $161.6 million, or $2.02
per share, for the first nine months of fiscal 1988.
   Revenues for the first nine months totaled $4.16 billion,
compared with $3.84 billion in 1988.
</TEXT>
