<FILEID>AP-NR-04-25-89 1512EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-Zenith     04-25 0300</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Zenith,0312</SECOND>
<HEAD>Zenith Posts $4 Million Loss for Quarter, But Expects Profitable
Year</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GLENVIEW, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Zenith Electronics Corp. on Tuesday
reported a $4 million loss in the first quarter due in part to
higher supply costs, but the maker of televisions and computers
said it still expects to turn a profit this year.
   The net loss of $4 million, a deficit of 15 cents a share, for
the three months ending April 1 compares with net income of
$400,000, or 1 cent a share, for the same period in 1988.
   First-quarter sales totaled $674.5 million, a 17 percent gain
from $574.1 million in the first quarter of 1988, Zenith said in a
news release from its headquarters in this north Chicago suburb.
   ``Our first-quarter loss was anticipated in our 1989 plan; we
still expect profit improvement for the full year,'' said Zenith
Chairman Jerry Pearlman.
   Zenith, the only major U.S.-based television manufacturer,
recorded its first annual profit in four years in 1988, mainly as a
result of booming computer sales.
   Sales of Zenith computer systems and components rose 15 percent
in the first quarter, to $402 million, but the group's operating
income declined due to higher prices for memory chips, lower sales
of power supplies and a $3 million loss in foreign exchange.
   Memory-chip costs are expected to drop significantly and sales
of power supplies are expected to double in the second quarter,
Zenith said.
   Sales of Zenith picture tubes, televisions and video-cassette
recorders rose 21 percent, to $272 million, in the first quarter.
   The consumer electronics group's operating income also improved,
Zenith said, although television price tags industrywide were below
year-ago levels.
   Zenith said it put through modest price increases for its
consumer electronics products early in the first quarter, and those
increases have been holding.
</TEXT>
