<SECOND>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0251</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soybeans Plunge Again On Wetter Weather</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soybean futures prices fell sharply for the
second consecutive session Tuesday on the Chicago Board of Trade as
scattered rainfall in the Midwest cooled drought fears.
   Wheat futures finished nearly unchanged.
   Overnight rain in the western Corn Belt and forecasts for more
rain over the next few days prompted moderate to heavy selling of
soybean, corn and oat futures contracts from the opening bell.
   The National Weather Service issued a six-to-10-day forecast
late Monday that predicted normal temperatures and normal rainfall
in the region early next week.
   ``It's a weather market,'' said John Frazier, a grain-market
analyst in Chicago with Balfour Maclaine Corp.
   The Agriculture Department reported that corn planting got under
way in most major producing areas last week. Soybean planting will
begin in early May.
   But the USDA also said the Kansas winter wheat crop was in
mostly very poor to poor condition last week due to a lack of
moisture. That report helped support the wheat market.
   At the close, wheat was } cent lower to } cent higher with the
contract for delivery in May at $4.15 a bushel; corn was 2{ cents
to 4\ cents lower with May at $2.64} a bushel; oats were 5{ cents
to 7\ cents lower with May at $1.89 a bushel; soybeans were 8{
cents to 10{ cents lower with May at $7.36 a bushel.
</TEXT>
