<FIRST>u f AM-BoeingOrder     04-25 0351</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Boeing Order,0364</SECOND>
<HEAD>USAir Orders Boeing Jets With Potential Value Of $1.7 Billion</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   USAir Inc. has ordered 18 Boeing 737 jetliners
and taken options on 36 more in a deal with a potential value of
about $1.7 billion, Boeing Commercial Airplanes Co. said Tuesday.
   The announcement was the latest indication that the aerospace
giant is continuing on a roll of large aircraft orders. It came
just one day after Boeing's annual shareholders meeting, at which
the plane manufacturer announced increased dividends and a stock
split, and predicted record-breaking sales this year.
   Boeing considers a plane sold when it is delivered to the buyer.
   The USAir order includes flexibility for the airline to decide
later whether it wants jets in the 737-300, -400 or -500 series.
The -500 is the smallest, with capacity of 100 to 132 passengers,
and the -400 is the largest, able to carry 145 to 170 passengers.
   Deliveries of the 18 firm orders will be one a month during 1991
and two monthly during the first quarter of 1992, with options
possibly exercised in 1994 and 1995.
   The latest transaction brings USAir's current Boeing 737 orders
to 68 aircraft, which will be delivered between now and 1992, plus
96 options, which would be delivered between 1992 and 1995, USAir
said.
   Washington-based USAir currently operates a fleet of 56
737-300s, the most of any airline.
   Piedmont Aviation, a USAir subsidiary, operates 39 737-300s and
14 737-400s and has six additional 737-400s on order. Piedmont will
be merged with USAir on Aug 5.
   With the USAir order, Boeing has received orders this year for
319 jetliners valued at about $19.7 billion. Of those, 120 orders
are for 737s.
   In all of last year, Boeing had orders for 636 planes, valued at
$29.7 billion.
   Total 737 orders stand at 2,384, making it the most popular
commercial jet of all time.
   USAir also has ordered 20 Fokker 100 jets and holds options on
20 more. First delivery is scheduled for June. In addition, USAir
recently decided to buy as many as 40 MD-82 aircraft from McDonnell
Douglas Corp.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
