<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-Cray     04-25 0375</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Cray,0387</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cray Posts Large Earnings Decline for First Quarter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cray Research Inc., the world's biggest
supercomputer maker, on Tuesday reported a 94 percent decline in
first-quarter earnings and said second-quarter earnings also could
be down significantly.
   The company reported first-quarter net earnings of $1.5 million,
or 5 cents a share, down from first-quarter earnings of $26.4
million, or 85 cents a share, for the same period in 1988.
First-quarter revenue was $116.1 million, compared with $145.9
million for the 1988 quarter.
   ``We entered the year expecting the delivery of computer systems
to be much higher in the second half of the year than the first,''
said Marcelo A. Gumucio, president and chief operating officer.
``The revenue results for the first quarter are consistent with
that outlook.
   ``Current delivery schedules indicate that more systems have
shifted to the last half of the year and we now expect revenue for
the second quarter to be similar to last year's second quarter,''
Gumucio said.
   But he added, ``We have not changed our objective of achieving a
10 percent revenue increase for the full year.''
   Gumucio said all operating areas are exercising strong expense
control in line with the company's revenue objective for the full
year ``while we continue to invest fully in new product development
projects to meet long-term objectives. Expenses will be spread more
evenly through the year than revenues.
   ``This affected earnings in the first quarter and earnings in
the second quarter could be down significantly from the same period
a year ago for the same reason,'' he said. ``Earnings for the full
year will depend primarily on our ability to meet the aggressive
delivery schedules for the third and fourth quarters.''
   During the first quarter, 13 systems were installed at customer
sites, including seven new systems and six used systems. Three of
the new systems were leased, as were four of the used systems, Cray
said.
   Cray posted a 6 percent increase in net earnings in 1988. It
reported $756.3 million in revenues and $156.6 million in net
profit for that year.
   Cray, based in Minneapolis, employs more than 5,200 people and
has manufacturing and development facilities in Chippewa Falls and
Rice Lake in Wisconsin and in Colorado Springs, Colo.
</TEXT>
