<FIRST>r f AM-CollectiveBargaining     04-25 0457</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Collective Bargaining,0472</SECOND>
<HEAD>Wage Gains in Collective Bargaining Agreements Rise</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Economy Bjt. Also moved on general news wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Contracts settled through collective
bargaining in the first three months of 1989 gave workers average
annual wage increases of 3.1 percent over the life of the pacts,
the government reported Tuesday.
   The wage gains were up from the 2.2 percent average raises
provided during the life of contracts settled in the fourth quarter
of 1988 and also ahead of the 2.4 percent average wage gains
contained in collective bargaining agreements settled in all of
last year.
   Analysts said the new gains were in line with other Labor
Department data showing wage inflation growing because of tight
labor markets.
   The quarterly report on collective bargaining, like the Labor
Department's broader Employment Cost Index report, showed workers
in the fast-growing service sector winning larger wage gains than
manufacturing workers.
   ``That's where the tighter labor markets are,'' chief economist
Allen Sinai of Boston Co. Economic Advisers Inc. said of
service-providing parts of the economy.
   The Labor Department said the 64 first-quarter collective
bargaining agreements it analyzed covered 199,000 workers. The
average length of the contracts was just under three years, with
only seven being for less than two years.
   First-year pay gains averaged 3.2 percent with average wage
increases of 3.1 percent in the second and third years of the
contracts, the department said.
   The government, which tracks agreements covering bargaining
units with at least 1,000 members, said 107 such contracts
affecting 636,000 workers had expired or been reopened in the first
quarter but had not been settled or ratified by April 1.
   Of that group, about 350,000 employees worked for railroads and
104,000 for airlines, with the remaining number dispersed
throughout a variety of industries.
   The first-quarter report showed that workers who received
lump-sum payments from their employers or had cost-of-living
adjustment clauses in their contracts on average received smaller
wage increases than workers who received neither of those forms of
compensation.
   About 30,000 workers got lump-sum payments as part of contracts
negotiated in the first quarter and their pay raises averaged 1.8
percent a year over the lives of the new contracts.
   Contracts affecting 21,000 workers contained COLA clauses,
generally tied to the government's inflation index, and the annual
wage gains in those agreements averaged 2.4 percent, the government
said.
   More than 75 percent of the workers whose contracts were settled
in the first quarter worked in the non-manufacturing sector of the
economy, and their annual pay gains averaged 3.3 percent over the
lives of the contracts.
   In the manufacturing sector, where lump-sum payments and COLA
clauses are prevalent, wage increases averaged 2.3 percent annually
over the contract lives.
</TEXT>
