<FIRST>u f AM-Bush-Competitiveness     04-25 0591</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Competitiveness,0611</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush: High Five To High Tech</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Bush, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVE WILSTEIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PALO ALTO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush quoted several sports
figures _ Tommy Lasorda, Satchel Paige and Woody Hayes _ and gave a
``high five to high tech'' during a pep talk on competitiveness
Tuesday in Silicon Valley.
   Critics complained, however, that he didn't say enough about
unfair trade by foreign competitors in his speech before business
leaders and workers at Ford Aerospace's Space Systems Division.
   After Bush received boos for his reference to Lasorda, the Los
Angeles Dodgers manager who is an enemy to San Francisco Giants
fans, the president won applause for advocating a cut in the
capital gains tax and a boost in spending for NASA and other
science and technology.
   He praised Ford Aerospace, which recently delivered the first of
two communications Superbird satellites to Japan in a $209 million
contract, as a good example of America's ability to compete
internationally.
   ``Today, American satellites are among the most competitive
spacecraft for customers who want affordable, high-powered
communications satellites,'' Bush said.
   He quoted former pitcher Satchel Paige _ ``Don't look back.
Somebody might be gaining on you.'' _ and said America must invest
in the future by developing new programs to accommodate a changing
workforce.
   As an example, Bush cited Ford's Employee Assistance Program,
which helps workers find child-care help.
   Though Bush offered no new strategies for increasing U.S.
productivity or improving America's ability to compete abroad, his
appearance in the nation's high-technology capital early in his
term showed an eagerness to stimulate business.
   ``I think it fires up the people to want to be competitive, to
realize they're making progress, and to want to be in the forefront
of America's success for exports and products for our own use,''
said Robert E. Berry, vice president and general manager of Ford's
Space Systems Division.
   Chris Hoeber, director of Ford's commercial space programs
operations, led Bush on a tour of the facility's space
environmental chamber, which duplicates temperatures in space, and
showed him the next Superbird satellite.
   ``This is a case study to show American businessmen what is
possible if they're willing to take the time and make the
investment in Japan and other countries,'' said Hoeber. ``There's
no reason why Americans can't be as competitive as anyone else.''
   Larry Stone, mayor of Sunnyvale in the heart of Silicon Valley,
criticized Bush for saying very little about fair, free trade and
the restrictive policies of other countries.
   But Stone commended Bush for returning to an area that he lost
``fairly handily'' in the November election.
   ``He came back within the first 100 days and gave a message that
I think will be widely accepted by the corporations here _ the
capital gains tax and the extension on research and development tax
credits.''
   Rep. Tom Campbell, the first-term Republican congressman and
Stanford Business School professor who represents much of Silicon
Valley, accompanied Bush on his first domestic speaking tour since
entering office.
   ``The R&amp;D tax credit is so important and the capital gains tax
is critical,'' Campbell said. ``He's hitting it in every speech.''
   Campbell said he talked with Bush aboard Air Force One about
other ways to boost competitiveness, including improving access to
foreign markets, ending excessive litigation and guarding against
transferring technology to other countries that could hurt U.S.
business.
   ``We talked explicitly about access to foreign markets in
connection with the semiconductor agreement to sell to Japan,''
Campbell said. Bush did not mention the semiconductor problem in
his speech.
</TEXT>
