<FIRST>u f AM-CommoditiesRdp     04-25 0675</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Commodities Rdp,0700</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soybeans Plunge Again On Wetter Weather</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Soybean futures prices fell sharply Tuesday for the second
consecutive session on the Chicago Board of Trade as scattered
rainfall in the Midwest continued to cool drought fears. Wheat
futures finished nearly unchanged.
   On other markets, petroleum futures prices surged; hog futures
advanced strongly while other livestock and meat markets were
mixed; and precious metals prices declined.
   Wheat settled 1\ cents lower to 1} cents higher with the
contract for delivery in May at $4.14{ a bushel; corn was 3 cents
to 5 cents lower with May at $2.64 a bushel; oats were 5{ cents to
7\ cents lower with May at $1.89 a bushel; soybeans were 10 cents
to 15 cents lower with May at $7.32{ a bushel.
   Overnight rain in the western Corn Belt and forecasts for more
rain over the next few days prompted moderate to heavy selling of
soybean, corn and oat futures contracts right from the opening bell.
   ``It's a weather market,'' said John Frazier, a grain-market
analyst in Chicago with Balfour Maclaine Corp.
   The various private forecasters used by futures traders were in
closer agreement about the weather outlook than they had been in
the past two weeks, Frazier said.
   The National Weather Service issued a six-to-10-day forecast
late Monday that predicted normal temperatures and normal rainfall
in the Midwest early next week.
   The Agriculture Department reported that corn planting got under
way in most major producing areas last week. Soybean planting will
begin in early May.
   But the USDA also said most of the Kansas winter wheat crop was
in poor to very poor condition last week due to a lack of moisture.
That report helped support the wheat market.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, gasoline prices jumped
nearly 4 cents a gallon, fueled by rumors of problems on the Alaska
pipeline and concerns about refiners' ability to provide
cleaner-burning gasoline to states mandating a switch to a tougher
anti-pollution standard.
   ``It was a wild and crazy day in that respect,'' said Peter
Beutel, a New York analyst for Elders Futures Inc. ``I can't
remember the last time there was a near 4-cent increase in gasoline
prices, if ever.''
   Beutel said the rally also was helped along by word that an oil
platform damaged last week in the North Sea will be out of action
into early May.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 5 cents lower to 80
cents higher with June at $21.41 a barrel; heating oil was .05 cent
lower to .27 cent higher, with May at 52.08 cents a gallon;
unleaded gasoline was .40 cent to 3.93 cents higher, with May at
76.16 cents a gallon.
   Hog prices for June, July and August delivery leaped on the
Chicago Mercantile Exchange amid signs that hog slaughter levels
are falling.
   The rally extended Monday's slight gains in a market
strengthened by bullish chart patterns.
   ``It's all due to expectations we're going to be getting into
lighter kills in June, July and August,'' said Phil Stanley, an
independent livestock trader in Chicago.
   Cattle futures finished mixed after rebounding from a steep
slide that flushed many small speculators out of the market,
Stanley said.
   Live cattle settled .25 cent lower to .10 cent higher with June
at 70.52 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .45 cent lower to .12
cent higher with May at 76 cents a pound; live hogs were .03 cent
lower to 1 cent higher with June at 46.60 cents a pound; frozen
pork bellies were .60 cent lower to .35 cent higher with May at
31.57 cents a pound.
   Gold and silver futures retreated on New York's Commodity
Exchange, erasing much of the previous session's advance, in the
face of a stronger U.S. dollar and a smaller-than-expected increase
in March durable-goods orders, both signs that inflationary
pressures are easing.
   Gold settled $2 to $2.50 lower with June at $388.89 a troy
ounce; silver was 3.6 cents to 3.8 cents lower with May at $5.795 a
troy ounce.
</TEXT>
