<FIRST>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     04-25 0592</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dollar-Gold,0613</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Mostly Higher, Gold Mixed</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede LONDON BC</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar finished higher against most major
currencies Tuesday, recovering from an early selloff.
   Gold prices declined slightly in U.S. dealings after edging a
bit higher on foreign markets. Republic National Bank of New York
quoted a bid of $384.75 for a troy ounce of gold at 4 p.m. EDT, $2
lower than Monday's late bid.
   Zlatko Glamuzina, chief currency dealer at Banco di Sicilia,
said dealers sold dollars after the Commerce Department released a
report on ``big ticket'' durable goods orders.
   The reported said orders rose 0.8 percent in March. But,
excluding the increase in the volatile transportation category,
orders were off 2.8 percent and analysts interpreted the figure as
evidence of slower economic growth.
   A report from the National Association of Realtors said sales of
existing homes dropped for the third straight month in March to the
slowest pace in more than a year, an indication that rising
mortgage interest rates are discouraging home buyers.
   On the inflation front, the Labor Department said wages and
salaries paid American workers in private industry rose 4.2 percent
in the last 12 months, the biggest jump in 3{ years. The Employment
Cost Index reading was consistent with recent reports pointing to a
buildup in inflationary pressures in a tight job market.
   Glamuzina said the dollar slowly recovered amid mainly
institutional buying. Trading was fairly subdued, he said.
   The markets were quiet ahead of the first-quarter U.S. gross
national product report due on Wednesday, foreign exchange dealers
said.
   The announcement that Japan's Prime Minister Noboru Takeshita
will resign focused attention on the yen. The Japanese currency was
firmer as a result.
   The dollar closed at 131.17 yen, down from Monday's late 131.38.
In London late Tuesday, the dollar traded higher at 131.28 yen, and
at 131.475 yen in New York, down from 131.55 yen Monday.
   In London one British pound cost $1.7030 late Tuesday, cheaper
for buyers than Monday's late level of $1.7050. Sterling stood at
$1.69945 in New York compared to $1.70625 Monday.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with late Monday's
levels, included: 1.86655 West German marks, up from 1.86075;
1.64625 Swiss francs, up from 1.6420; 1.18925 Canadian dollars,
unchanged; 6.3175 French francs, up from 6.3070; and 1,367.20
Italian lire, up from 1,364.625.
   Other late rates for the dollar in Europe compared with Monday's
late rates included: 1.8625 West German marks, up from 1.8575;
1.6435 Swiss francs, up from 1.6395; 6.3065 French francs, up from
6.2975; 2.1000 Dutch guilders, up from 2.0960; and, 1.1910 Canadian
dollars, up from 1.1890.
   Italian markets were closed for a holiday. In London, the dollar
closed at 1,366.00 Italian lire, up from 1,362.50 in Italy on
Monday.
   Gold bullion prices rose by less than $1 an ounce on markets
abroad and then fell in U.S. trading.
   On the Commodity Exchange in New York, gold bullion for current
delivery fell to $385.70 a troy ounce from Monday's settlement of
$387.70.
   The late bid price for gold in London, the major European
precious metals market, was $385.75 a troy ounce, up from $384.90
late Monday. The late Zurich bid price was $385, up from $384.65.
   Earlier in Hong Kong gold closed at $385.65 bid, up from $384.05.
   Silver prices barely budged overseas and edged slighly lower in
the United States. On New York's Comex, silver bullion for current
delivery closed at $5.789 a troy ounce, down from $5.825 Monday.
Silver bullion traded late in London at $5.81 bid a troy ounce,
unchanged.
</TEXT>
