<FILEID>AP-NR-04-25-89 1749EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f BC-Earns-Steel 1stLd-Writethru   04-25 0688</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Steel, 1st Ld-Writethru,0710</SECOND>
<HEAD>USX Profits Rise; Bethlehem Profits Fall</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EARL BOHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   USX Corp.'s profits shot up 88 percent while Bethlehem Steel
Corp.'s profits fell 24 percent, the nation's biggest and
second-biggest steelmakers said Tuesday in first-quarter reports.
   Pittsburgh-based USX said its net income surged 88 percent to
$296 million, or $1.09 per share, led by a near three-fold increase
in operating income at Marathon Oil Co.
   Operating income from steel sagged 40 percent to $99 million on
sales of $1.5 billion.
   Income from continuing operations at Texas Oil &amp; Gas Corp.
shrank from $7 million to $3 million even though sales grew 42
percent from $276 million to $393 million.
   Texas Oil &amp; Gas eported operating income of $147 million, but
$144 million of that came from the settlement of lawsuits
concerning take-or-pay supply contracts, said company spokesman
William P. Ryder.
   Overall sales grew by 12.5 percent to $4.5 billion from $4.0
billion in the 1988 first quarter, when profits were $157 million,
or 52 cents per share.
   Marathon contributed operating income of $241 million on $2.4
billion in first-quarter sales compared with $84 million on $2.1
billion in sales a year earlier.
   ``Second-quarter operating results should be even stronger'' in
energy, USX Chairman David M. Roderick said in a printed statement.
   Marathon's improvement was the result of higher profit margins
on refined products, greater volume and higher prices for crude oil
and natural gas and lower exploration costs. The company spent $31
million exploring for oil and gas in the first quarter, down from
$50 million a year earlier.
   Operating income in steel declined from $167 million on sales of
$1.4 billion.
   ``The decline ... was due primarily to continued weakness in the
oil country tubular goods market and increased costs for raw
materials,'' Roderick said.
   Income from the diversified group of USX dropped from $98
million on $341 million in 1988 first-quarter sales to $30 million
on $252 million in sales, reflecting the sale of businesses in the
group and a $43 million on-time credit last year.
   USX received $83 million in extraordinary income in the first
quarter due primarily to the sale of assets, including the
phosphate fertilizer business of the Agri-Chemicals dividion and
the sale of 25 percent of Quebec Cartier Mining Co.
   The company boosted capital spending by $143 million to $372
million.
   ``Even after this relatively heavy capital spending ... the
corporation's cash balance continues over $2 billion,'' Roderick
said. ``This cash flow for the first quarter is on track with our
goal of generating more than $1 billion in 1989, permitting
continuation of our program to strengthen our balance sheet and
enhance shareholder value.''
   Bethlehem Steel said its 24 percent decline was the result of a
one-time charge.
   The Bethlehem, Pa.-based steelmaker said its net income fell to
$64.7 million, or 78 cents per share, from $85.4 million, or $1.23
per share, a year earlier. Sales rose 5.6 percent to $1.4 billion
from $1.33 billion in the comparable period a year earlier.
   The nation's second-largest steelmaker said it charged $55
million against the first quarter as the cost of reorganizing its
troubled Baltimore Marine Division. The division could be hurt
further by a strike that was begun March 17 by members of the
International Association of Machinists, Bethlehem said.
   The 1988 first quarter results included a charge of $19 million
over a coal mine fire and employee benefits and a $10 million
credit as an investment tax credit refund.
   Shipments increased 2 percent from 2.6 million tons to 2.7
million tons. Production declined 1 percent to 3.2 million tons as
the company operated at 82 percent of capacity, only 1 percentage
point below the 1988 first quarter.
   Chairman Walter F. Williams said he expects shipments to remain
about the same at least through the second quarter. He said second
half industry shipments will decline from levels of the first half.
   Bethlehem's future financial performance will be affected by its
contract negotiations with the United Steelworkers and by the
extent to which the Bush administration's renews steel import
quotas due to expire in September, Williams said.
</TEXT>
