<FIRST>u f BC-Earns-Media 1stLd-Writethru f0140 04-25 0626</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Media, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0140,0645</SECOND>
<HEAD>Profits Off at Times Mirror, Washington Post in Absence of One-Time
Gains</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Tops with 1 new graf to include Knight-Ridder. Adds 6 grafs
with Knight Ridder details.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Times Mirror Co. and Washington Post Co. said Tuesday their
first-quarter earnings fell from the levels of last year, when they
had one-time gains on asset sales. Another media company,
Knight-Ridder Inc., also reported a decline in its first-quarter
profit.
   Times Mirror, owner of the Los Angeles Times, Newsday and other
papers, said it earned $68.8 million, or 53 cents a share, in the
first quarter, down 8 percent from $75.1 million, or 58 cents a
share, a year earlier.
   First-quarter sales rose 9.3 percent to $846.9 million from
$774.6 million a year earlier.
   The Times Mirror results for the first quarter of 1988 included
an after-tax gain of $15.3 million from sale of timberland and of
Times-Mirror Press. If that gain were excluded, this year's profit
would have risen 15 percent, the Los Angles-based media concern
said.
   Newspaper publishing revenue, hurt in recent months by soft
demand for advertising, rose 11 percent in the quarter because of
higher advertising volume, cost-cutting and the fact the accounting
period was five days longer than last year's. Advertising
performance improved at the Los Angeles Times and Baltimore Sun
papers, but continued slow in New York.
   Revenue rose 9 percent for book, magazine and other publishing
and 17 percent for cable television. Broadcast TV revenue declined
less than 1 percent.
   In addition to the Times, Newsday and the Baltimore Sun papers,
Times Mirror holdings include The Hartford Courant, The (Allentown,
Pa.) Morning Call, The (Stamford, Conn.) Advocate and Greenwich
(Conn.) Time; KDFW-TV in Dallas and other publishing, broadcast and
cable TV operations.
   Washington Post, which owns the Washington Post newspaper and
Newsweek magazine and has interests in TV stations and cable
television, said its earnings tumbled 71 percent to $41.5 million,
or $3.22 a share, in the first quarter from $144.8 million, or
$11.25 a share, a year earlier.
   First-quarter revenue rose 6.5 percent to $341.9 million from
$321.2 million a year earlier.
   The 1988 results had included a non-recurring gain of $115.7
million from the sale of cellular telephone interests.
   Excluding that gain, the company said its earnings would have
risen 42 percent from a year earlier.
   Newspaper division revenue rose 7 percent in the latest quarter
as advertising lineage at the Washington Post edged up 3 percent.
   Revenue from the company's four television stations rose 5
percent and cable division revenue rose 13 percent. Newsweek's
revenue rose 1 percent from a year ago.
   Miami-based Knight-Ridder said its profit fell 39.3 percent to
$20.5 million, or 39 cents a share, from $33.8 million, or 59 cents
a share, a year earlier.
   First-quarter revenue rose 10.4 percent to $540.7 million from
$489.7 million a year earlier.
   Robert F. Singleton, senior vice president and chief financial
officer, said, ``This was a difficult quarter, but the results were
just about what we expected when we set our 1989 budget.''
   He said more than half of the decline was due to acquisitions,
including the purchase of Dialog Information Services and an
investment in a cable operation, while the rest reflected
``softness in operations and higher interest rates.''
   He said he expected growth in earnings per share for the year,
partly because of softening newsprint prices, stronger operating
results from the newspaper division and growth in business
information services.
   He said the company also expects to benefit from lower interest
costs as the result of the previously-disclosed agreements to sell
its eight television stations and two newspapers.
   Knight-Ridder owns 30 newspapers, offers a variety of electronic
business information services and has interests in cable television.
</TEXT>
