<FIRST>r f AM-Sprint-Refund     04-25 0255</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sprint-Refund,0267</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thousands to Receive Refund on Overcharge</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LAS VEGAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   US Sprint Communications Co. plans to give
refunds to thousands of customers in Las Vegas after one man
complained he was overcharged $60 by the long-distance telephone
company.
   Sprint officials have acknowledged that thousands of their
22,000 Las Vegas customers were overcharged from April through
August of 1988 because computers recorded the wrong time of day for
the phone calls. The mistake also affected credit-card customers
dialing from Las Vegas.
   Sprint officials declined to estimate how much the refunds would
be.
   The refunds were prompted by Lenny Frome, a Las Vegas resident
who complained about a billing error to the company last year.
   Frome, a retired aerospace engineer who teaches mathematics at
the University of Nevada-Las Vegas, figured the company owed him
about $60 in overcharges. When he felt the company was delaying in
resolving the issue, Frome took his complaint to former Sen. Chic
Hecht, R-Nev., who passed it along to the Federal Communications
Commission.
   Michael Furtney, a vice president of corporate relations for
Sprint, said Tuesday the company was correcting the situation when
the FCC notified Sprint about the complaint.
   Furtney defended any delays in dealing with Frome, saying
erroneous charges are ``hard to find in a company that's generating
billions of dollars in revenues.''
   ``It's like looking for a needle in a haystack,'' he said.
   Furtney said the company plans to identify all overcharged
customers within two weeks. He said customers should receive
refunds within a month after that.
</TEXT>
