<FILEID>AP-NR-04-25-89 2017EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-DuPont-Waste     04-25 0210</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Du Pont-Waste,0221</SECOND>
<HEAD>Du Pont, Waste Management Form Plastics Recycling Venture</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Du Pont Co. and Waste Management Inc. said
Tuesday they had signed a letter of intent to form a joint plastics
recycling venture to help deal with the growing amount of solid
waste from the nation's municipalities.
   ``It's a unique venture. It brings together the two largest
companies in their respective fields,'' said Frank Aronhalt,
director of environmental affairs for Du Pont, based in Wilmington,
Del.
   The companies did not disclose the value of the deal.
   Aronhalt said a new plastics recycling plant will be built
somewhere in the Midwest or Southeast.
   ``We hope to have the first plant up and running by the early
1990s,'' he said.
   The first plant will have a recycling capacity of up to 40
million pounds annually, the companies said.
   Under the plan, old plastic will be collected and separated by
Waste Management then sent to be treated and upgraded into
materials that can be reused by various industries, including the
automotive and airline industries, Aronhalt said.
   ``From collection to recycling, we'll now have a closed loop,''
Aronhalt said.
   Waste Management, based in Oak Brook, Ill., collects waste from
more than 8 million residential and industrial customers.
</TEXT>
