<FILEID>AP-NR-04-25-89 2020EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-MillerAds     04-25 0307</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Miller Ads,0317</SECOND>
<HEAD>Miller Starts New Commercials To Boost High Life Sales</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MILWAUKEE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Attempting to reverse the decline in its
flagship High Life brand, Miller Brewing Co. unveiled new
commercials Tuesday promoting the beer as a reward for everyday
heros.
   The new High Life campaign, under the slogan, ``The best comes
shining through,'' is reminiscent of the Miller-time commercials of
the 1970s that touted beer as a reward for regular work.
   For example, one commercial in the new series extols a man who
helps a woman cross the street, and another salutes a farmer who
helps harvest corn for the widow of a friend. Others praise a man
in a wheelchair who is playing basketball and show a member of a
car-racing team warning a competitor of a mechanical problem with
his car, thereby possibly losing the race but doing the honorable
thing at the same time.
   ``These ads portray people who do the right thing,'' said Robert
Toledo, vice president of brand management and promotions for
Miller. And unlike the Miller time ads ``these celebrate basic
human values and elevate the man and the beer'' and not just a
regular job well-done.
   High Life sales fell to sixth place last year from third in 1987
among the top domestic brewers, according to statistics from
Beverage Media, a liquor industry publication.
   Beverage Media estimated 8.5 million barrels of High Life were
sold last year, down from 9.3 million in 1987.
   Moving past High Life in the rankings were Bud Light at 9.7
million barrels, Coors Light at 8.7 million barrels and Busch at
8.6 million, the publication said.
   The top sellers were Budweiser at 50.6 million barrels and
Miller Lite at 19.6 million barrels.
   The new ad campaign for Miller High Life was the first developed
for the brand by Leo Burnett USA, Chicago.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
