<FIRST>r f AM-BellLayoffs     04-25 0267</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bell Layoffs,0277</SECOND>
<HEAD>Up To 2,000 Bell Helicopter Employees May Lose Jobs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT WORTH, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Defense spending cuts proposed Tuesday
include axing funds for the new V-22 Osprey transport aircraft, a
move which could cost the jobs of up to 2,000 Bell Helicopter
Textron Inc., company officials said.
   The workers could face layoffs within 10 days, and another 500
jobs could be cut within a year, Bell officials said in a letter to
employees before the cuts were formally proposed.
   Defense Secretary Dick Cheney outlined $10 billion in Pentagon
cuts before a hearing of the House Armed Services Committee. Cheney
said the Marine Corps has been told to scrap development of the
V-22 aircraft, which is manufactured as a joint project by Bell and
Boeing Helicopter Co. of Philadelphia.
   The two companies are developing the tilt-rotor aircraft under a
$1.8 billion contract, scheduled to run through mid-1992.
   The Pentagon is required to cut future spending plans by $10
billion for the next fiscal year under a budget agreement the Bush
administration and Congress reached earlier this spring.
   The cuts also reportedly were to include cancellation of another
large Bell program, the OH-58D AHIP helicopter.
   Although the company had not been officially informed of the
cuts, Bell was required by federal plant-closing legislation to
notify employees of possible layoffs, spokesman Bob Leder said.
   Leder said Bell has not formulated specific layoff plans, but he
said a ``worst-case scenario'' might require Bell to lay off 1,800
to 2,000 workers within 10 days.
   A total of 2,500 workers could lose their jobs within a year, he
added.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
