<FIRST>r f BC-Kawasaki-Helicopter     04-25 0127</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Kawasaki-Helicopter,0134</SECOND>
<HEAD>Japanese Firm Chosen by McDonnel Douglas</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MESA, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Kawasaki Heavy Industries Ltd. has been
chosen to provide transmissions for the McDonnell Douglas MDX
commercial helicopter, the aircraft maker announced Tuesday.
   McDonnell Douglas said Kawasaki will provide 500 transmissions
through 1998 for the eight-place twin-engine helicopter, one
feature of which will be lack of a tail rotor.
   The transmissions will be assembled in Japan, then will be
shipped to Mesa for installation, though Kawasaki engineers will be
here during the preliminary design phase, the company said.
   Kawasaki has produced a McDonnell Douglas helicopter in Japan
under license since 1968. Its transmission was chosen from among
four competing designs.
   The MDX is expected to fly in 1992, with deliveries to begin the
following year.
</TEXT>
