<FIRST>u f AM-NUMMITruck     04-25 0146</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-NUMMI Truck,0151</SECOND>
<HEAD>Toyota-GM Joint Venture to Build Truck</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A new pickup truck will be assembled beginning in
the spring of 1991 by the New United Motor Manufacturing Inc. joint
venture in California and will be sold through Toyota dealers,
officials said Tuesday.
   The joint venture between General Motors Corp. and Toyota Motor
Corp. agreed on the project Monday. The project will add 700 new
jobs to the 2,700 workers now at the plant, NUMMI said in a
statement released in Detroit.
   NUMMI also will invest more than $200 million in its Fremont,
Calif., plant, which currently builds Toyota Corolla sedans and
Chevrolet Geo Prizms.
   NUMMI spokeswoman Sharon Sarris said the two-wheel drive truck,
with a 2.4-liter engine, will replace a truck Toyota currently
markets in the United States. The new truck will be made for the
U.S. market only, she added.
</TEXT>
