<FIRST>r f AM-Kuhn-Shearson     04-25 0275</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Kuhn-Shearson,0286</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shearson Accuses Law Firm of Billing for Work Not Performed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Myerson &amp; Kuhn, the law firm co-headed by former
baseball commissioner Bowie Kuhn, has been accused of billing
Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc. approximately $2 million for work that
Shearson says the law firm did not perform.
   Michael O'Neill, a spokesman for Shearson, confirmed Tuesday the
existence of an investigation into the matter, disclosed in
Monday's editions of The Wall Street Journal.
   ``There have been billing irregularities,'' O'Neill said. ``We
have have brought them to the attention of Myerson &amp; Kuhn and we
have ended the relationship.''
   The law firm denied the charges.
   Myerson &amp; Kuhn was formed in 1988 and is headed by Kuhn and
Harvey Myerson.
   Shearson, which had been a client of Myerson's former law firm,
retained Myerson &amp; Kuhn for about $12 million annually, a financial
industry source said Tuesday. The Journal, quoting unidentified
sources, said the amount of overbilling was about $2 million.
   In addition, Myerson &amp; Kuhn said the Appellate Division of New
York State Supreme Court was looking into the matter after
receiving a complaint from Shearson. The Appellate Division, which
investigates allegations of misconduct, informed Myerson &amp; Kuhn at
the end of last week that it had 20 days to respond to the charges,
the spokesman said.
   ``There has never been a basis for a claim of overbilling,''
Myerson &amp; Kuhn said Tuesday in a statement. ``The orchestrated
public attack upon us, rather than an effort to present a claim in
a decent a businesslike way, is itself compelling evidence that
some agenda outside a good-faith dispute has motivated these
attacks.''
</TEXT>
