<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-Whirlpool     04-25 0246</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Whirlpool,0339</SECOND>
<HEAD>Philips Appliance Interest Boosts Whirlpool Earnings</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BENTON HARBOR, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Whirlpool Corp.'s purchase of a
share of the appliance business of N.V. Philips boosted Whirlpool's
first-quarter earnings, the company said Tuesday.
   Whirlpool became the world's largest appliance concern in
January when it agreed to buy a 53 percent interest in the
appliance division of the Dutch company, forming a venture called
Whirlpool International.
   At Whirlpool's annual meeting Tuesday in Chicago, shareholders
elected Gerrit Jeelof, a Philips vice president and chairman of
North American Philips Corp., as a Whirlpool director.
   The Whirlpool board named Wilhemus G. Maeyer, president and
chief executive officer of Whirlpool International, as executive
vice president at Whirlpool.
   Whirlpool reported profit of $40.7 million, or 59 cents a share,
for the first quarter, up from $37.1 million, or 54 cents a share,
in the first quarter of 1988.
   Revenues for the quarter were $1.6 billion, up from $1.1 billion
in the comparable 1988 period, the company said.
   Chairman David R. Whitwam said inflation will tend to increase
materials costs during the rest of the year, however.
   European appliance sales are expected to increase 1 percent to 3
percent this year, but a U.S. economic slowdown could reduce
domestic sales 2 percent to 5 percent, he said.
   The board also elected Whitwam as president in addition to his
posts as chairman and chief executive officer. Former president
Albert E. Suter resigned April 4, saying he wanted to pursue other
business opportunities.
</TEXT>
