<FIRST>u f AM-Dunkin'Donuts 1stLd-Writethru f0302 04-25 0457</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dunkin' Donuts, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0302,0468</SECOND>
<HEAD>Canadian Group Seeks Federal Approval To Take Over Dunkin' Donuts</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 7th graf, `Kingsbridge Capital ...,' to CORRECT that asset
figure is given in Canadian dollars, sted American.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN COOPERMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An investment group controlled by Canadian real
estate mogul George Mann applied Tuesday for permission from
federal regulators to acquire more than 50 percent of Dunkin'
Donuts Inc.
   Kingsbridge Capital Group said in the filing with the Federal
Trade Commission that it has already bought 7.6 percent of the
stock in the doughnut maker, which owns or franchises more than
1,780 shops.
   Kingsbridge announced April 20 that it had acquired 6.6 percent
of Dunkin' Donuts and might seek control over the Randolph,
Mass.-based company, which reported earnings of $13.5 million on
sales of $112.8 million last year.
   The group still has not decided whether to launch a takeover
bid, spokesman Eric W. Evans said Tuesday.
   ``What we're seeking is approval to acquire up to 100 percent
(of Dunkin' Donuts), but that doesn't mean we're going to do it,''
he said.
   Dunkin' Donuts Vice President Richard N. Hart Jr. said it would
vigorously resist any takeover attempt.
   Kingsbridge Capital Group is a Toronto-based merchant bank owned
by Unicorp Canada Corp., the 15th largest company in Canada with
assets of 5.9 billion Canadian dollars. Unicorp is controlled by
Mann, its chairman, who owns about 25 percent of its total stock
and 68 percent of its voting shares.
   Under U.S. antitrust laws, investors must apply for permission
to buy more than $15 million or 15 percent of the stock in large,
publicly held companies.
   Kingsbridge's purchases so far total just under $15 million, and
Evans said the group would like to exceed that figure. But he said
there is ``no current intention to acquire more than 15 percent''
of Dunkin' Donuts, the threshhold that would trigger anti-takeover
defenses.
   Dunkin' Donuts moved quickly after last week's announcement to
shore up those defenses, setting up both a ``poison pill''
shareholder rights plan and an employee stock ownership plan.
   The poison pill would give stockholders an automatic right to
purchase additional shares in the event of a takeover,
significantly boosting the cost to the buyer.
   The ESOP would put 1.1 million shares, or about 16.7 percent of
the total outstanding, into the hands of workers. Hart said Dunkin'
Donuts has begun buying back an equal number of its shares,
purchasing 300,000 so far this year.
   In addition, Hart said, Dunkin' Donuts laid off 80 of its 560
employees last Friday as part of a continuing reorganization that
began before the Kingsbridge announcement. People who work in the
stores are employees of the individual franchise owners, not the
company.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890425-0316 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-25-89 2226EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-FaultyPacemakers     04-25 0323</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Faulty Pacemakers,0336</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Approves Settlement Against Company That Made Faulty Pacemakers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD COLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge on Tuesday approved a $764,000
settlement of criminal charges against the Cordis Corp. after the
Miami-based company pleaded guilty to selling faulty pacemakers
from 1983 to 1985.
   Last October, U.S. District Judge Stanley Marcus refused to
accept fines and court costs totaling $264,000, saying the amount
was ``not commensurate with the crime charged.''
   But on Tuesday, he agreed to the new plea bargain after
prosecutors added a $500,000 count.
   Four former Cordis officers are set to go on trial here in
September on an indictment in the case, but the case Tuesday
involved the company itself, which was charged separately with 12
felony and 13 misdemeanor counts. The company sold the pacemaker
division in 1987.
   Last month in Washington, Cordis also agreed to pay $5 million
in civil penalties levied by the Veterans Administration and the
U.S. Health and Human Services Department.
   ``As far as the company is concerned, the issue is behind us,''
Cordis spokesman Chick McDowell said after Tuesday's hearing.
   Cordis was accused of selling 2,200 defective pacemakers and
6,000 batteries prone to corrosion from December 1983 to October
1985.
   The U.S. Food and Drug Administration said the pacemakers could
have stopped without warning, although no deaths were attributed to
failure of the devices, which are implanted under the skin to
regulate the heartbeat. The charges said company officials knew of
the problems but sold the pacemakers anyway.
   Cordis sold its pacemaker business to the Australian medical
device manufacturer Telectronics. Cordis now concentrates on making
catheters for diagnosing and treating heart problems and gauges for
monitoring pressure on the brain.
   The company reported a loss of $56.1 million in 1987, but a
major restructuring after the sale of the pacemaker operation
brought the company a profit in 1988 of $2.4 million on sales of
$132 million.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
