<SECOND>BC-United-Order,0190</SECOND>
<HEAD>Report: United Airlines To Order 190 Boeing Jets</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   United Airlines plans to announce Wednesday that
it is ordering 190 narrow-body jets worth $7.5 billion from Boeing
Co., according to a published report.
   United, a subsidiary of UAL Corp. of Chicago, said Tuesday it
would hold a news conference in Chicago on Wednesday to make an
important announcement, but it declined to disclose its purpose.
   The New York Times, quoting industry sources, reported in
Wednesday's editions that the airline would announce it was buying
90 Boeing 757s to be delivered starting in August 1989, and 100
Boeing 737s, of which 35 are firm orders and the rest options.
   The carrier's management said previously that it intended to
place a significant jet order.
   Julius Maldutis, an airline analyst for Solomon Brothers Inc.,
said the order was designed to counter recent major jet orders by
American Airlines and Delta Air Lines.
   He added that he expected United to place another order in the
summer for wide-body aircraft such as the Boeing 747 or the
McDonnell Douglas Corp. MD-11.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
